ry:Cornish-language surnames]]\n\n[[de:Knowles]]\n[[fr:Knowles]]\n[[pt:Knowles]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:9920:eba3:383a:aedc:15a1:a02a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Corrected misinformation)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knowles_(surname)"}
{"title_page": "Ott (record producer)", "text_new": "{{short description|British record producer and musician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name        = Ott\n| image        = \n| caption       = \n| image_size     = \n| background     = solo_singer\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1968|5|12}}\n| alias        = Hikikomori, Umberloid\n| origin       = London, England\n| genre        = [[Electronica]], [[Dub music|dub]], [[Ambient music|ambient]], [[trip hop]], [[ethnic electronica]], [[livetronica]]\n| years_active    = 2002\u2013present\n| label        = [[Twisted Records (UK)]]\n| associated_acts   = [[Shpongle]], [[The Orb]]\n| website         = [http://www.ottsonic.net/ www.ottsonic.net]    \n}}\nOtto '''\"Ott\" ''' Langrell (born <!--Grover Smith  (unsure cit. needed) --> 12 April 1968 in [[London]], England) is a British record producer and musician who has worked with [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]], [[Embrace (English band)|Embrace]], [[The Orb]], and [[Brian Eno]], and has achieved recognition since 2002 for his own psychedelic dub tracks and his collaborations with [[Simon Posford]] ([[Hallucinogen (musician)|Hallucinogen]] / [[Shpongle]]).<ref>http://www.discogs.com/artist/Ott</ref> He has released two albums on [[Twisted Records (UK)|Twisted Records]]: ''[[Blumenkraft]]'' (2003), ''[[Skylon (album)|Skylon]]'' (2008) and two albums on [[Ottsonic]]: ''[[Mir (album)|Mir]]'' (2011) and ''[[Fairchildren (album)|Fairchildren]]'' (2015).\n\n==Career==\n\nSince the early 2000s, Ott has produced, mixed and recorded music released on [[Twisted Records (UK)|Twisted Records]], including various collaborations with founder [[Simon Posford]]. His first major contribution to Twisted was the record ''[[In Dub (Hallucinogen album)|Hallucinogen \u2013 In Dub]]'', on which he remixed six classic Hallucinogen songs.<ref>http://www.discogs.com/Hallucinogen-In-Dub/release/58836,</ref> In May 2003 he released his own album, ''[[Blumenkraft]]'', on Twisted;<ref>http://www.twistedmusic.com/artists/ott</ref> it was reviewed by ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-fY4AQAAIAAJ&q=ott+Blumenkraft&dq=ott+Blumenkraft&hl=en&ei=ew8YTq-9D4TzsgbGnMXBDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA, review], ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]''. Excerpt via [[Google books]]. Retrieved 14 July 2011</ref> His work has also been featured in releases from the record label Liquid Sound Design (now known as Liquid Sound, run by [[Martin Glover]]), especially those compilations produced by Humphrey Bacchus during his time at the label. He followed up his debut album in January 2008 with ''[[Skylon (album)|Skylon]]'', followed by ''[[Mir (album)|Mir]]'' in March 2011.<ref>http://www.ottsonic.net</ref>\n\nOtt performed at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] in 2007.<ref>http://music.guardian.co.uk/glastonbury2007/lineup/page/0,,2092462,00.html</ref> His performance at [[Glade Festival]] in 2011 was described as \"the perfect opening act\" in an article at ''[[Virtual Festivals]]''.<ref name=\"virtfest_kicks_off\">[http://www.virtualfestivals.com/latest/news/10553 Ott kicks off the next evolution of Glade Festival 2011]: Psychedelic Dub Producer Ott Sets The Tone for the Weekend. Joe Taylor, ''[[Virtual Festivals]]'', 10 June 2011. Retrieved July 2011.</ref> That publication also called Ott a \"[[Psydub|psy-dub]] [[maestro]]\" and gave his performance a full 10/10.<ref name=\"virtfest_maestro\">[http://www.virtualfestivals.com/festivals/reviews/10600 First Review: Glade Festival 2011]. Joe Taylor, ''[[Virtual Festivals]]'', 13 June 2011. Retrieved 14 July 2011. \"Psy-dub maestro Ott kick starts proceedings...\"</ref>\n\nHe has also contributed to several other records on Twisted as well as other labels.\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Studio ===\n* ''[[Blumenkraft]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Skylon (Album)|Skylon]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Mir (album)|Mir]]'' (2011)\n* ''Baby Robot EP'' (2013)\n* ''[[Fairchildren (album)|Fairchildren]]'' (2015)\n\n=== As engineer ===\n\n* ''[[Are You Shpongled?]]'' (Compiled and edited by Ott)\n* ''Eclipse \u2013 A Journey of Permanence & Impermanence'' (Compiled and edited by Ott and [[Simon Posford]])\n* ''[[In Dub (Hallucinogen album)|Hallucinogen \u2013 In Dub]]'' (Produced, programmed and mixed by Ott)\n* ''[[Nothing Lasts...But Nothing Is Lost]]'' (Engineered by Ott. He also plays [[timbales]] on tracks 3 and 5)\n* ''Hallucinogen in Dub Live''\n\n=== Other ===\n\n* ''Scilly Automatic'' (from ''Talisman'', [[Interchill Records]] CD015, 2002)\n* ''Ott Meets Billy The Kid'' (from ''Elucidations'' by Liquid Sound Design, 2002)\n* ''Evil Do'ers'' by Gargoyles [Ott and Simon Posford] (from ''Talisman'', Interchill Records] CD015, 2002)\n* ''Joyful Wonder'' (from ''Backroom Beats 2'', Twisted Records 2003)\n* ''Spacebaby (Seiberg & Witten Mix)'' by Gargoyles (from ''Backroom Beats 2'', Twisted Records 2003)\n* ''Neon Tetra'' by Umberloid (written and produced by Ott and Chris Barker; from ''13th Moon'', Interchill Records CD016, 2003)\n* ''Shpongle \u2013 The Remixes'' (Remix of ''Around The World in a Tea Daze'', 2003)\n* ''Tripswitch \u2013 Silver (Ott Remix)'' (from ''Wider Horizons'', by Liquid Sound Design, 2004)\n* ''Exit Chapel Perilous'' by Umberloid (written and produced by Ott and Chris Barker, from ''Soul vibration Vol. 1'' by Liquid Records, 2005)\n* ''[[Entheogenic (band)|Entheogenic]] \u2013 Dialogue of the Speakers'' (Remixes of ''Timeless E.S.P.'' and ''Ground Luminosity'', 2005)\n* ''Eye of the Beholder'' (written and produced by Ott and Colin Bennun; from ''Free Range'' by O.O.O.D., [[Organic Records]] ORGCD0012, 2006)\n* ''Bluetech \u2013 Prayer For Rain (Ott Remix)'' (from ''Natural Born Chillers 2'', Aleph Zero Records 2009)\n* ''Sound Tribe Sector 9 \u2013 The Spectacle (Ott Remix)'' (from ''STS9 \u2013 Peaceblaster: The New Orleans Make It Right Remixes'', 2009)\n* ''The Disco Biscuits \u2013 Konkrete (Ott Remix)'' (from ''The Disco Biscuits \u2013 Widgets EP'', 2009)\n* ''Terra Nine \u2013 No Return (Ott Remix)'' (from ''Terra Nine \u2013 Stream Of Consciousness'', 2009)\n* ''Hoopy Frood \u2013 Indigo'' (Produced by Ott, 2009)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Ott Ott at discogs.com]\n* [http://www.ottsonic.net Ott's official Website]\n* [http://www.twistedmusic.com/artists/ott Ott at Twisted Records]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:British record producers]]\n[[Category:Dub musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:British electronic musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British record producer and musician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name        = Ott\n| image        = \n| caption       = \n| image_size     = \n| background     = solo_singer\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1968|5|12}}\n| alias        = Hikikomori, Umberloid\n| origin       = London, England\n| genre        = [[Electronica]], [[Dub music|dub]], [[Ambient music|ambient]], [[trip hop]], [[ethnic electronica]], [[livetronica]]\n| years_active    = 2002\u2013present\n| label        = [[Twisted Records (UK)]]\n| associated_acts   = [[Shpongle]], [[The Orb]]\n| website         = [http://www.ottsonic.net/ www.ottsonic.net]    \n}}\n'''Ott''' (born <!--Grover Smith  (unsure cit. needed) --> 12 April 1968 in [[London]], England) is a British record producer and musician who has worked with [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]], [[Embrace (English band)|Embrace]], [[The Orb]], and [[Brian Eno]], and has achieved recognition since 2002 for his own psychedelic dub tracks and his collaborations with [[Simon Posford]] ([[Hallucinogen (musician)|Hallucinogen]] / [[Shpongle]]).<ref>http://www.discogs.com/artist/Ott</ref> He has released two albums on [[Twisted Records (UK)|Twisted Records]]: ''[[Blumenkraft]]'' (2003), ''[[Skylon (album)|Skylon]]'' (2008) and two albums on [[Ottsonic]]: ''[[Mir (album)|Mir]]'' (2011) and ''[[Fairchildren (album)|Fairchildren]]'' (2015).\n\n==Career==\n\nSince the early 2000s, Ott has produced, mixed and recorded music released on [[Twisted Records (UK)|Twisted Records]], including various collaborations with founder [[Simon Posford]]. His first major contribution to Twisted was the record ''[[In Dub (Hallucinogen album)|Hallucinogen \u2013 In Dub]]'', on which he remixed six classic Hallucinogen songs.<ref>http://www.discogs.com/Hallucinogen-In-Dub/release/58836,</ref> In May 2003 he released his own album, ''[[Blumenkraft]]'', on Twisted;<ref>http://www.twistedmusic.com/artists/ott</ref> it was reviewed by ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-fY4AQAAIAAJ&q=ott+Blumenkraft&dq=ott+Blumenkraft&hl=en&ei=ew8YTq-9D4TzsgbGnMXBDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA, review], ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]''. Excerpt via [[Google books]]. Retrieved 14 July 2011</ref> His work has also been featured in releases from the record label Liquid Sound Design (now known as Liquid Sound, run by [[Martin Glover]]), especially those compilations produced by Humphrey Bacchus during his time at the label. He followed up his debut album in January 2008 with ''[[Skylon (album)|Skylon]]'', followed by ''[[Mir (album)|Mir]]'' in March 2011.<ref>http://www.ottsonic.net</ref>\n\nOtt performed at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] in 2007.<ref>http://music.guardian.co.uk/glastonbury2007/lineup/page/0,,2092462,00.html</ref> His performance at [[Glade Festival]] in 2011 was described as \"the perfect opening act\" in an article at ''[[Virtual Festivals]]''.<ref name=\"virtfest_kicks_off\">[http://www.virtualfestivals.com/latest/news/10553 Ott kicks off the next evolution of Glade Festival 2011]: Psychedelic Dub Producer Ott Sets The Tone for the Weekend. Joe Taylor, ''[[Virtual Festivals]]'', 10 June 2011. Retrieved July 2011.</ref> That publication also called Ott a \"[[Psydub|psy-dub]] [[maestro]]\" and gave his performance a full 10/10.<ref name=\"virtfest_maestro\">[http://www.virtualfestivals.com/festivals/reviews/10600 First Review: Glade Festival 2011]. Joe Taylor, ''[[Virtual Festivals]]'', 13 June 2011. Retrieved 14 July 2011. \"Psy-dub maestro Ott kick starts proceedings...\"</ref>\n\nHe has also contributed to several other records on Twisted as well as other labels.\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Studio ===\n* ''[[Blumenkraft]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Skylon (Album)|Skylon]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Mir (album)|Mir]]'' (2011)\n* ''Baby Robot EP'' (2013)\n* ''[[Fairchildren (album)|Fairchildren]]'' (2015)\n\n=== As engineer ===\n\n* ''[[Are You Shpongled?]]'' (Compiled and edited by Ott)\n* ''Eclipse \u2013 A Journey of Permanence & Impermanence'' (Compiled and edited by Ott and [[Simon Posford]])\n* ''[[In Dub (Hallucinogen album)|Hallucinogen \u2013 In Dub]]'' (Produced, programmed and mixed by Ott)\n* ''[[Nothing Lasts...But Nothing Is Lost]]'' (Engineered by Ott. He also plays [[timbales]] on tracks 3 and 5)\n* ''Hallucinogen in Dub Live''\n\n=== Other ===\n\n* ''Scilly Automatic'' (from ''Talisman'', [[Interchill Records]] CD015, 2002)\n* ''Ott Meets Billy The Kid'' (from ''Elucidations'' by Liquid Sound Design, 2002)\n* ''Evil Do'ers'' by Gargoyles [Ott and Simon Posford] (from ''Talisman'', Interchill Records] CD015, 2002)\n* ''Joyful Wonder'' (from ''Backroom Beats 2'', Twisted Records 2003)\n* ''Spacebaby (Seiberg & Witten Mix)'' by Gargoyles (from ''Backroom Beats 2'', Twisted Records 2003)\n* ''Neon Tetra'' by Umberloid (written and produced by Ott and Chris Barker; from ''13th Moon'', Interchill Records CD016, 2003)\n* ''Shpongle \u2013 The Remixes'' (Remix of ''Around The World in a Tea Daze'', 2003)\n* ''Tripswitch \u2013 Silver (Ott Remix)'' (from ''Wider Horizons'', by Liquid Sound Design, 2004)\n* ''Exit Chapel Perilous'' by Umberloid (written and produced by Ott and Chris Barker, from ''Soul vibration Vol. 1'' by Liquid Records, 2005)\n* ''[[Entheogenic (band)|Entheogenic]] \u2013 Dialogue of the Speakers'' (Remixes of ''Timeless E.S.P.'' and ''Ground Luminosity'', 2005)\n* ''Eye of the Beholder'' (written and produced by Ott and Colin Bennun; from ''Free Range'' by O.O.O.D., [[Organic Records]] ORGCD0012, 2006)\n* ''Bluetech \u2013 Prayer For Rain (Ott Remix)'' (from ''Natural Born Chillers 2'', Aleph Zero Records 2009)\n* ''Sound Tribe Sector 9 \u2013 The Spectacle (Ott Remix)'' (from ''STS9 \u2013 Peaceblaster: The New Orleans Make It Right Remixes'', 2009)\n* ''The Disco Biscuits \u2013 Konkrete (Ott Remix)'' (from ''The Disco Biscuits \u2013 Widgets EP'', 2009)\n* ''Terra Nine \u2013 No Return (Ott Remix)'' (from ''Terra Nine \u2013 Stream Of Consciousness'', 2009)\n* ''Hoopy Frood \u2013 Indigo'' (Produced by Ott, 2009)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.discogs.com/artist/Ott Ott at discogs.com]\n* [http://www.ottsonic.net Ott's official Website]\n* [http://www.twistedmusic.com/artists/ott Ott at Twisted Records]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:British record producers]]\n[[Category:Dub musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:British electronic musicians]]\n", "name_user": "195.147.237.179", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ott_(record_producer)"}
{"title_page": "1988 U.S. Figure Skating Championships", "text_new": "{{Infobox Figure Skating Competition\n| title = 1988 United States Figure Skating Championships\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| comptype = National Championship\n| startdate = January 4\n| enddate = 10\n| skatingseason = 1987\u201388\n| location = [[Denver, Colorado]]\n| host = \n| venue = \n| prizemoney = \n| defendladies = \n| defenddance = \n| championmen = [[Brian Boitano]]\n| championladies = [[Debi Thomas]]\n| championpairs = [[Jill Watson]] / [[Peter Oppegard]]\n| championdance = [[Suzanne Semanick]] / [[Scott Gregory (ice skater)|Scott Gregory]]\n| previouscomp = [[1987 United States Figure Skating Championships|1987 U.S. Championships]]\n| nextcomp = [[1989 United States Figure Skating Championships|1989 U.S. Championships]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1988 [[United States Figure Skating Championships]]''' was an event organized by [[U.S. Figure Skating]] to determine the U.S. national champions. The event was one of the criteria used to select the U.S. teams for the [[Figure skating at the 1988 Winter Olympics|1988 Winter Olympics]],<ref name=nyt880106/> as well as the [[1988 World Figure Skating Championships|1988 World Championships]]. Medals were awarded in four colors: gold (first), silver (second), bronze (third), and pewter (fourth) in four disciplines \u2013 [[single skating|men's singles, ladies' singles]], [[pair skating]], and [[ice dancing]] \u2013 across three levels: senior, junior, and novice. The 1988 Championships took place between January 4 and 10, 1988 in [[Denver, Colorado]].\n\n==Senior-level results==\n\n===Men===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Rank\n! Name\n! CF\n! SP\n! FS\n|- bgcolor=\"gold\"\n| align=\"center\" | '''1'''\n| [[Brian Boitano]] ||1||1||1\n|- bgcolor=\"silver\"\n| align=\"center\" | '''2'''\n| [[Paul Wylie]] ||3||3||2\n|- bgcolor=\"cc9966\"\n| align=\"center\" | '''3'''\n| [[Christopher Bowman]] ||2||2||\n|- bgcolor=\"#d1c571\"\n| align=\"center\" | 