abeth Punsalan]] / [[Shawn Rettstatt]]\n|- bgcolor=\"silver\"\n| align=\"center\" | '''2'''\n| \n|- bgcolor=\"cc9966\"\n| align=\"center\" | '''3'''\n| \n|- bgcolor=\"#d1c571\"\n| align=\"center\" | '''4'''\n| \n|-\n! ...\n| \n|-\n! 13\n| [[Julie Benz]] / [[David Schilling]]\n|-\n! ...\n| \n|}\n\n==Novice-level results==\n\n===Men===\nChris Browne 1st \u201cGold medal\u201d\nMichael Chack 2nd\nTom Incantalupo 3rd\n\n===Ladies===\n\n===Pairs===\n\n===Ice dancing===\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=nyt880106>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/06/sports/skaters-have-no-more-time-to-dream.html?pagewanted=print&src=pm | title = Skaters Have No More Time to Dream | first = Michael | last = Janofsky | work = The New York Times | date = January 6, 1988}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.resultscorner.com/Event.aspx?EventID=999 ladies' results]{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071011105350/http://www.pairsonice.net/compview.php?c=19880104 pairs' results]\n\n{{US Nationals Figure skating}}\n\n[[Category:U.S. Figure Skating Championships]]\n[[Category:1988 in figure skating|United States Figure Skating Championships, 1988]]\n[[Category:1988 in American sports|United States Figure Skating Championships, 1988]]\n[[Category:1988 in sports in Colorado|U.S. Figure]]\n[[Category:January 1988 sports events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Abbileigh", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1988_U.S._Figure_Skating_Championships"}
{"title_page": "Worshipful Company of Clockmakers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox Livery Company\n| name        = Worshipful Company of Clockmakers\n| image       = Clockmakers Company Coat of Arms.jpg\n| caption     = Arms of the Clockmakers' Company, granted in January 1672. Blazon: ''Sable, a Clock ye Four Pillars thereof Erected on Four Lyons, and on Each Capital a Globe with a Cross, and in the Middest an Imperiall Crowne all Or, and for their Crest upon an Helmet Proper Mantled Gules Doubled Argent and Wreath of their Colours a Spheare Or, the Armes Supported by the Figures of a Naked Old Man Holding a Scithe and an Hour Glasse Representing Time, and of an Emperour in Roabes Crowned Holding a Scepter.''\n| motto       = ''Tempus Rerum Imperator''\n| location    = 1 Throgmorton Avenue, London EC2N 2BY\n| formation   = {{start date|df=yes|1631}}\n| association = Horology\n| precedence  = 61st\n| master      = Joanna Migdal (Lady White)\n| website     = {{url|clockmakers.org}}\n}}\n{{short description|Livery company of the City of London}}\nThe '''Worshipful Company of Clockmakers''' was established under a [[Royal Charter]] granted by [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] in 1631.<ref>https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/royal-charters/list-of-charters-granted/</ref> It ranks sixty-first among the [[livery companies]] of the City of London, and comes under the jurisdiction of the [[Privy Council]]. The company established a library and its [[Clockmakers' Museum|Museum]] in 1813, which is the oldest specific collection of clocks and watches worldwide.<ref>https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/see-and-do/clockmakers-museum</ref> This is administered by the company's affiliated charity, the Clockmakers\u2019 Charity,<ref>Charity No. 275380 registered with the UK Charity Commission</ref> and is presently housed on the second floor of London's [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]]. The modern aims of the company and its Museum are charitable and educational, in particular to promote and preserve clockmaking and watchmaking, which as of 2019 were added to the [[HCA Red List of Endangered Crafts]].\n\n==Museum==\nThe [[Clockmakers' Museum|Clockmakers\u2019 Museum]], first established in 1813, was housed at London's [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall]] from 1874 to 2014. The collection of clocks and watches was moved to a new gallery provided by the Science Museum, officially opened by HRH [[Princess Anne]] on 22 October 2015. The company's archive and library are however still kept at [[Guildhall Library]]. The collection includes [[John Harrison|John Harrison's]] sea watch H5, once personally tested by [[King George III]].\n\n==Motto==\nThe company's motto, ''Tempus Rerum Imperator'', can be translated as \u2018Time, the Ruler of All Things\u2019. It appears as an epitaph on the tombstone of former British Prime Minister [[Harold Wilson]], a liveryman of the company. It has also been adopted by the [[Google Web Accelerator]] project.\n\n==History==\nPrior to the seventeenth century, clockmaking by native English craftsmen was mostly confined to the production of [[turret clocks]]. Domestic clocks and watches were mostly imported or the work of immigrants from the Continent. Because turret clock making involved working in ferrous metal, clockmakers within the City of London tended to be freemen of the [[Worshipful Company of Blacksmiths|Blacksmiths\u2019 Company]], though some were members of other livery companies, notably the [[Worshipful Company of Clothworkers|Clothworkers]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=English Lantern Clocks|last=White|first=George|publisher=ACC|year=1989|location=|pages=51\u201354}}</ref>\n\nAfter the loss of many London clock and watchmakers in the plagues of 1598 and 1603, the trade consolidated and began to grow. The continued influx of newcomers led to resentment from those who had become established in London towards outsiders who came to set up in or near the City and who threatened their market. From 1620 onwards, groups of clockmakers attempted to set up their own guild. The Blacksmiths initially succeeded in opposing these moves. Eventually, however, with the King issuing charters as a means of raising much needed finance at a time when he had prorogued Parliament, the clockmakers succeeded in securing a Royal Charter, on 22 August 1631, to the distress of the Blacksmiths, who could naturally expect to lose members, and therefore income.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Clockmakers of London|last=White|first=George|publisher=WCC|year=2018|location=London|pages=14\u201319}}</ref>\n\nThe Charter gave regulatory authority to the Clockmakers to control the horological trade in the City of London and for a radius of ten miles around. It incorporated a controlling body which should have \u2018continuance for ever under the style and name of The Master, Wardens and Fellowship of the Art and Mystery of Clockmaking\u2019. It provided that the Fellowship should be governed by a Master, three Wardens and ten or more Assistants who would form the Court. The first Master was [[David Ramsay (watchmaker)|David Ramsay]], a Scot, who had been appointed watchmaker to [[James VI of Scotland]], later James I of England. The noted clockmaker [[Edward East (clockmaker)|Edward East]] also formed part of the first Court.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Some Account of the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers|last=Atkins|first=Samuel|publisher=|year=1881|location=London|pages=8}}</ref>\n\nThe original Charter is still in the company's possession and is housed with the rest of its library and archive in the Guildhall Library.<ref>See the catalogue of the London Metropolitan Archive, reference CLC/L/CD</ref>\nThe company obtained a [[grant of arms]] from the [[College of Arms]] in January 1672. In 1766, the [[Court of Aldermen]] granted the Company its livery. The number of Liverymen was originally limited at sixty but has been increased in number over the years by approval of the [[City of London Corporation]] and currently stands at a maximum of three hundred.<ref>http://www.clockmakers.org/history-customs/freedom-and-livery/</ref>\n\n==Horological Training and Awards for Excellence==\nThe company bestows three awards for excellence: the Tompion Medal for outstanding achievements in horology, the Harrison Medal for the propagation of horological knowledge and its appreciation, and the Derek Pratt Prize for innovation, ingenuity, elegance, and the highest standards of workmanship and precision performance in the craft and science of time and timekeeping.\nThe company also closely co-operates with the trustees of the [[George Daniels (watchmaker)|George Daniels]] Educational Trust in supporting education in horology.\n\n==Affiliations==\nThe Clockmakers Company is formally affiliated with the [[Antiquarian Horological Society]], the [[UCL Observatory]], [[HMS Protector (A173)|HMS ''Protector'']], the Royal Navy's Ice Patrol Ship.<ref>http://www.clockmakers.org/about/affiliations/</ref> and [[HMS Archer|HMS ''Archer'']], a P264 Class University Royal Naval Unit based in Edinburgh.\n\n==Masters==\n[[File:Reverend Henry Leonard Nelthropp.jpg|thumb|The Reverend Henry Leonard Nelthropp MA FSA, Master of the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers of the City of London 1893 and 1894.]]\n[[File:City of London, unusually arranged clock - geograph.org.uk - 559842.jpg|thumb|The [[Newgate|Newgate Street]] clock, the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers' 375th anniversary gift to the City of London.]]\nThose who have been Master of the company include the following:<ref>[http://www.clockmakers.org/about/the-court-committees-panels/masters-since-1631/ Masters since 1631], The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers website, accessed 06/02/2011</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1631, [[David Ramsay (watchmaker)|David Ramsay]]\n*1636, [[Elias Allen]]\n*1645, 1652 [[Edward East (clockmaker)|Edward East]]\n*1700, [[Charles Gretton]]<ref>[Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. Vancouver, Canada: Three O'clock Publishing. {{ISBN|978-0-9940460-0-0}}. https://www.grettonbook.com</ref>\n*1702, [[Joseph Windmills]]\n*1703, [[Thomas Tompion]]\n*1708, [[Daniel Quare]]\n*1717 Nathaniel Chamberlain \n*1718, [[Joseph Windmills|Thomas Windmills]]\n*1817, [[John Roger Arnold]]\n*1821, 1823, 1825, 1827, 1847 [[Benjamin Lewis Vulliamy]]\n*1855, 1862 [[Charles Frodsham]]\n*1893, 1894 Revd. Henry Leonard Nelthropp\n*1902, 1914 [[William Henry Mahoney Christie]] KCB FRS\n*1922, 1931 Sir [[Frank Watson Dyson]] KBE FRS FRSE\n*1926, [[Hugh Rotherham]]\n*1946, [[Edward Iliffe, 1st Baron Iliffe|Lord Iliffe of Yattendon]] GBE\n*1949, 1954 Sir [[Harold Spencer Jones]] KBE FRS FRSE PRAS\n*1950, [[William Hamilton Shortt]] FBHI\n*1959, [[Viscount Falmouth]]\n*1960, [[Baron Harris|Lord Harris]]\n*1969, Sir [[Richard van der Riet Woolley]] OBE FRS\n*1974, Sir [[Frank Chalton Francis]] KCB\n*1976, Sir [[Hugh Wontner]] GBE CVO\n*1980, [[George Daniels (watchmaker)|George Daniels]] CBE DSc FBHI FSA AHCI\n*1986, [[Viscount Falmouth]]\n*1989, [[Lord Murton of Lindisfarne]] OBE TD PC\n*2000, [[Alexander Boksenberg]] CBE FRS\n*2001, Sir George White, Bt, FSA\n*2002, Michael Monro Smith\n*2003, Christopher John Hurrion\n*2004, Philip John Willoughby\n*2005, Diana Muriel Uff\n*2006, [[David Pennefather|Maj Gen David Anthony Somerset Pennefather CB OBE]]\n*2007, David John Poole FBHI\n*2008, Dr Michael David Sanderson PhD\n*2009, Cdr Peter John Linstead-Smith OBE RN\n*2010, Howard Carl Newman FBHI\n*2011, Andrew Charles Henry Crisford FSA\n*2012, Mark Westcombe Elliott FCA\n*2013, Prof Paul Eugene Marcus Jarrett FRCS\n*2014, [[Jonathan Betts|Jonathan Daniel Betts MBE FSA FBHI]]\n*2015, Philip William Tennant Whyte, Hon FBHI\n*2016, Robert Michael Justice Stewart\n*2017, Roy Charles Harris, FBHI\n*2018, Andrew Lewis James, FRSA, Hon MBHI\n*2019, Jonathan Edward Hills\n*2020, Joanna Migdal (Lady White)\n{{colend}}\n{{Expand list|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Company Chaplains and Church==\n* Reverend Hugh Bearn <ref>http://liverydatabase.liverycompanies.info/networks/553/index.html</ref>\n* [[St James Garlickhythe]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px>\nFile:Wenceslas Hollar - Elias Allen.jpg|[[Elias Allen]]\nFile:Thomas Tompion00.jpg|[[Thomas Tompion]]\nFile:John Arnold.jpg|[[John Arnold (watchmaker)|John Arnold]]\nFile:Charles Frodsham.gif|[[Charles Frodsham]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[British Horological Institute]]\n*[[Clockmakers' Museum]]\n*[[Antiquarian Horological Society]]\n*[[Charles Gretton]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.grettonbook.com/home The Gretton Project]: Research endeavour and book (''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking'', published 2016) about clockmaker and watchmaker [[Charles Gretton]], who was Master of the Clockmakers' Company in 1700. The book contains a substantial historical introduction as well as historical appendices, providing considerable information about the Company in the late 17th and early 18th centuries.\n*[http://www.clockmakers.org/ The Clockmakers' Company]\n\n{{Livery Companies in the City of London}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Worshipful Company Of Clockmakers}}\n[[Category:Livery companies|Clockmakers]]\n[[Category:Horology]]\n[[Category:1631 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Time in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Horological organizations]]\n[[Category:Clocks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox Livery Company\n| name        = Worshipful Company of Clockmakers\n| image       = Clockmakers Company Coat of Arms.jpg\n| caption     = Arms of the Clockmakers' Company, granted in January 1672. Blazon: ''Sable, a Clock ye Four Pillars thereof Erected on Four Lyons, and on Each Capital a Globe with a Cross, and in the Middest an Imperiall Crowne all Or, and for their Crest upon an Helmet Proper Mantled Gules Doubled Argent and Wreath of their Colours a Spheare Or, the Armes Supported by the Figures of a Naked Old Man Holding a Scithe and an Hour Glasse Representing Time, and of an Emperour in Roabes Crowned Holding a Scepter.''\n| motto       = ''Tempus Rerum Imperator''\n| location    = 1 Throgmorton Avenue, London EC2N 2BY\n| formation   = {{start date|df=yes|1631}}\n| association = Horology\n| precedence  = 61st\n| master      = Joanna Migdal (Lady White)\n| website     = {{url|clockmakers.org}}\n}}\n{{short description|Livery company of the City of London}}\nThe '''Worshipful Company of Clockmakers''' was established under a [[Royal Charter]] granted by [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] in 1631.<ref>https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/royal-charters/list-of-charters-granted/</ref> It ranks sixty-first among the [[livery companies]] of the City of London, and comes under the jurisdiction of the [[Privy Council]]. The company established a library and its [[Clockmakers' Museum|Museum]] in 1813, which is the oldest specific collection of clocks and watches worldwide.<ref>https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/see-and-do/clockmakers-museum</ref> This is administered by the company's affiliated charity, the Clockmakers\u2019 Charity,<ref>Charity No. 275380 registered with the UK Charity Commission</ref> and is presently housed on the second floor of London's [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]]. The modern aims of the company and its Museum are charitable and educational, in particular to promote and preserve clockmaking and watchmaking, which as of 2019 were added to the [[HCA Red List of Endangered Crafts]].\n\n==Museum==\nThe [[Clockmakers' Museum|Clockmakers\u2019 Museum]], first established in 1813, was housed at London's [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall]] from 1874 to 2014. The collection of clocks and watches was moved to a new gallery provided by the Science Museum, officially opened by HRH [[Princess Anne]] on 22 October 2015. The company's archive and library are however still kept at [[Guildhall Library]]. The collection includes [[John Harrison|John Harrison's]] sea watch H5, once personally tested by [[King George III]].\n\n==Motto==\nThe company's motto, ''Tempus Rerum Imperator'', can be translated as \u2018Time, the Ruler of All Things\u2019. It appears as an epitaph on the tombstone of former British Prime Minister [[Harold Wilson]], a liveryman of the company. It has also been adopted by the [[Google Web Accelerator]] project.\n\n==History==\nPrior to the seventeenth century, clockmaking by native English craftsmen was mostly confined to the production of [[turret clocks]]. Domestic clocks and watches were mostly imported or the work of immigrants from the Continent. Because turret clock making involved working in ferrous metal, clockmakers within the City of London tended to be freemen of the [[Worshipful Company of Blacksmiths|Blacksmiths\u2019 Company]], though some were members of other livery companies, notably the [[Worshipful Company of Clothworkers|Clothworkers]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=English Lantern Clocks|last=White|first=George|publisher=ACC|year=1989|location=|pages=51\u201354}}</ref>\n\nAfter the loss of many London clock and watchmakers in the plagues of 1598 and 1603, the trade consolidated and began to grow. The continued influx of newcomers led to resentment from those who had become established in London towards outsiders who came to set up in or near the City and who threatened their market. From 1620 onwards, groups of clockmakers attempted to set up their own guild. The Blacksmiths initially succeeded in opposing these moves. Eventually, however, with the King issuing charters as a means of raising much needed finance at a time when he had prorogued Parliament, the clockmakers succeeded in securing a Royal Charter, on 22 August 1631, to the distress of the Blacksmiths, who could naturally expect to lose members, and therefore income.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Clockmakers of London|last=White|first=George|publisher=WCC|year=2018|location=London|pages=14\u201319}}</ref>\n\nThe Charter gave regulatory authority to the Clockmakers to control the horological trade in the City of London and for a radius of ten miles around. It incorporated a controlling body which should have \u2018continuance for ever under the style and name of The Master, Wardens and Fellowship of the Art and Mystery of Clockmaking\u2019. It provided that the Fellowship should be governed by a Master, three Wardens and ten or more Assistants who would form the Court. The first Master was [[David Ramsay (watchmaker)|David Ramsay]], a Scot, who had been appointed watchmaker to [[James VI of Scotland]], later James I of England. The noted clockmaker [[Edward East (clockmaker)|Edward East]] also formed part of the first Court.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Some Account of the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers|last=Atkins|first=Samuel|publisher=|year=1881|location=London|pages=8}}</ref>\n\nThe original Charter is still in the company's possession and is housed with the rest of its library and archive in the Guildhall Library.<ref>See the catalogue of the London Metropolitan Archive, reference CLC/L/CD</ref>\nThe company obtained a [[grant of arms]] from the [[College of Arms]] in January 1672. In 1766, the [[Court of Aldermen]] granted the Company its livery. The number of Liverymen was originally limited at sixty but has been increased in number over the years by approval of the [[City of London Corporation]] and currently stands at a maximum of three hundred.<ref>http://www.clockmakers.org/history-customs/freedom-and-livery/</ref>\n\n==Horological Training and Awards for Excellence==\nThe company bestows three awards for excellence: the Tompion Medal for outstanding achievements in horology, the Harrison Medal for the propagation of horological knowledge and its appreciation, and the Derek Pratt Prize for innovation, ingenuity, elegance, and the highest standards of workmanship and precision performance in the craft and science of time and timekeeping.\nThe company also closely co-operates with the trustees of the [[George Daniels (watchmaker)|George Daniels]] Educational Trust in supporting education in horology.\n\n==Affiliations==\nThe Clockmakers Company is formally affiliated with the [[Antiquarian Horological Society]], the [[UCL Observatory]], [[HMS Protector (A173)|HMS ''Protector'']], the Royal Navy's Ice Patrol Ship.<ref>http://www.clockmakers.org/about/affiliations/</ref> and [[HMS Archer|HMS ''Archer'']], a P264 Class University Royal Naval Unit based in Edinburgh.\n\n==Masters==\n[[File:Reverend Henry Leonard Nelthropp.jpg|thumb|The Reverend Henry Leonard Nelthropp MA FSA, Master of the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers of the City of London 1893 and 1894.]]\n[[File:City of London, unusually arranged clock - geograph.org.uk - 559842.jpg|thumb|The [[Newgate|Newgate Street]] clock, the Worshipful Company of Clockmakers' 375th anniversary gift to the City of London.]]\nThose who have been Master of the company include the following:<ref>[http://www.clockmakers.org/about/the-court-committees-panels/masters-since-1631/ Masters since 1631], The Worshipful Company of Clockmakers website, accessed 06/02/2011</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*1631, [[David Ramsay (watchmaker)|David Ramsay]]\n*1636, [[Elias Allen]]\n*1645, 1652 [[Edward East (clockmaker)|Edward East]]\n*1700, [[Charles Gretton]]<ref>[Radage, Dennis, Meinen, Warner, and Radage, Laila. (2016). ''Charles Gretton: Clock & Watchmaking Through The Golden Age''. Vancouver, Canada: Three O'clock Publishing. {{ISBN|978-0-9940460-0-0}}. https://www.grettonbook.com</ref>\n*1702, [[Joseph Windmills]]\n*1703, [[Thomas Tompion]]\n*1708, [[Daniel Quare]]\n*1717 Nathaniel Chamberlain \n*1718, [[Joseph Windmills|Thomas Windmills]]\n*1817, [[John Roger Arnold]]\n*1821, 1823, 1825, 1827, 1847 [[Benjamin Lewis Vulliamy]]\n*1855, 1862 [[Charles Frodsham]]\n*1893, 1894 Revd. Henry Leonard Nelthropp\n*1902, 1914 [[William Henry Mahoney Christie]] KCB FRS\n*1922, 1931 Sir [[Frank Watson Dyson]] KBE FRS FRSE\n*1926, [[Hugh Rotherham]]\n*1946, [[Edward Iliffe, 1st Baron Iliffe|Lord Iliffe of Yattendon]] GBE\n*1949, 1954 Sir [[Harold Spencer Jones]] KBE FRS FRSE PRAS\n*1950, [[William Hamilton Shortt]] FBHI\n*1959, [[Viscount Falmouth]]\n*1960, [[Baron Harris|Lord Harris]]\n*1969, Sir [[Richard van der Riet Woolley]] OBE FRS\n*1974, Sir [[Frank Chalton Francis]] KCB\n*1976, Sir [[Hugh Wontner]] GBE CVO\n*1980, [[George Daniels (watchmaker)|George Daniels]] CBE DSc FBHI FSA AHCI\n*1986, [[Viscount Falmouth]]\n*1989, [[Lord Murton of Lindisfarne]] OBE TD PC\n*2000, [[Alexander Boksenberg]] CBE FRS\n*2001, Sir George White, Bt, FSA\n*2002, Michael Monro Smith\n*2003, Christopher John Hurrion\n*2004, Philip John Willoughby\n*2005, Diana Muriel Uff\n*2006, [[David Pennefather|Maj Gen David Anthony Somerset Pennefather CB OBE]]\n*2007, David John Poole FBHI\n*2008, Dr Michael David Sanderson PhD\n*2009, Cdr Peter John Linstead-Smith OBE RN\n*2010, Howard Carl Newman FBHI\n*2011, Andrew Charles Henry Crisford FSA\n*2012, Mark Westcombe Elliott FCA\n*2013, Prof Paul Eugene Marcus Jarrett FRCS\n*2014, [[Jonathan Betts|Jonathan Daniel Betts MBE FSA FBHI]]\n*2015, Philip William Tennant Whyte, Hon FBHI\n*2016, Robert Michael Justice Stewart\n*2017, Roy Charles Harris, FBHI\n*2018, Andrew Lewis James, FRSA, Hon MBHI\n*2019, Jonathan Edward Hills\n*2020, Joanna Migdal (Lady White)\n{{colend}}\n{{Expand list|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Company Chaplains and Church==\n* Reverend Hugh Bearn <ref>http://liverydatabase.liverycompanies.info/networks/553/index.html</ref>\n* [[St James Garlickhythe]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=160px>\nFile:Wenceslas Hollar - Elias Allen.jpg|[[Elias Allen]]\nFile:Thomas Tompion00.jpg|[[Thomas Tompion]]\nFile:John Arnold.jpg|[[John Arnold (watchmaker)|John Arnold]]\nFile:Charles Frodsham.gif|[[Charles Frodsham]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[British Horological Institute]]\n*[[Clockmakers' Museum]]\n*[[Antiquarian Horological Society]]\n*[[Charles Gretton]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.clockmakers.org/ The Clockmakers' Company]\n\n{{Livery Companies in the City of London}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Worshipful Company Of Clockmakers}}\n[[Category:Livery companies|Clockmakers]]\n[[Category:Horology]]\n[[Category:1631 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Time in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Horological organizations]]\n[[Category:Clocks]]\n", "name_user": "Dania.Sheldon", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(adjusted wording in one external link)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Worshipful_Company_of_Clockmakers"}
{"title_page": "Morden", "text_new": "{{about|the district of London}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name= Morden\n|static_image_name= Morden Hall Park 3.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Morden Hall\n|map_type= Greater London\n|coordinates= {{coord|51.4015|-0.1949|display=inline,title}}\n|population= 48,233\n|os_grid_reference= TQ255685\n|london_borough= Merton\n|region= London\n|country= England\n|post_town= MORDEN\n|postcode_area= SM\n|postcode_district= SM4\n|dial_code= 020\n|constituency_westminster= [[Wimbledon (UK Parliament constituency)|Wimbledon]]\n|constituency_westminster1= [[Mitcham and Morden (UK Parliament constituency)|Mitcham and Morden]]\n}}\n'''Morden''' is a district and town in south London, England, within the [[London Borough of Merton]]. It is around {{convert|8|mi|km|0}} [[Points of the compass|south-southwest]] of [[Charing Cross]]. Morden adjoins [[Merton Park]] and [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]] to the north, [[Mitcham, London|Mitcham]] to the east, [[Sutton, London|Sutton]] to the south and [[Worcester Park]] to the west. It is also famous as the homeplace of famous hula hoopers Katie Duck, Eira Evans and Karolina Caires.\n\nMorden had a population of 48,233 in 2011, including the wards of Cannon Hill, [[Lower Morden]], Merton Park, Ravensbury and St Helier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222202755/http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Origin of name ==\nMorden's name may be derived from the [[Common Brittonic]] words ''Mawr'' (great or large) and ''Dun'' (fort), or possibly \"The Town on the Moor\".\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early history ===\nHuman activity in Morden dates back to the [[Iron Age]] period when [[Celt]]ic tribes are known to have occupied areas around [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]], but the first significant development in Morden was the construction of the [[Roman road]] called [[Stane Street (Chichester)|Stane Street]] from [[Chichester]] to [[London]].\n\nThe route of [[Stane Street (Chichester)|Stane Street]] through Morden followed the current [[A24 road (Great Britain)|A24]], London Road up Stonecot Hill from the south west crossing [[Morden Park]] to the west of the current [[dual carriageway]] road and passing through the pitch and putt golf course and the grounds of [[St Lawrence Church, Morden|St Lawrence's Church]]. The road then descended the other side of the hill towards the town centre passing west of the [[Morden tube station|Underground station]] and crossing the north corner of [[Morden Hall Park]] heading in the direction of [[Colliers Wood]] and [[Tooting]]. Small [[Roman Britain|Roman]] [[artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]], mainly coins and pottery, have been found at various locations within the area although there is no evidence of any settlement.\n\nEthelstan the Etheling, son of [[Ethelred the Unready]], left \"land at Mordune\" to the [[abbey]] of Christ and St. Peter in his will of 1015, which became the site of the first [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxon]] parish church of [[St Lawrence]].\n\nIn 1086, the [[Domesday Book]] recorded the manor as ''Mordone'', part of [[Wallington (hundred)|Wallington]] [[Hundred (country subdivision)|Hundred]]. It was held by [[Westminster Abbey]] and its assets were: 3 [[hide (unit)|hides]]; 1 [[Mill (grinding)|mill]] worth \u00a32 and 7 [[plough]]s. It rendered \u00a315.<ref>[http://www.gwp.enta.net/surrnames.htm Surrey Domesday Book] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715015325/http://www.gwp.enta.net/surrnames.htm |date=15 July 2007 }}</ref> in total. Fourteen people were recorded as living in the area.\n\n=== The Garth family ===\n[[File:Morden hall park.jpg|thumb|Morden Hall Park now, where the Garth family lived]]\n[[File:Morden Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1298676.jpg|thumb|Morden Hall, home of the Garth family]]\nThe manor and village remained abbey property until the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] in [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]'s reign when the manor was sold to Lionel Ducket and Edward Whitchurch. Together, they sold it on the following year to Sir Richard Garth who became [[Lord of the Manor]].<ref name=BHO_1>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=43056&strquery=morden 'Parishes: Morden', A History of the County of Surrey: Volume 4 (1912), pp. 235-37.]</ref> The Garth family owned the land and maintained their connection with the parish for the next four centuries, living at [[Morden Hall Park]] until the manor was sold by another Sir [[Richard Garth]] in 1872.<ref name=BHO_1/>\n\nThe prominence of the Garth family is recorded locally in the name of Garth Road, [[Lower Morden]] and the former Garth School. The two lions included in the present civic [[heraldry|arms]] of the [[London Borough of Merton]] are adopted from the arms of Sir Richard.\n\n=== 19th century ===\n{| class=\"wikitable wiki table right\"\n|+'''Morden's Population'''<ref name = census>UK Census records</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:50%;\"|19th century|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:50%;\"|20th century\n|- \n|1801||style=\"text-align:right;\"|512||1901||style=\"text-align:right;\"|960\n|-   \n|1811||style=\"text-align:right;\"|549||1911||style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,202 \n|- \n|1821||style=\"text-align:right;\"|638||1921||style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,355 \n|- \n|1831||style=\"text-align:right;\"|655||1931||style=\"text-align:right;\"|12,618\n|-  \n|1841||style=\"text-align:right;\"|685||1941{{efn-lr|name=fn1}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|war\n|-  \n|1851||style=\"text-align:right;\"|628||1951||style=\"text-align:right;\"|35,417\n|-\n|1861||style=\"text-align:right;\"|654||1961{{efn-lr|name=fn2}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|68,011\n|-\n|1871||style=\"text-align:right;\"|787||1971{{efn-lr|name=fn2}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|62,872\n|- \n|1881||style=\"text-align:right;\"|694||1981{{efn-lr|name=fn2}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|61,108\n|- \n|1891||style=\"text-align:right;\"|763||1991{{efn-lr|name=fn3}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|n/a\n|-\n|}\n{{notelist-lr|refs=\n{{efn-lr|name=fn1|no census was held due to war}}\n{{efn-lr|name=fn2|includes Merton}}\n{{efn-lr|name=fn3|census data no longer relates to parish boundaries}}\n}}\nDespite the rapid [[suburban]] development of nearby [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]] occasioned by the arrival of the new railways constructed in the mid 19th century, Morden remained a rural parish throughout the 19th century. While the population of [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]] grew hugely from 1,591 in 1801 to 41,652 in 1901, the population of Morden was 512 in 1801 and, one hundred years later, had grown to just 960.<ref name = census>UK Census records</ref>\n\nIn 1871, the area of the parish of Morden was {{convert|1474.926|acre|km2|3}}<ref name = os_1871>[[Ordnance Survey]] map, 1871 edition</ref> with the small village clustered around [[St Lawrence Church, Morden|St Lawrence's church]] at the top of the hill on the road from London to [[Epsom]] (now London Road/Epsom Road). Approximately half a mile to the west of the main village and the grounds of [[Morden Park]] stood the hamlet of [[Lower Morden]].\n\nClose to the church were the George Inn, a 17th-century [[coaching inn]] (now modernised and part of a national pub restaurant chain), the estate of [[Morden Park]] and a school.\n\nThe other main public house in the village was the Crown Inn, located to the north east of the village with a small cluster of cottages on Crown Road. The rest of what is now the commercial centre of Morden was fields.\n\nIn the late 19th century the principal industry remained agriculture, although some industrial activity did exist along the [[River Wandle]] where [[watermill]]s ground tobacco to [[Snuff (tobacco)|snuff]] and a varnish works existed close to the site of Poplar Primary School. By 1898, the varnish works had gone and there was a [[brickworks]]<ref name = os_1898>Ordnance Survey map, 1898 edition</ref> on the site of Mostyn Gardens in Martin Way (then called Green Lane).<ref name = os_1898/>\n\n===20th century===\nUnder the [[Local Government Act 1894|Local Government Act, 1894]], the parish of Morden formed part of the [[Croydon Rural District]] of [[Surrey]]. The first two decades of the 20th century saw little change in the village, with industry still mainly agricultural in nature; however development in the parish of [[Merton (historic parish)|Merton]] to the north led to that area being removed from the [[rural district]] to form the [[Merton Urban District]] in 1907. Morden was merged with the Merton Urban District, in 1913, to form the [[Merton and Morden Urban District]].<ref name = vob>[http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_page.jsp?u_id=10036574 VisionofBritain.org.uk]</ref> It was not, until 1926, when [[Morden tube station|Morden Underground station]] opened as the terminus of a new extension of the [[City & South London Railway]] (now part of the [[London Underground]]'s [[Northern line]]), that the fast and direct route to Central [[London]] opened up the village for residential development.\n\nTo complement the new station, a garage was constructed on the other side of London Road, adjacent to the railway cutting and, in 1932, Morden Cinema was built next to it on the corner of Aberconway Road. Around the station a new commercial centre grew quickly as shops sprang up along London Road and Crown Lane, including a rebuilt and enlarged Crown public house (opened in 1932)<ref name=my_merton>[http://www.merton.gov.uk/my_merton_17_lr.pdf my merton, issue 17, June-July 2006, p. 17]</ref> and a large [[Royal Arsenal Co-operative Society]] (RACS) department store (opened in 1940).<ref name=my_merton/>\n\nAway from the new commercial centre of Morden, the existing rural roads were widened and rebuilt and the fields were rapidly divided into building plots and laid out for new housing.  Further transport improvements came with the construction of a new [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]] branch line [[Wimbledon and Sutton Railway|from Wimbledon to Sutton]] via stations at [[South Merton railway station|South Merton]] and [[Morden South railway station|Morden South]] (so named to differentiate it from [[Morden tube station|Morden Underground Station]] and [[Morden Road tram stop|Morden Station]] (now Morden Road tram stop), although it was actually north east of the original village centre). The new line opened in January 1930. As a result of the new transport links, the population of Morden increased rapidly from 1,355 in 1921 to 12,618 in 1931. In the next fifteen years, the population continued to grow, as most of the parish was covered in new [[suburban]] homes.\n\nOne of the main residential developments in the 1930s was the [[St. Helier, London|St. Helier]] estate, built by the [[London County Council]] (LCC) to house workers from Inner London and named in honour of Lady St. Helier, an [[alderman]] of the LCC. The estate was at the time the largest local authority development in South London and has its road names arranged in alphabetical order, from the north-west corner ([[Abbotsbury]] Road) to the south-east corner ([[Woburn Abbey|Woburn]] Road). Reflecting the previous ownership of the land by [[Westminster Abbey]], all are named after religious establishments. \n{| style=\"margin:auto;\"\n|-\n|[[File:Mordenmap 1920s.png|thumb|200px|A map of Morden from the 1920s]] || [[File:Morden map 1944.jpg|thumb|200px|A map of Morden from 1944]]\n|}\nIn 1943, the council was granted a civic [[coat-of-arms]] incorporating lions from the Garth family arms and the fret from the arms of [[Merton Priory]]. The motto, ''\"In Libertate Vis\"'', means ''\"Our Strength is our Freedom\"''. In 1965, under the [[London Government Act 1963]], the Merton and Morden Urban District Council was abolished and its area combined with that of the [[Municipal Borough of Wimbledon]] and the [[Municipal Borough of Mitcham]] to form the present-day London Borough of Merton.\n\n===Today===\n[[File:White Bridge, Morden Hall Park.jpg|thumb|Morden Hall Park, 5 minutes walk from the town centre.]]\n[[File:MordenHall.jpg|right|thumb|Morden Hall]]\n\nDespite London's suburban expansion, a little of the earlier rural nature of Morden has survived; for instance several grand period buildings remain, especially within Morden's parks.  The area retains a good provision of parks and green spaces, many of them created from former country estates. The 125 acre [[Morden Hall Park]] is of particular note and is run by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] (see below).  Its main entrance is only a quarter-of-a-mile from Morden Underground Station.\n\nThe largest building in the town centre is Crown House, sixties-built and 14 storeys tall; designed in 1959 by A. Green ARIBA and built between 1960 and 1962. The concaved frontage of the building lends it some distinction, as does the \"chessboard\" style juxtaposition of its light and dark facade features. It incorporated The Crown [[public house]], on which site part of the building covered. The building is home to Merton Council's civic centre and a large adjoining library.\n\nAt around the same time, Morden Underground Station, originally a single storey building, with shops, had three-storey office accommodation incorporated above it.\n\nA further office building with a large supermarket (now a [[Sainsbury's]]) at ground-floor level was built in the 1980s at the other end of the town centre.\n\nThe cinema and adjoining garage were demolished and replaced by shops some years ago.\n\n==Landmarks==\n\nMorden plays host to a number of buildings and parks worthy of note including:\n\n[[File:Baitul Futuh back.jpg|thumb|[[Baitul Futuh]] Mosque]]\n*The [[Baitul Futuh|Bait'ul Futuh]] Mosque, the largest mosque in Western Europe, built by the [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]]. Completed in 2003 at a cost of approximately \u00a35.5 million, the mosque covers an area of 5.2 acres (21,000 m2) and the full complex can accommodate up to 10,000 worshippers. It was voted one of the top 50 buildings in the world by ''[[Spectator Magazine]]''.{{cn|date=May 2018}} It is located  next to Morden South railway station and approximately 700 yards from Morden Underground station.\n*[[Morden Hall Park]] is a key feature of the Morden area with large, period buildings located within its boundaries. It is a [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] park, and is located on the banks of the [[River Wandle]], near the town centre and few hundred yards from Morden Underground station.  It covers over 50ha (125 acres) of parkland with the River Wandle meandering through it spanned by numerous foot-bridges. The estate contains a number of historic buildings including Morden Hall itself, Morden Cottage, an old Snuff Mill, and many old farm buildings, some of which are now a garden centre and a city farm. The rose garden has over 2000 roses. The estate land was originally owned by Westminster Abbey. There is evidence of an earlier manor-house, but Morden Hall dates back to the 1770s and contains a variety of natural landscapes, including the parkland of the \"Deer Park\", meadow and marshland.\n[[File:Morden Park House.JPG|thumb|right|Morden Park House]]\n*[[Morden Park]], another park containing a  period building of note. The park includes land that previously formed the grounds of Morden Park House, a small 18th-century country estate. The Georgian country house was built at the top of the hill in the 1770s for merchant and distiller John Ewart with attached landscaped gardens.\n[[File:St Lawrence Church, Morden-Geograph-4321087-by-Stephen-Craven.jpg|thumb|[[St Lawrence Church, Morden]]]]\n*[[St Lawrence Church, Morden]].  St Lawrence Church is the Church of England parish church for Morden.  The building is [[Grade I listed]],<ref>{{NHLE|num=1080899 |desc=|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref> and located on London Road, at the highest point of Morden, overlooking Morden Park. Located on the [[#The Garth family|Garth family]] estate,<ref>See the \"Ecclesiae Amicus\" (Latin for Friend of the Church) inscription on the gravestone of Richard Garth by the Communion table</ref> the current church was built in the 1630s in the [[Protestant]] style, and replaced an earlier wooden one from the Saxon period.\n*[[Morden Baptist Church]]. The Church stands with the main entrance facing up Crown Lane on the Morden one way system.  In 1990 a very substantial building scheme was undertaken to provide the current improved facilities, including an enclosed concourse, new offices and a sound-proofed creche with a view into the main church.\n\n==Sport & Leisure==\n\nMorden has a [[Non-League football]] club [[Tooting & Mitcham United F.C.]] who play at Imperial Fields.\n\n==Transport==\n\n[[File:ISH Morden2.jpg|thumb|Morden Underground station with Crown House in the background]]\n[[File:1960's Morden town centre..jpg|thumb|Morden in the 1960s]]\n[[File:Morden Underground Station.jpg|thumb|Morden Underground - main station entrance]]\n\nNearest tube station:\n\n* [[Morden tube station|Morden Underground station]]\n\nNearest railway stations and [[tramlink]] stops (in order of proximity):\n\n* [[Morden South railway station]]\n* [[Morden Road tram stop]]\n* [[South Merton railway station]]\n* [[St. Helier railway station]]\n* [[Phipps Bridge tram stop]]\n* [[Belgrave Walk tram stop]]\n* [[Mitcham tram stop]]\n\nLocal day and night Buses and the garages that serve Morden are:\n* 80 (Belmont High Down & Downview - Hackbridge Reynolds Close) - ''Go Ahead London - Sutton Garage''\n* 93 (Putney Bridge - North Cheam) (24 Hour) - ''Go Ahead London - Sutton Garage''\n* 118 (Morden Station - Brixton) - ''Go Ahead London - Merton Garage''\n* 154 (Morden Station - West Croydon Bus Station) - ''Go Ahead London - Sutton Garage''\n* 157 (Morden Station - Crystal Palace) - ''Arriva London - Thornton Heath Garage''\n* 163 (Wimbledon Station - Morden Station) - ''Go Ahead London - Merton Garage''\n* 164 (Wimbledon Station - Sutton Station) - ''Go Ahead London - Merton Garage''\n* 201 (Morden - Herne Hill) - ''Abellio London - Beddington Cross''\n* 293 (Morden Station - Epsom General Hospital) - ''RATP Quality Line - Epsom Garage''\n* 413 (Morden Tube Station - Sutton Bus Garage) - ''RATP Quality Line - Epsom Garage''\n* 470 (Epsom Town Centre - Colliers Wood Tube Station) - ''RATP Quality Line - Epsom Garage''\n* K5 (Morden - Ham) - ''RATP Quality Line - Epsom Garage''\n* N155 (Morden Station - Aldwych) - ''London General - Sutton Garage''\n\n==Notable people associated with Morden==\n*Admiral [[Mariot Arbuthnot]]<ref>[http://www.motco.com/map/81001 Motco.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060614013352/http://www.motco.com/MAP/81001/ |date=14 June 2006 }} [http://www.motco.com/MapImages/81001/81001034-w.jpg 15 Miles Round London (First edition), J Cary, 1786, Morden] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928085842/http://www.motco.com/MapImages/81001/81001034-w.jpg |date=28 September 2006 }}</ref> - Commander of the [[Royal Navy]] in North America during the [[American War of Independence]].\n*Sir [[Joseph Bazalgette]] - Engineer of [[London sewerage system|London's sanitary system]], the [[Chelsea Embankment|Chelsea]] and [[Victoria Embankment]]s lived in the village for a few years in the 1870s.\n*Sir [[Richard Garth]] - Lord of the Manor, [[Privy Counsellor]] and Chief Justice of Bengal\n*[[Alexander Maconochie (penal reformer)|Alexander Maconochie]] - Founder of the [[Royal Geographical Society]] and penal reformer.\n*[[Good Shoes]] - an [[indie music]] band whose first album, ''[[Think Before You Speak]]'', included the track \"[[Morden (Good Shoes song)|Morden]]\"\n*[[Sampha]] - a [[singer-songwriter]] best known for his collaborative work with [[SBTRKT]], [[Jessie Ware]] and [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]].\n\n==Nearest places==\n* [[Colliers Wood]]\n* [[Hackbridge]]\n* [[Merton Park]]\n* [[Mitcham, London, England|Mitcham]]\n* [[Lower Morden]]\n* [[Motspur Park]]\n* [[Raynes Park]]\n* [[St. Helier, London|St. Helier]]\n* [[South Wimbledon]]\n* [[Sutton, London|Sutton]]\n* [[Sutton Common]]\n* [[Wimbledon, London, England|Wimbledon]]\n* [[Worcester Park]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Morden baptist church.gif|[[Morden Baptist Church]], Crown Lane\nFile:Bridge at Morden Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1230196.jpg|Bridge at Morden Hall Park\nFile:Morden Hall Park 1.jpg|Morden Hall Park\nFile:Stable Block at Morden Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1230210.jpg|Stable Block at Morden Hall Park.\nFile:The Rose Garden, Morden Hall Park - geograph.org.uk - 1348687.jpg|The Rose Garden, Morden Hall Park\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|London}}\n{{Commons cat|Morden, London|Morden}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120209012036/http://www.collectbritain.co.uk/personalisation/object.cfm?uid=003KTOP00000041U009E0000&largeimage=1#largeimage British Library Collect Britain archive - Mordon, Surrey, 1780]\n* {{ltmcollection|28/i0000d28.jpg|London Transport Museum Photographic Archive}} Aerial view of Morden town centre in 1926 when the Underground station opened. The first roads have been laid out but the area is still mostly fields. The Crown Inn is visible on the left.\n* [http://www.britishpathe.com/product_display.php?canisternumber=UN+79+C&sortnumber=&filmid=&szin=&group=&decade=&date1=&date2=&date3=&datefrom=&dateto=&choice=all&description=Enter+search+word%28s%29+here&searchword=&choice1=all&title=Enter+a+film+title+here&choice2=all&keywords=Enter+key+words+here&choice3=all&summary=Enter+a+summary+search+here&advanced.x=25&advanced.y=25 British Pathe News Archive] 1930s Newsreel footage of construction of Morden Cinema (download - select low resolution free preview)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060614013352/http://www.motco.com/MAP/81001/ Motco.com] [https://web.archive.org/web/20060928085842/http://www.motco.com/MapImages/81001/81001034-w.jpg 15 Miles Round London (First edition), J Cary, 1786, Morden]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929121905/http://mysite.wanadoo-members.co.uk/cavalcade/morden.jpg Odeon Cavalcade - Morden Cinema, 1960s]\n\n{{LB Merton}}\n{{London Districts}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Merton]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the district of London}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name= Morden\n|static_image_name= Morden Hall Park 3.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Morden Hall\n|map_type= Greater London\n|coordinates= {{coord|51.4015|-0.1949|display=inline,title}}\n|population= 48,233\n|os_grid_reference= TQ255685\n|london_borough= Merton\n|region= London\n|country= England\n|post_town= MORDEN\n|postcode_area= SM\n|postcode_district= SM4\n|dial_code= 020\n|constituency_westminster= [[Wimbledon (UK Parliament constituency)|Wimbledon]]\n|constituency_westminster1= [[Mitcham and Morden (UK Parliament constituency)|Mitcham and Morden]]\n}}\n'''Morden''' is a district and town in south London, England, within the [[London Borough of Merton]]. It is around {{convert|8|mi|km|0}} [[Points of the compass|south-southwest]] of [[Charing Cross]]. Morden adjoins [[Merton Park]] and [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]] to the north, [[Mitcham, London|Mitcham]] to the east, [[Sutton, London|Sutton]] to the south and [[Worcester Park]] to the west. \n\nMorden had a population of 48,233 in 2011, including the wards of Cannon Hill, [[Lower Morden]], Merton Park, Ravensbury and St Helier.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222202755/http://data.london.gov.uk/2011-census-ward-pop |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Origin of name ==\nMorden's name may be derived from the [[Common Brittonic]] words ''Mawr'' (great or large) and ''Dun'' (fort), or possibly \"The Town on the Moor\".\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early history ===\nHuman activity in Morden dates back to the [[Iron Age]] period when [[Celt]]ic tribes are known to have occupied areas around [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]], but the first significant development in Morden was the construction of the [[Roman road]] called [[Stane Street (Chichester)|Stane Street]] from [[Chichester]] to [[London]].\n\nThe route of [[Stane Street (Chichester)|Stane Street]] through Morden followed the current [[A24 road (Great Britain)|A24]], London Road up Stonecot Hill from the south west crossing [[Morden Park]] to the west of the current [[dual carriageway]] road and passing through the pitch and putt golf course and the grounds of [[St Lawrence Church, Morden|St Lawrence's Church]]. The road then descended the other side of the hill towards the town centre passing west of the [[Morden tube station|Underground station]] and crossing the north corner of [[Morden Hall Park]] heading in the direction of [[Colliers Wood]] and [[Tooting]]. Small [[Roman Britain|Roman]] [[artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]], mainly coins and pottery, have been found at various locations within the area although there is no evidence of any settlement.\n\nEthelstan the Etheling, son of [[Ethelred the Unready]], left \"land at Mordune\" to the [[abbey]] of Christ and St. Peter in his will of 1015, which became the site of the first [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxon]] parish church of [[St Lawrence]].\n\nIn 1086, the [[Domesday Book]] recorded the manor as ''Mordone'', part of [[Wallington (hundred)|Wallington]] [[Hundred (country subdivision)|Hundred]]. It was held by [[Westminster Abbey]] and its assets were: 3 [[hide (unit)|hides]]; 1 [[Mill (grinding)|mill]] worth \u00a32 and 7 [[plough]]s. It rendered \u00a315.<ref>[http://www.gwp.enta.net/surrnames.htm Surrey Domesday Book] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715015325/http://www.gwp.enta.net/surrnames.htm |date=15 July 2007 }}</ref> in total. Fourteen people were recorded as living in the area.\n\n=== The Garth family ===\n[[File:Morden hall park.jpg|thumb|Morden Hall Park now, where the Garth family lived]]\n[[File:Morden Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1298676.jpg|thumb|Morden Hall, home of the Garth family]]\nThe manor and village remained abbey property until the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] in [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]'s reign when the manor was sold to Lionel Ducket and Edward Whitchurch. Together, they sold it on the following year to Sir Richard Garth who became [[Lord of the Manor]].<ref name=BHO_1>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=43056&strquery=morden 'Parishes: Morden', A History of the County of Surrey: Volume 4 (1912), pp. 235-37.]</ref> The Garth family owned the land and maintained their connection with the parish for the next four centuries, living at [[Morden Hall Park]] until the manor was sold by another Sir [[Richard Garth]] in 1872.<ref name=BHO_1/>\n\nThe prominence of the Garth family is recorded locally in the name of Garth Road, [[Lower Morden]] and the former Garth School. The two lions included in the present civic [[heraldry|arms]] of the [[London Borough of Merton]] are adopted from the arms of Sir Richard.\n\n=== 19th century ===\n{| class=\"wikitable wiki table right\"\n|+'''Morden's Population'''<ref name = census>UK Census records</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:50%;\"|19th century|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:50%;\"|20th century\n|- \n|1801||style=\"text-align:right;\"|512||1901||style=\"text-align:right;\"|960\n|-   \n|1811||style=\"text-align:right;\"|549||1911||style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,202 \n|- \n|1821||style=\"text-align:right;\"|638||1921||style=\"text-align:right;\"|1,355 \n|- \n|1831||style=\"text-align:right;\"|655||1931||style=\"text-align:right;\"|12,618\n|-  \n|1841||style=\"text-align:right;\"|685||1941{{efn-lr|name=fn1}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|war\n|-  \n|1851||style=\"text-align:right;\"|628||1951||style=\"text-align:right;\"|35,417\n|-\n|1861||style=\"text-align:right;\"|654||1961{{efn-lr|name=fn2}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|68,011\n|-\n|1871||style=\"text-align:right;\"|787||1971{{efn-lr|name=fn2}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|62,872\n|- \n|1881||style=\"text-align:right;\"|694||1981{{efn-lr|name=fn2}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|61,108\n|- \n|1891||style=\"text-align:right;\"|763||1991{{efn-lr|name=fn3}}||style=\"text-align:right;\"|n/a\n|-\n|}\n{{notelist-lr|refs=\n{{efn-lr|name=fn1|no census was held due to war}}\n{{efn-lr|name=fn2|includes Merton}}\n{{efn-lr|name=fn3|census data no longer relates to parish boundaries}}\n}}\nDespite the rapid [[suburban]] development of nearby [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]] occasioned by the arrival of the new railways constructed in the mid 19th century, Morden remained a rural parish throughout the 19th century. While the population of [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]] grew hugely from 1,591 in 1801 to 41,652 in 1901, the population of Morden was 512 in 1801 and, one hundred years later, had grown to just 960.<ref name = census>UK Census records</ref>\n\nIn 1871, the area of the parish of Morden was {{convert|1474.926|acre|km2|3}}<ref name = os_1871>[[Ordnance Survey]] map, 1871 edition</ref> with the small village clustered around [[St Lawrence Church, Morden|St Lawrence's church]] at the top of the hill on the road from London to [[Epsom]] (now London Road/Epsom Road). Approximately half a mile to the west of the main village and the grounds of [[Morden Park]] stood the hamlet of [[Lower Morden]].\n\nClose to the church were the George Inn, a 17th-century [[coaching inn]] (now modernised and part of a national pub restaurant chain), the estate of [[Morden Park]] and a school.\n\nThe other main public house in the village was the Crown Inn, located to the north east of the village with a small cluster of cottages on Crown Road. The rest of what is now the commercial centre of Morden was fields.\n\nIn the late 19th century the principal industry remained agriculture, although some industrial activity did exist along the [[River Wandle]] where [[watermill]]s ground tobacco to [[Snuff (tobacco)|snuff]] and a varnish works existed close to the site of Poplar Primary School. By 1898, the varnish works had gone and there was a [[brickworks]]<ref name = os_1898>Ordnance Survey map, 1898 edition</ref> on the site of Mostyn Gardens in Martin Way (then called Green Lane).<ref name = os_1898/>\n\n===20th century===\nUnder the [[Local Government Act 1894|Local Government Act, 1894]], the parish of Morden formed part of the [[Croydon Rural District]] of [[Surrey]]. The first two decades of the 20th century saw little change in the village, with industry still mainly agricultural in nature; however development in the parish of [[Merton (historic parish)|Merton]] to the north led to that area being removed from the [[rural district]] to form the [[Merton Urban District]] in 1907. Morden was merged with the Merton Urban District, in 1913, to form the [[Merton and Morden Urban District]].<ref name = vob>[http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_page.jsp?u_id=10036574 VisionofBritain.org.uk]</ref> It was not, until 1926, when [[Morden tube station|Morden Underground station]] opened as the terminus of a new extension of the [[City & South London Railway]] (now part of the [[London Underground]]'s [[Northern line]]), that the fast and direct route to Central [[London]] opened up the village for residential development.\n\nTo complement the new station, a garage was constructed on the other side of London Road, adjacent to the railway cutting and, in 1932, Morden Cinema was built next to it on the corner of Aberconway Road. Around the station a new commercial centre grew quickly as shops sprang up along London Road and Crown Lane, including a rebuilt and enlarged Crown public house (opened in 1932)<ref name=my_merton>[http://www.merton.gov.uk/my_merton_17_lr.pdf my merton, issue 17, June-July 2006, p. 17]</ref> and a large [[Royal Arsenal Co-operative Society]] (RACS) department store (opened in 1940).<ref name=my_merton/>\n\nAway from the new commercial centre of Morden, the existing rural roads were widened and rebuilt and the fields were rapidly divided into building plots and laid out for new housing.  Further transport improvements came with the construction of a new [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]] branch line [[Wimbledon and Sutton Railway|from Wimbledon to Sutton]] via stations at [[South Merton railway station|South Merton]] and [[Morden South railway station|Morden South]] (so named to differentiate it from [[Morden tube station|Morden Underground Station]] and [[Morden Road tram stop|Morden Station]] (now Morden Road tram stop), although it was actually north east of the original village centre). The new line opened in January 1930. As a result of the new transport links, the population of Morden increased rapidly from 1,355 in 1921 to 12,618 in 1931. In the next fifteen years, the population continued to grow, as most of the parish was covered in new [[suburban]] homes.\n\nOne of the main residential developments in the 1930s was the [[St. Helier, London|St. Helier]] estate, built by the [[London County Council]] (LCC) to house workers from Inner London and named in honour of Lady St. Helier, an [[alderman]] of the LCC. The estate was at the time the largest local authority development in South London and has its road names arranged in alphabetical order, from the north-west corner ([[Abbotsbury]] Road) to the south-east corner ([[Woburn Abbey|Woburn]] Road). Reflecting the previous ownership of the land by [[Westminster Abbey]], all are named after religious establishments. \n{| style=\"margin:auto;\"\n|-\n|[[File:Mordenmap 1920s.png|thumb|200px|A map of Morden from the 1920s]] || [[File:Morden map 1944.jpg|thumb|200px|A map of Morden from 1944]]\n|}\nIn 1943, the council was granted a civic [[coat-of-arms]] incorporating lions from the Garth family arms and the fret from the arms of [[Merton Priory]]. The motto, ''\"In Libertate Vis\"'', means ''\"Our Strength is our Freedom\"''. In 1965, under the [[London Government Act 1963]], the Merton and Morden Urban District Council was abolished and its area combined with that of the [[Municipal Borough of Wimbledon]] and the [[Municipal Borough of Mitcham]] to form the present-day London Borough of Merton.\n\n===Today===\n[[File:White Bridge, Morden Hall Park.jpg|thumb|Morden Hall Park, 5 minutes walk from the town centre.]]\n[[File:MordenHall.jpg|right|thumb|Morden Hall]]\n\nDespite London's suburban expansion, a little of the earlier rural nature of Morden has survived; for instance several grand period buildings remain, especially within Morden's parks.  The area retains a good provision of parks and green spaces, many of them created from former country estates. The 125 acre [[Morden Hall Park]] is of particular note and is run by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] (see below).  Its main entrance is only a quarter-of-a-mile from Morden Underground Station.\n\nThe largest building in the town centre is Crown House, sixties-built and 14 storeys tall; designed in 1959 by A. Green ARIBA and built between 1960 and 1962. The concaved frontage of the building lends it some distinction, as does the \"chessboard\" style juxtaposition of its light and dark facade features. It incorporated The Crown [[public house]], on which site part of the building covered. The building is home to Merton Council's civic centre and a large adjoining library.\n\nAt around the same time, Morden Underground Station, originally a single storey building, with shops, had three-storey office accommodation incorporated above it.\n\nA further office building with a large supermarket (now a [[Sainsbury's]]) at ground-floor level was built in the 1980s at the other end of the town centre.\n\nThe cinema and adjoining garage were demolished and replaced by shops some years ago.\n\n==Landmarks==\n\nMorden plays host to a number of buildings and parks worthy of note including:\n\n[[File:Baitul Futuh back.jpg|thumb|[[Baitul Futuh]] Mosque]]\n*The [[Baitul Futuh|Bait'ul Futuh]] Mosque, the largest mosque in Western Europe, built by the [[Ahmadiyya Muslim Community]]. Completed in 2003 at a cost of approximately \u00a35.5 million, the mosque covers an area of 5.2 acres (21,000 m2) and the full complex can accommodate up to 10,000 worshippers. It was voted one of the top 50 buildings in the world by ''[[Spectator Magazine]]''.{{cn|date=May 2018}} It is located  next to Morden South railway station and approximately 700 yards from Morden Underground station.\n*[[Morden Hall Park]] is a key feature of the Morden area with large, period buildings located within its boundaries. It is a [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] park, and is located on the banks of the [[River Wandle]], near the town centre and few hundred yards from Morden Underground station.  It covers over 50ha (125 acres) of parkland with the River Wandle meandering through it spanned by numerous foot-bridges. The estate contains a number of historic buildings including Morden Hall itself, Morden Cottage, an old Snuff Mill, and many old farm buildings, some of which are now a garden centre and a city farm. The rose garden has over 2000 roses. The estate land was originally owned by Westminster Abbey. There is evidence of an earlier manor-house, but Morden Hall dates back to the 1770s and contains a variety of natural landscapes, including the parkland of the \"Deer Park\", meadow and marshland.\n[[File:Morden Park House.JPG|thumb|right|Morden Park House]]\n*[[Morden Park]], another park containing a  period building of note. The park includes land that previously formed the grounds of Morden Park House, a small 18th-century country estate. The Georgian country house was built at the top of the hill in the 1770s for merchant and distiller John Ewart with attached landscaped gardens.\n[[File:St Lawrence Church, Morden-Geograph-4321087-by-Stephen-Craven.jpg|thumb|[[St Lawrence Church, Morden]]]]\n*[[St Lawrence Church, Morden]].  St Lawrence Church is the Church of England parish church for Morden.  The building is [[Grade I listed]],<ref>{{NHLE|num=1080899 |desc=|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref> and located on London Road, at the highest point of Morden, overlooking Morden Park. Located on the [[#The Garth family|Garth family]] estate,<ref>See the \"Ecclesiae Amicus\" (Latin for Friend of the Church) inscription on the gravestone of Richard Garth by the Communion table</ref> the current church was built in the 1630s in the [[Protestant]] style, and replaced an earlier wooden one from the Saxon period.\n*[[Morden Baptist Church]]. The Church stands with the main entrance facing up Crown Lane on the Morden one way system.  In 1990 a very substantial building scheme was undertaken to provide the current improved facilities, including an enclosed concourse, new offices and a sound-proofed creche with a view into the main church.\n\n==Sport & Leisure==\n\nMorden has a [[Non-League football]] club [[Tooting & Mitcham United F.C.]] who play at Imperial Fields.\n\n==Transport==\n\n[[File:ISH Morden2.jpg|thumb|Morden Underground station with Crown House in the background]]\n[[File:1960's Morden town centre..jpg|thumb|Morden in the 1960s]]\n[[File:Morden Underground Station.jpg|thumb|Morden Underground - main station entrance]]\n\nNearest tube station:\n\n* [[Morden tube station|Morden Underground station]]\n\nNearest railway stations and [[tramlink]] stops (in order of proximity):\n\n* [[Morden South railway station]]\n* [[Morden Road tram stop]]\n* [[South Merton railway station]]\n* [[St. Helier railway station]]\n* [[Phipps Bridge tram stop]]\n* [[Belgrave Walk tram stop]]\n* [[Mitcham tram stop]]\n\nLocal day and night Buses and the garages that serve Morden are:\n* 80 (Belmont High Down & Downview - Hackbridge Reynolds Close) - ''Go Ahead London - Sutton Garage''\n* 93 (Putney Bridge - North Cheam) (24 Hour) - ''Go Ahead London - Sutton Garage''\n* 118 (Morden Station - Brixton) - ''Go Ahead London - Merton Garage''\n* 154 (Morden Station - West Croydon Bus Station) - ''Go Ahead London - Sutton Garage''\n* 157 (Morden Station - Crystal Palace) - ''Arriva London - Thornton Heath Garage''\n* 163 (Wimbledon Station - Morden Station) - ''Go Ahead London - Merton Garage''\n* 164 (Wimbledon Station - Sutton Station) - ''Go Ahead London - Merton Garage''\n* 201 (Morden - Herne Hill) - ''Abellio London - Beddington Cross''\n* 293 (Morden Station - Epsom General Hospital) - ''RATP Quality Line - Epsom Garage''\n* 413 (Morden Tube Station - Sutton Bus Garage) - ''RATP Quality Line - Epsom Garage''\n* 470 (Epsom Town Centre - Colliers Wood Tube Station) - ''RATP Quality Line - Epsom Garage''\n* K5 (Morden - Ham) - ''RATP Quality Line - Epsom Garage''\n* N155 (Morden Station - Aldwych) - ''London General - Sutton Garage''\n\n==Notable people associated with Morden==\n*Admiral [[Mariot Arbuthnot]]<ref>[http://www.motco.com/map/81001 Motco.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060614013352/http://www.motco.com/MAP/81001/ |date=14 June 2006 }} [http://www.motco.com/MapImages/81001/81001034-w.jpg 15 Miles Round London (First edition), J Cary, 1786, Morden] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928085842/http://www.motco.com/MapImages/81001/81001034-w.jpg |date=28 September 2006 }}</ref> - Commander of the [[Royal Navy]] in North America during the [[American War of Independence]].\n*Sir [[Joseph Bazalgette]] - Engineer of [[London sewerage system|London's sanitary system]], the [[Chelsea Embankment|Chelsea]] and [[Victoria Embankment]]s lived in the village for a few years in the 1870s.\n*Sir [[Richard Garth]] - Lord of the Manor, [[Privy Counsellor]] and Chief Justice of Bengal\n*[[Alexander Maconochie (penal reformer)|Alexander Maconochie]] - Founder of the [[Royal Geographical Society]] and penal reformer.\n*[[Good Shoes]] - an [[indie music]] band whose first album, ''[[Think Before You Speak]]'', included the track \"[[Morden (Good Shoes song)|Morden]]\"\n*[[Sampha]] - a [[singer-songwriter]] best known for his collaborative work with [[SBTRKT]], [[Jessie Ware]] and [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]].\n\n==Nearest places==\n* [[Colliers Wood]]\n* [[Hackbridge]]\n* [[Merton Park]]\n* [[Mitcham, London, England|Mitcham]]\n* [[Lower Morden]]\n* [[Motspur Park]]\n* [[Raynes Park]]\n* [[St. Helier, London|St. Helier]]\n* [[South Wimbledon]]\n* [[Sutton, London|Sutton]]\n* [[Sutton Common]]\n* [[Wimbledon, London, England|Wimbledon]]\n* [[Worcester Park]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Morden baptist church.gif|[[Morden Baptist Church]], Crown Lane\nFile:Bridge at Morden Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1230196.jpg|Bridge at Morden Hall Park\nFile:Morden Hall Park 1.jpg|Morden Hall Park\nFile:Stable Block at Morden Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1230210.jpg|Stable Block at Morden Hall Park.\nFile:The Rose Garden, Morden Hall Park - geograph.org.uk - 1348687.jpg|The Rose Garden, Morden Hall Park\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|London}}\n{{Commons cat|Morden, London|Morden}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120209012036/http://www.collectbritain.co.uk/personalisation/object.cfm?uid=003KTOP00000041U009E0000&largeimage=1#largeimage British Library Collect Britain archive - Mordon, Surrey, 1780]\n* {{ltmcollection|28/i0000d28.jpg|London Transport Museum Photographic Archive}} Aerial view of Morden town centre in 1926 when the Underground station opened. The first roads have been laid out but the area is still mostly fields. The Crown Inn is visible on the left.\n* [http://www.britishpathe.com/product_display.php?canisternumber=UN+79+C&sortnumber=&filmid=&szin=&group=&decade=&date1=&date2=&date3=&datefrom=&dateto=&choice=all&description=Enter+search+word%28s%29+here&searchword=&choice1=all&title=Enter+a+film+title+here&choice2=all&keywords=Enter+key+words+here&choice3=all&summary=Enter+a+summary+search+here&advanced.x=25&advanced.y=25 British Pathe News Archive] 1930s Newsreel footage of construction of Morden Cinema (download - select low resolution free preview)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060614013352/http://www.motco.com/MAP/81001/ Motco.com] [https://web.archive.org/web/20060928085842/http://www.motco.com/MapImages/81001/81001034-w.jpg 15 Miles Round London (First edition), J Cary, 1786, Morden]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929121905/http://mysite.wanadoo-members.co.uk/cavalcade/morden.jpg Odeon Cavalcade - Morden Cinema, 1960s]\n\n{{LB Merton}}\n{{London Districts}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Merton]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:dc5e:2d00:749a:f694:c7b9:c8d9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed grammar)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morden"}
{"title_page": "Djaoeh Dimata", "text_new": "{{featured article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name      = Djaoeh Dimata\n| image     = Djaoeh Di Mata ad.jpg\n| image size   = 300\n| border     =\n| alt      =\n| caption    = Newspaper advertisement, [[Surabaya]]\n| director    =[[Andjar Asmara]]\n| producer    =\n| writer     = Andjar Asmara\n| starring    = {{plain list|\n* [[Ratna Asmara]]\n* [[Ali Joego]]\n}}\n| music     =\n| cinematography = A.A. Denninghoff-Stelling\n| editing    =\n| studio     = South Pacific Film Corporation\n| distributor  =\n| released    = {{Film date|1948|||Dutch East Indies|df=yes}}\n| runtime    =\n| country    = {{plain list|\n* [[Indonesia]]\n* [[Dutch East Indies]]\n}}\n| language    = Indonesian\n| budget     =\n| gross     =\n}}\n[[Connie Glynn]]'s friend, Mint Coven, who has the username @mintfaery on most social media, is quite possibly an even more rotten piece of trash than Connie Glynn is. It was revealed on Twitter that she had encouraged Connie to get rid of all those videos. Connie talked about switching some of them to unlisted where people who have seen and liked them can still watch them, but I will have to see that happen with the most helpful and relatable ones to fully believe it will with those and not just ones people can personally relate to less. But for now, let's direct most of our hate to Mint who is definitely a rotten piece of trash who doesn't think of what's best for anyone she doesn't know.\n\n'''''Djaoeh Dimata'''''{{efn|Various contemporary spellings also include ''Djaoeh di Mata'', ''Djauh Dimata'', and ''Djauh di Mata''.}} ({{IPA-id|d\u0292a\u02c8u di\u02c8mata|}}; [[EYD|Perfected Spelling]]: '''''Jauh Dimata'''''; Indonesian for ''Out of Sight'') is a 1948 film from what is now Indonesia{{efn|The film was released during the [[Indonesian National Revolution]], in which time Indonesia had declared itself independent while the [[Dutch East Indies]] was still formally in existence.}} written and directed by [[Andjar Asmara]] for the South Pacific Film Corporation (SPFC). Starring [[Ratna Asmara]] and [[Ali Joego]], it follows a woman who goes to [[Jakarta]] to find work after her husband is blinded in an accident. SPFC's first production, ''Djaoeh Dimata'' took two to three months to film and cost almost 130,000 [[Netherlands Indies gulden|gulden]].\n\nThe first [[list of films of the Dutch East Indies|domestically produced]] feature film to be released in five years, ''Djaoeh Dimata'' received favourable reviews, although financially it was outperformed by [[Roestam Sutan Palindih]]'s ''[[Air Mata Mengalir di Tjitarum]]'' (released soon after). The film's cast remained active in the Indonesian film industry, some for another thirty years, and SPFC produced six more works before closing in 1949. A copy of the film is stored at [[Sinematek Indonesia]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Ratna Asmara, Ali Yugo, and Iscandar Sukarno in Djaoeh di Mata, Peran Pemuda dalam Kebangkitan Film Indonesia, p50.jpg|upright=1.35|thumb|Ratna Asmara, Ali Joego, and Iscandar Sukarno in a scene from the film]]\nA poor villager, Asrad ([[Ali Joego]]), is blinded following a traffic accident and thus unable to work. As a result, his wife Soelastri ([[Ratna Asmara]]) travels to the capital, [[Jakarta]], to find a job. As Asrad does not trust his wife and fears she may be unfaithful, he writes her a letter telling her to not come back. Soelastri becomes a singer, and&nbsp;\u2013 unknown to Asrad&nbsp;\u2013 soon achieves wide acclaim. Her most popular song, \"Djaoeh Dimata\", receives heavy airplay on the radio and soon becomes one of Asrad's favourites. Ultimately Soelastri is brought home by Soekarto (Iskandar Sucarno), who attempts to pass her off as a maid for Asrad. When Asrad recognises his wife's voice, they are reconciled.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djaoeh Dimata}}; {{harvnb|''Het Dagblad'' 1949, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe first two years of the 1940s saw a growth in the cinema of the [[Dutch East Indies]], with over forty [[List of films of the Dutch East Indies|domestic productions]] released.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=385\u2013387}} Following the [[Japanese occupation of Indonesia|Japanese occupation]] in February 1942, production slowed greatly and nearly all film studios were closed. The last studio, the [[Chinese Indonesians|ethnic Chinese]]-owned Multi Film, was confiscated by the Japanese to establish the film production company Nippon Eigasha in Jakarta, the colony's capital. This included Multi Film's equipment, with which Nippon Eigasha produced one feature film&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rd Ariffien]]'s ''[[Berdjoang]]'' (''Struggle''; 1943)&nbsp;\u2013 six short films, and several [[newsreel]]s. All were [[Japanese propaganda during World War II|pro-Japanese propaganda]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=339\u2013343}}\n\nAfter the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]] in August 1945, a number of [[native Indonesian]] employees of Nippon Eigasha formed [[Berita Film Indonesia]], which first made use of the studios. This company was allied with the newly [[proclamation of Indonesian Independence|proclaimed]] Indonesian government.{{sfn|Danujaya|Tjasmadi|1992|p=50}} During the ensuing [[Indonesian National Revolution|revolution]], allied Dutch and British forces occupied Jakarta in November 1945. The Dutch took over the studio, and production of [[newsreels]] at Multi Film's studios began in 1947 under the banner Regerings Film Bedrijf. The following year the Dutch established a subsidiary company to produce [[fictional film]]s. This new company, the South Pacific Film Corporation (SPFC), was subsidised in part by the [[Netherlands Indies Civil Administration]], a continuation of the former Dutch colonial government of the Indies.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=359}}\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image\n| footer    = [[Ratna Asmara]] and [[Ali Joego]], stars of the film\n\n| image1    = Ratna Asmara p298.JPG\n| alt1      = Ratna Asmara, pictured in 1940\n| width1    = 182\n\n| image2    = Ali Yugo in Djaoeh di Mata.jpg\n| alt2      = Ali Yugo, pictured in 1948\n| width2= 200\n}}\nSPFC hired [[Andjar Asmara]], a former journalist and stagewriter who had been active with [[The Teng Chun]]'s Java Industrial Film before the Japanese occupation, to direct ''Djaoeh Dimata'';{{sfn|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}} he based the screenplay on his stageplay of the same name.{{sfn|Sumardjo|1992|p=247}} However, as with his pre-war ventures, the native Indonesian Andjar was more of an acting and [[dialogue coach]]; the Dutch cinematographer, A.A. Denninghoff-Stelling, held more creative power over the final product.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=359}} [[Max Tera]] served as assistant cinematographer on this [[black-and-white]] film.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Max Tera}}\n\nThe film starred Ratna Asmara (wife of Andjar), Ali Yugo, Iskandar Sucarno, and Djauhari Effendi,{{efn|Sources do not indicate Effendi's role.}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Kredit Djaoeh Dimata}} all of whom had previous theatrical experience. Ratna and Ali, together with Andjar, had been members of the travelling troupe [[Dardanella (theatre company)|Dardanella]] in the early 1930s and entered the film industry together in 1940 with ''[[Kartinah]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}; {{harvnb|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}}</ref> Iskandar and Djauhari, meanwhile, had been active in the theatre during the occupation; both made their feature film debuts with ''Djaoeh Dimata''.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djauhari Effendi}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Iskander Sucarno}}; {{harvnb|''Het Vrije Volk'' 1948, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] was conducted on sets constructed by artistic director Hajopan Bajo Angin in SFPC's studio in Jakarta. The company's equipment was of good quality, but conditions were detrimental to filming; a contemporary report notes that one [[take]], done inside the studio, was ruined by the sound of a passing car.{{sfn|''Limburgsch Dagblad'' 1948, In Batavia Wordt}} Filming, which took two{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1948, Indonesische films}} to three months,{{sfn|''Het Vrije Volk'' 1948, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}} was completed on 10 November 1948.{{sfn|''Het Dagblad'' 1948, Camera draait}} Production costs were almost 130,000 [[Netherlands Indies gulden|gulden]],{{efn|At the time, 130,000 gulden was officially the equivalent to US$ 50,000, with an exchange rate at 2.6 gulden to the dollar. Owing to the war, however, the black market price of dollars was four to five times as much {{harv|Mooney 1948, Holland}}.}} which was partially obtained from ethnic Chinese backers.<ref>{{harvnb|''Limburgsch Dagblad'' 1948, In Batavia Wordt}}; {{harvnb|''De Vrije Pers'' 1948, Indonesische films}}</ref> The film included multiple songs, including [[Gesang Martohartono]]'s 1940 hit \"[[Bengawan Solo (song)|Bengawan Solo]]\".{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1949, (untitled)}}\n\nA documentary detailing one day of the production, called ''Er wordt een film gemaakt'' (''\"A film is being made\"'') exists in the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zoeken.beeldengeluid.nl/program/urn:vme:default:program:2101608050034444231?q=Djoeah+di+Mata|title=Er Wordt Een Film Gemaakt (14 November 1948)|language=nl|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://in.beeldengeluid.nl/collectie/details/expressie/79332/false/true|title=Beeld En Geluid|language=nl|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''Djaoeh Dimata'' was released in late 1948, the first domestic feature film since ''Berdjoang''.{{sfn|Said|McGlynn|Heider|1991|p=3}} Despite this five-year gap, film critic [[Usmar Ismail]] writes that it did not stray from the formula which had been proven before the war,{{sfn|Ismail|1983|pp=54\u201356}} one which Indonesian film historian [[Misbach Yusa Biran]] notes focused on songs, beautiful scenery and romance.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=25}} [[Roestam Sutan Palindih]]'s ''[[Air Mata Mengalir di Tjitarum]]'' (''Tears Flow in Citarum''), which had similar themes, was released shortly after ''Djaoeh Dimata'' by the rival Tan & Wong Bros.; it proved the greater financial success.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=367}} Only three domestic productions were released in 1948; the last was another SPFC production, entitled ''Anggrek Bulan'' (''Moon Orchid''), which was also directed by Andjar.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=385}}\n\nReviews of the film, which was rated for all ages,{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1949, (untitled)}} were mixed. One in the Jakarta-based ''Het Dagblad'' found the film to have many (unspecified) weak moments as well as strong ones. It particularly praised Ali's acting as a blind man, as well as Denninghoff-Stelling's camerawork.{{sfn|''Het Dagblad'' 1949, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}} Another reviewer, in the magazine ''Mestika'', described Ratna as an \"unprecedented tragedienne\"{{efn|Original: \"''...&nbsp;een tragedienne zonder weerga''\"}} capable of making viewers cry \"unrestrained tears of emotion\".{{efn|Original: \"''...&nbsp;zijn tranen van ontroering, niet bedwingen kan.''\"}}<ref>Quoted in {{harvnb|''Het Nieuwsblad voor Sumatra'' 1949, Een 'Anak Medan'}}</ref> After ''Djaoeh Dimata'' was released in [[Singapore]] in June 1949, a reviewer for ''[[The Straits Times]]'' praised the film's \"fine photography and almost perfect sound\".{{sfn|''The Straits Times'' 1949, Indies Film}}\n\nAndjar directed two further films for South Pacific, ''Anggrek Bulan'' and ''[[Gadis Desa]]'' (''Maiden from the Village''; 1949).{{sfn|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}} Ratna had no further acting roles, although in 1950 she became Indonesia's first female director with ''[[Sedap Malam]]'' (''Sweetness of the Night''), for [[Djamaluddin Malik]]'s company Persari.{{sfn|Swestin|2009|p=104}} Ali, Iskandar, and Djauhari remained active as actors, Ali and Iskandar through the 1960s and Djauhari until the 1970s.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djauhari Effendi}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Iskander Sucarno}}</ref> SPFC made another six films before shutting down at the end of the [[Indonesian National Revolution]] in 1949.{{Efn|The Dutch had recognised Indonesia's independence after [[Dutch\u2013Indonesian Round Table Conference|several months of negotiations]]. In the aftermath, the Indonesian government acquired Regerings Film Bedrijf, SPFC's parent company. It was merged with Berita Film Indonesia to form Perusahaan Pilem Negara (State Film Company), later renamed [[Produksi Film Negara]] {{harv|JCG, Berita Film Indonesia}}.}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, South Pacific}} A [[35mm movie film|35&nbsp;mm]] copy of ''Djaoeh Dimata'' is stored at [[Sinematek Indonesia]] in Jakarta.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djaoeh Dimata}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Ali Yugo\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4b9bad932aa5f_ali-yugo\n |work        = filmindonesia.or.id\n |publisher   = Konfidan Foundation\n |location    = Jakarta\n |accessdate  = 1 December 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6CaSr61kQ?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4b9bad932aa5f_ali-yugo\n |archivedate = 1 December 2012\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Andjar Asmara\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/709\n |encyclopedia        = Encyclopedia of Jakarta\n |publisher   = Jakarta City Government\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}}\n |accessdate  = 7 August 2012\n |archivedate = 7 August 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69jK75pUT?url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/709\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Berita Film Indonesia\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/3836\n |encyclopedia        = Encyclopedia of Jakarta\n |publisher   = Jakarta City Government\n |ref         = {{harvid|JCG, Berita Film Indonesia}}\n |accessdate  = 2 December 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6CbtLDUbe?url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/3836\n |archivedate = 2 December 2012\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  | title = Sejarah Film 1900\u20131950: Bikin Film di Jawa\n  |trans-title=History of Film 1900\u20131950: Making Films in Java\n  | language = Indonesian\n  | last = Biran\n  | first = Misbach Yusa\n  | authorlink = Misbach Yusa Biran\n  | location = Jakarta\n  | publisher = Komunitas Bamboo working with the Jakarta Art Council\n  | year = 2009\n  | isbn = 978-979-3731-58-2\n  | ref = harv\n  |title-link=Sejarah Film 1900\u20131950: Bikin Film di Jawa\n }}\n* {{cite news\n |title=Camera draait in studio's van Multifilm 'Djaoeh di Mata'\n |trans-title=The Camera Turns in Multifilm's Studios for 'Djaoeh di Mata'\n |language=Dutch\n |work=Het Dagblad\n |date=11 November 1948\n |page=2\n |url=http://kranten.kb.nl/view/article/id/ddd%3A010897595%3Ampeg21%3Ap002%3Aa0046\n |ref={{sfnRef|''Het Dagblad'' 1948, Camera draait}}\n |location=Jakarta\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=Layar Perak: 90 Tahun Bioskop di Indonesia\n |trans-title=Silver Screen: 90 Years of Cinema in Indonesia\n |language=Indonesian\n |publisher=Gramedia\n |last1=Danujaya\n |first1=Budiarto\n |first2=Mohammad Johan\n |last2=Tjasmadi\n |ref=harv\n |year=1992\n |oclc=28028443\n |location=Jakarta\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |title=Djaoeh di Mata\n |language=Dutch\n |work=Het Dagblad\n |date=13 March 1949\n |page=2\n |url=http://kranten.kb.nl/view/article/id/ddd%3A010897696%3Ampeg21%3Ap002%3Aa0059\n |ref={{sfnRef|Het Dagblad 1949, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}}\n |location=Jakarta\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |title='Djaoeh di Mata'&nbsp;\u2013 een Indonesiesche film\n |trans-title='Djaoeh di Mata'&nbsp;\u2013 an Indonesian Film\n |language=Dutch\n |work=Het Vrije Volk\n |date=4 December 1948\n |page=6\n |url=http://kranten.kb.nl/view/article/id/ddd%3A010897696%3Ampeg21%3Ap002%3Aa0059\n |ref={{sfnRef|Het Vrije Volk 1948, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}}\n |location=Rotterdam\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Djaoeh Dimata\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/title/lf-d011-48-446958_djauh-dimata\n |work        = filmindonesia.or.id\n |publisher   = Konfiden Foundation\n |location    = Jakarta\n |accessdate  = 23 August 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6A7g6Mdcc?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/title/lf-d011-48-446958_djauh-dimata\n |archivedate = 23 August 2012\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djaoeh Dimata}}\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Djauhari Effendi\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4bc56cfc79c29_djauhari-effendi\n |work        = filmindonesia.or.id\n |publisher   = Konfidan Foundation\n |location    = Jakarta\n |accessdate  = 1 December 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6CaT0jxD4?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4bc56cfc79c29_djauhari-effendi\n |archivedate = 1 December 2012\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djauhari Effendi}}\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |title=Een 'Anak Medan' als Filmster\n |trans-title=An 'Anak Medan' as an Actress\n |language=Dutch\n |work=Het Nieuwsblad voor Sumatra\n |date=3 March 1949\n |page=2\n |url=http://kranten.kb.nl/view/paper/id/ddd%3A010475041%3Ampeg21%3Ap002%3Aa0019\n |ref={{sfnRef|''Het Nieuwsblad voor Sumatra'' 1949, Een 'Anak Medan'}}\n |location=Medan\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |title=In Batavia Wordt Gefilmd 'Djauh di mata' eerste Indonesische speelfilm\n |trans-title=Filmed in Batavia: 'Djauh di Mata', the First Indonesian Film\n |language=Dutch\n |work=Limburgsch Dagblad\n |date=26 November 1948\n |page=5\n |url=http://kranten.kb.nl/view/article/id/ddd%3A010416175%3Ampeg21%3Ap005%3Aa0117\n |ref={{sfnRef|''Limburgsch Dagblad'' 1948, In Batavia Wordt}}\n |location=Heerlen\n}}\n* {{Cite news\n |title=Indies Film in S'pore\n |work=The Straits Times\n |location=Singapore\n |date=8 June 1949\n |page=7\n |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19490608-1.2.86.aspx\n |via=National Library of Singapore\n |ref={{sfnRef|''The Straits Times'' 1949, Indies Film}}\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |title=Indonesische films\n |trans-title=Indonesian Films\n |language=Dutch\n |work=De Vrije Pers\n |date=11 November 1948\n |page=2\n |url=http://kranten.kb.nl/view/article/id/ddd%3A011209980%3Ampeg21%3Ap002%3Aa0041\n |ref={{sfnRef|''De Vrije Pers'' 1948, Indonesische films}}\n |location=Surabaya\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Iskandar Sucarno\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4bc56cbfca4b3_iskandar-sucarno/filmography\n |work        = filmindonesia.or.id\n |publisher   = Konfidan Foundation\n |location    = Jakarta\n |accessdate  = 1 July 2013\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6Hmur0Hzv?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4bc56cbfca4b3_iskandar-sucarno/filmography\n |archivedate = 1 July 2013\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, Iskander Sucarno}}\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |last=Ismail\n |first=Usmar\n |title=Usmar Ismail Mengupas Film\n |trans-title=Usmar Ismail Discusses Film\n |chapter=Sari Soal dalam Film Indonesia\n |trans-chapter=A Summary of Issues Faced by Indonesian Films\n |pages=53\u201366\n |language=Indonesian\n |year=1983\n |publisher=Sinar Harapan\n |location=Jakarta\n |ref=harv\n |oclc=10435722\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Kredit Djaoeh Dimata\n |trans-title=Credits for Djaoeh Dimata\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/title/lf-d011-48-446958_djauh-dimata/credit\n |work        = filmindonesia.or.id\n |publisher   = Konfidan Foundation\n |location    = Jakarta\n |accessdate  = 1 July 2013\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6HmuK6VgU?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/title/lf-d011-48-446958_djauh-dimata/credit\n |archivedate = 1 July 2013\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, Kredit Djaoeh Dimata}}\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite web |title=Max Tera |language=Indonesian |url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4b9bad50c31ee_max-tera |work=filmindonesia.or.id |publisher=Konfidan Foundation |location=Jakarta |accessdate=13 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6A7imii3t?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/title/lf-t006-49-102168_tjitra |ref={{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, Max Tera}} |archivedate=23 August 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}\n* {{cite news\n |last=Mooney\n |first=George A.\n |work=The New York Times\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/11/14/archives/holland-attacked-on-indies-policies-indonesian-minister-says.html\n |date=14 November 1948\n |pages=F1, F2\n |ref={{sfnRef|Mooney 1948, Holland}}\n |title=Holland Attacked on Indies Policies\n}} {{subscription needed}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=Cinema of Indonesia: Eleven Indonesian Films, Notes & Synopses\n |last1=Said\n |first1=Salim\n |last2=McGlynn\n |first2=John H.\n |author2-link=John H. McGlynn\n |last3=Heider\n |first3=Karl G\n |author3-link=Karl G. Heider\n |publisher=Festival of Indonesia Foundation\n |location=New York\n |year=1991\n |isbn=978-1-879578-00-5\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = South Pacific Film\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmo4b9bcdde9ed16_south-pacific-film/filmography\n |work        = filmindonesia.or.id\n |publisher   = Konfidan Foundation\n |location    = Jakarta\n |accessdate  = 1 December 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6Ca1Uc78e?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmo4b9bcdde9ed16_south-pacific-film/filmography\n |archivedate = 1 December 2012\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, South Pacific}}\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=Perkembangan Teater Modern dan Sastra Drama Indonesia\n |trans-title=Development of Modern Theatre and Literary Drama in Indonesia\n |language=Indonesian\n |publisher=Citra Aditya Bakti\n |last1=Sumardjo\n |first1=Jakob\n |ref=harv\n |year=1992\n |isbn=978-979-414-615-6\n |location=Bandung\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n |title       = In the Boys' Club: A Historical Perspective on the Roles of Women in the Indonesian Cinema 1926&nbsp;\u2013 May 1998\n |pages       = 103\u2013111\n |date        = July 2009\n |url         = http://puslit2.petra.ac.id/ejournal/index.php/iko/article/viewFile/18314/18162\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69zwHVXHA?url=http://puslit2.petra.ac.id/ejournal/index.php/iko/article/viewFile/18314/18162\n |archivedate = 18 August 2012\n |ref         = harv\n |last        = Swestin\n |first       = Grace\n |journal        = Scriptura\n |issue       = 2\n |location    = Surabaya\n |publisher   = Petra Christian University\n |volume      = 3\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |title=(untitled)\n |language=Dutch\n |url=http://kranten.kb.nl/view/paper/id/ddd%3A011210134%3Ampeg21%3Ap004%3Aa0010\n |work=De Vrije Pers\n |publisher=De Erven J.A. Wormser Mogelijk freelancers\n |date=18 May 1949\n |page=4\n |ref={{sfnRef|De Vrije Pers 1949, (untitled)}}\n}}\n{{refend}}\n{{Andjar Asmara}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|Indonesia|Netherlands}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n[[Category:Indonesian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Indonesian films]]\n[[Category:Films of the Dutch East Indies]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Andjar Asmara]]\n", "text_old": "{{featured article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name      = Djaoeh Dimata\n| image     = Djaoeh Di Mata ad.jpg\n| image size   = 300\n| border     =\n| alt      =\n| caption    = Newspaper advertisement, [[Surabaya]]\n| director    =[[Andjar Asmara]]\n| producer    =\n| writer     = Andjar Asmara\n| starring    = {{plain list|\n* [[Ratna Asmara]]\n* [[Ali Joego]]\n}}\n| music     =\n| cinematography = A.A. Denninghoff-Stelling\n| editing    =\n| studio     = South Pacific Film Corporation\n| distributor  =\n| released    = {{Film date|1948|||Dutch East Indies|df=yes}}\n| runtime    =\n| country    = {{plain list|\n* [[Indonesia]]\n* [[Dutch East Indies]]\n}}\n| language    = Indonesian\n| budget     =\n| gross     =\n}}\n'''''Djaoeh Dimata'''''{{efn|Various contemporary spellings also include ''Djaoeh di Mata'', ''Djauh Dimata'', and ''Djauh di Mata''.}} ({{IPA-id|d\u0292a\u02c8u di\u02c8mata|}}; [[EYD|Perfected Spelling]]: '''''Jauh Dimata'''''; Indonesian for ''Out of Sight'') is a 1948 film from what is now Indonesia{{efn|The film was released during the [[Indonesian National Revolution]], in which time Indonesia had declared itself independent while the [[Dutch East Indies]] was still formally in existence.}} written and directed by [[Andjar Asmara]] for the South Pacific Film Corporation (SPFC). Starring [[Ratna Asmara]] and [[Ali Joego]], it follows a woman who goes to [[Jakarta]] to find work after her husband is blinded in an accident. SPFC's first production, ''Djaoeh Dimata'' took two to three months to film and cost almost 130,000 [[Netherlands Indies gulden|gulden]].\n\nThe first [[list of films of the Dutch East Indies|domestically produced]] feature film to be released in five years, ''Djaoeh Dimata'' received favourable reviews, although financially it was outperformed by [[Roestam Sutan Palindih]]'s ''[[Air Mata Mengalir di Tjitarum]]'' (released soon after). The film's cast remained active in the Indonesian film industry, some for another thirty years, and SPFC produced six more works before closing in 1949. A copy of the film is stored at [[Sinematek Indonesia]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Ratna Asmara, Ali Yugo, and Iscandar Sukarno in Djaoeh di Mata, Peran Pemuda dalam Kebangkitan Film Indonesia, p50.jpg|upright=1.35|thumb|Ratna Asmara, Ali Joego, and Iscandar Sukarno in a scene from the film]]\nA poor villager, Asrad ([[Ali Joego]]), is blinded following a traffic accident and thus unable to work. As a result, his wife Soelastri ([[Ratna Asmara]]) travels to the capital, [[Jakarta]], to find a job. As Asrad does not trust his wife and fears she may be unfaithful, he writes her a letter telling her to not come back. Soelastri becomes a singer, and&nbsp;\u2013 unknown to Asrad&nbsp;\u2013 soon achieves wide acclaim. Her most popular song, \"Djaoeh Dimata\", receives heavy airplay on the radio and soon becomes one of Asrad's favourites. Ultimately Soelastri is brought home by Soekarto (Iskandar Sucarno), who attempts to pass her off as a maid for Asrad. When Asrad recognises his wife's voice, they are reconciled.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djaoeh Dimata}}; {{harvnb|''Het Dagblad'' 1949, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe first two years of the 1940s saw a growth in the cinema of the [[Dutch East Indies]], with over forty [[List of films of the Dutch East Indies|domestic productions]] released.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=385\u2013387}} Following the [[Japanese occupation of Indonesia|Japanese occupation]] in February 1942, production slowed greatly and nearly all film studios were closed. The last studio, the [[Chinese Indonesians|ethnic Chinese]]-owned Multi Film, was confiscated by the Japanese to establish the film production company Nippon Eigasha in Jakarta, the colony's capital. This included Multi Film's equipment, with which Nippon Eigasha produced one feature film&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rd Ariffien]]'s ''[[Berdjoang]]'' (''Struggle''; 1943)&nbsp;\u2013 six short films, and several [[newsreel]]s. All were [[Japanese propaganda during World War II|pro-Japanese propaganda]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=339\u2013343}}\n\nAfter the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrender]] in August 1945, a number of [[native Indonesian]] employees of Nippon Eigasha formed [[Berita Film Indonesia]], which first made use of the studios. This company was allied with the newly [[proclamation of Indonesian Independence|proclaimed]] Indonesian government.{{sfn|Danujaya|Tjasmadi|1992|p=50}} During the ensuing [[Indonesian National Revolution|revolution]], allied Dutch and British forces occupied Jakarta in November 1945. The Dutch took over the studio, and production of [[newsreels]] at Multi Film's studios began in 1947 under the banner Regerings Film Bedrijf. The following year the Dutch established a subsidiary company to produce [[fictional film]]s. This new company, the South Pacific Film Corporation (SPFC), was subsidised in part by the [[Netherlands Indies Civil Administration]], a continuation of the former Dutch colonial government of the Indies.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=359}}\n\n==Production==\n{{multiple image\n| footer    = [[Ratna Asmara]] and [[Ali Joego]], stars of the film\n\n| image1    = Ratna Asmara p298.JPG\n| alt1      = Ratna Asmara, pictured in 1940\n| width1    = 182\n\n| image2    = Ali Yugo in Djaoeh di Mata.jpg\n| alt2      = Ali Yugo, pictured in 1948\n| width2= 200\n}}\nSPFC hired [[Andjar Asmara]], a former journalist and stagewriter who had been active with [[The Teng Chun]]'s Java Industrial Film before the Japanese occupation, to direct ''Djaoeh Dimata'';{{sfn|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}} he based the screenplay on his stageplay of the same name.{{sfn|Sumardjo|1992|p=247}} However, as with his pre-war ventures, the native Indonesian Andjar was more of an acting and [[dialogue coach]]; the Dutch cinematographer, A.A. Denninghoff-Stelling, held more creative power over the final product.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=359}} [[Max Tera]] served as assistant cinematographer on this [[black-and-white]] film.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Max Tera}}\n\nThe film starred Ratna Asmara (wife of Andjar), Ali Yugo, Iskandar Sucarno, and Djauhari Effendi,{{efn|Sources do not indicate Effendi's role.}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Kredit Djaoeh Dimata}} all of whom had previous theatrical experience. Ratna and Ali, together with Andjar, had been members of the travelling troupe [[Dardanella (theatre company)|Dardanella]] in the early 1930s and entered the film industry together in 1940 with ''[[Kartinah]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}; {{harvnb|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}}</ref> Iskandar and Djauhari, meanwhile, had been active in the theatre during the occupation; both made their feature film debuts with ''Djaoeh Dimata''.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djauhari Effendi}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Iskander Sucarno}}; {{harvnb|''Het Vrije Volk'' 1948, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}}</ref>\n\n[[Principal photography]] was conducted on sets constructed by artistic director Hajopan Bajo Angin in SFPC's studio in Jakarta. The company's equipment was of good quality, but conditions were detrimental to filming; a contemporary report notes that one [[take]], done inside the studio, was ruined by the sound of a passing car.{{sfn|''Limburgsch Dagblad'' 1948, In Batavia Wordt}} Filming, which took two{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1948, Indonesische films}} to three months,{{sfn|''Het Vrije Volk'' 1948, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}} was completed on 10 November 1948.{{sfn|''Het Dagblad'' 1948, Camera draait}} Production costs were almost 130,000 [[Netherlands Indies gulden|gulden]],{{efn|At the time, 130,000 gulden was officially the equivalent to US$ 50,000, with an exchange rate at 2.6 gulden to the dollar. Owing to the war, however, the black market price of dollars was four to five times as much {{harv|Mooney 1948, Holland}}.}} which was partially obtained from ethnic Chinese backers.<ref>{{harvnb|''Limburgsch Dagblad'' 1948, In Batavia Wordt}}; {{harvnb|''De Vrije Pers'' 1948, Indonesische films}}</ref> The film included multiple songs, including [[Gesang Martohartono]]'s 1940 hit \"[[Bengawan Solo (song)|Bengawan Solo]]\".{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1949, (untitled)}}\n\nA documentary detailing one day of the production, called ''Er wordt een film gemaakt'' (''\"A film is being made\"'') exists in the Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zoeken.beeldengeluid.nl/program/urn:vme:default:program:2101608050034444231?q=Djoeah+di+Mata|title=Er Wordt Een Film Gemaakt (14 November 1948)|language=nl|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://in.beeldengeluid.nl/collectie/details/expressie/79332/false/true|title=Beeld En Geluid|language=nl|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''Djaoeh Dimata'' was released in late 1948, the first domestic feature film since ''Berdjoang''.{{sfn|Said|McGlynn|Heider|1991|p=3}} Despite this five-year gap, film critic [[Usmar Ismail]] writes that it did not stray from the formula which had been proven before the war,{{sfn|Ismail|1983|pp=54\u201356}} one which Indonesian film historian [[Misbach Yusa Biran]] notes focused on songs, beautiful scenery and romance.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=25}} [[Roestam Sutan Palindih]]'s ''[[Air Mata Mengalir di Tjitarum]]'' (''Tears Flow in Citarum''), which had similar themes, was released shortly after ''Djaoeh Dimata'' by the rival Tan & Wong Bros.; it proved the greater financial success.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=367}} Only three domestic productions were released in 1948; the last was another SPFC production, entitled ''Anggrek Bulan'' (''Moon Orchid''), which was also directed by Andjar.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=385}}\n\nReviews of the film, which was rated for all ages,{{sfn|''De Vrije Pers'' 1949, (untitled)}} were mixed. One in the Jakarta-based ''Het Dagblad'' found the film to have many (unspecified) weak moments as well as strong ones. It particularly praised Ali's acting as a blind man, as well as Denninghoff-Stelling's camerawork.{{sfn|''Het Dagblad'' 1949, 'Djaoeh di Mata'}} Another reviewer, in the magazine ''Mestika'', described Ratna as an \"unprecedented tragedienne\"{{efn|Original: \"''...&nbsp;een tragedienne zonder weerga''\"}} capable of making viewers cry \"unrestrained tears of emotion\".{{efn|Original: \"''...&nbsp;zijn tranen van ontroering, niet bedwingen kan.''\"}}<ref>Quoted in {{harvnb|''Het Nieuwsblad voor Sumatra'' 1949, Een 'Anak Medan'}}</ref> After ''Djaoeh Dimata'' was released in [[Singapore]] in June 1949, a reviewer for ''[[The Straits Times]]'' praised the film's \"fine photography and almost perfect sound\".{{sfn|''The Straits Times'' 1949, Indies Film}}\n\nAndjar directed two further films for South Pacific, ''Anggrek Bulan'' and ''[[Gadis Desa]]'' (''Maiden from the Village''; 1949).{{sfn|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}} Ratna had no further acting roles, although in 1950 she became Indonesia's first female director with ''[[Sedap Malam]]'' (''Sweetness of the Night''), for [[Djamaluddin Malik]]'s company Persari.{{sfn|Swestin|2009|p=104}} Ali, Iskandar, and Djauhari remained active as actors, Ali and Iskandar through the 1960s and Djauhari until the 1970s.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djauhari Effendi}}; {{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Iskander Sucarno}}</ref> SPFC made another six films before shutting down at the end of the [[Indonesian National Revolution]] in 1949.{{Efn|The Dutch had recognised Indonesia's independence after [[Dutch\u2013Indonesian Round Table Conference|several months of negotiations]]. In the aftermath, the Indonesian government acquired Regerings Film Bedrijf, SPFC's parent company. It was merged with Berita Film Indonesia to form Perusahaan Pilem Negara (State Film Company), later renamed [[Produksi Film Negara]] {{harv|JCG, Berita Film Indonesia}}.}}{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, South Pacific}} A [[35mm movie film|35&nbsp;mm]] copy of ''Djaoeh Dimata'' is stored at [[Sinematek Indonesia]] in Jakarta.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djaoeh Dimata}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Ali Yugo\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4b9bad932aa5f_ali-yugo\n |work        = filmindonesia.or.id\n |publisher   = Konfidan Foundation\n |location    = Jakarta\n |accessdate  = 1 December 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6CaSr61kQ?url=http://filmindonesia.or.id/movie/name/nmp4b9bad932aa5f_ali-yugo\n |archivedate = 1 December 2012\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Filmindonesia.or.id, Ali Yugo}}\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Andjar Asmara\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/709\n |encyclopedia        = Encyclopedia of Jakarta\n |publisher   = Jakarta City Government\n |ref         = {{sfnRef|Encyclopedia of Jakarta, Andjar Asmara}}\n |accessdate  = 7 August 2012\n |archivedate = 7 August 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69jK75pUT?url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/709\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Berita Film Indonesia\n |language    = Indonesian\n |url         = http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/3836\n |encyclopedia        = Encyclopedia of Jakarta\n |publisher   = Jakarta City Government\n |ref         = {{harvid|JCG, Berita Film Indonesia}}\n |accessdate  = 2 December 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6CbtLDUbe?url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/jakv1/encyclopedia/detail/3836\n |archivedate = 2 December 2012\n |url-status     = dead\n |df          = dmy\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  | title = Sejarah Film 1900\u20131950: Bikin Film di Jawa\n  |trans-title=History of Film 1900\u20131950: Making Films in Java\n  | language = Indonesian\n  | last = Biran\n  | first = Misbach Yusa\n  | authorlink = Misbach Yusa Biran\n  | location = Jakarta\n  | publisher = Komunitas Bamboo wor