ing/more/cool_web/\n\n\u00b7 Under the Mountains & Beside a Creek http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/writing/more/under_the_mountains_and_beside_a_creek/\n\n\u00b7 The Lyric Stance (Island Journal, 126, 2011) http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/writing/more/the_lyric_stance_voice_place_and_the_lyric_essay/\n\n\u00b7 A Portrait of the Artist as Half a Dozen Places (2009; Meanjin)\n\n\u00b7 A Storm & a Teacup https://web.archive.org/web/20160304102809/http://www.australianbookreview.com.au/files/Features/Calibre/Calibre_-_Tredinnick_essay.pdf\n\n\u00b7 Days of Christmas (won the Wildcare Nature Writing Prize, 2004, in Best Australian Essays 2005) http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/writing/more/days_of_christmas/\n\n\u00b7 Loneliness and Creativity http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/news/more/loneliness_and_creativity/\n\n\u00b7 A Peaceable Revolution (in the book Project Republic, 2013) http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/writing/more/a_peaceable/\n\n\u00b7 The Weather of Who We Are (broadcast on \u201cOckham\u2019s Razor\u201d, Radio National, May 2012; also in Best Australian Science Writing 2013) http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/ockhamsrazor/the-weather-of-who-we-are/4016824;\n\n\u00b7 A Poet's Guide to Climate Change (broadcast on \u201cOckham\u2019s Razor\u201d, Radio National 2012) http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/ockhamsrazor/a-poet27s-guide-to-climate-change/4426198\n\n\u00b7 Getting Over Your Self (Introduction to Sparks, anthology of writing from Uni Sydney creative writing students, 2012) http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/writing/more/getting_over_your_self/\n\n\u00b7 Prize Life; Praise Life (Introduction to Award-Winning Australian Writing 2012) http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/writing/more/prize_life_praise_life/\n\n=== As editor ===\n\n* ''A Place on Earth'' (UNSW / U Nebraska, 2003/4)\n* ''Australian Love Poems 2013'' (Inkerman and Blunt, 2013)\n\n=== Prose ===\n\n* ''The Land's Wild Music'' (Trinity, 2005)\n* ''The Blue Plateau: A Landscape Memoir'' (UNSW / Milkweed, 2009)\n* ''Australia's Wild Weather'' (NLA, November 2009)\nFor a full list, see http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/A14240?mainTabTemplate=agentWorksBy\n\n=== Non-fiction ===\n\n* ''The Little Red Writing Book'' (UNSW, 2006)\n* ''The Little Green Grammar Book'' (UNSW, 2008)\n* ''Writing Well: The Essential Guide'' (Cambridge, 2008)\n* ''The Little Black Book of Business Writing'' with Geoff Whyte (UNSW, 2010)\n\n===Critical studies and reviews of Tredinnick's work===\n;Fire diary\n* {{cite journal |author=Ryan, Brendan |authorlink=Brendan Ryan (poet) |date=September 2011 |title=Walking the line |journal=Australian Book Review |issue=334 |pages=64}}\n\n== References ==\n# http://montrealprize.com/about-us/2011-competition/2011-montreal-prize-winner/\n# [https://web.archive.org/web/20140429044726/http://www.literaturewales.org/cipc/i/141520/ Cardiff International Poetry Competition 2012 \u2013 The Winners]. \n# [http://pba.slwa.wa.gov.au/awards_archive/2010 Western Australian Premier's Book Awards \u2013 2010].\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.marktredinnick.com.au}}\n* [http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/singlePoet.do?poetId=12219 Profile at the Poetry Archive]\n* [http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/poet-walks-away-with-major-international-prize-20111218-1p0lr.html Profile at the Sydney Morning Herald]\n\n<!-- Just press the \"Save page\" button below without changing anything! Doing so will submit your article submission for review. Once you have saved this page you will find a new yellow 'Review waiting' box at the bottom of your submission page. If you have submitted your page previously, either the old pink 'Submission declined' template or the old grey 'Draft' template will still appear at the top of your submission page, but you should ignore it. Again, please don't change anything in this text box. Just press the \"Save page\" button below. -->\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tredinnick, Mark}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian poets]]\n[[Category:Australian essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Meanjin people]]\n[[Category:Australian male poets]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Poetrylove444", "label": "safe", "comment": "format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Tredinnick"}
{"title_page": "John Gorton", "text_new": "{{for|the English writer|John Gorton (writer\n|office4           = [[Minister for Social Services (Australia)#List of works ministers|Minister for Works]]\n|primeminister4    = [[Robert Menzies]]<br />[[Harold Holt]]\n|term_start4       = 18 December 1963\n|term_end4         = 28 February 1967\n|predecessor4      = [[Gordon Freeth]]\n|successor4        = [[Bert Kelly]]\n\n|office5           = [[Minister for Home Affairs (Australia)#List of Ministers for the Interior|Minister for the Interior]]\n|primeminister5    = [[Robert Menzies]]\n|term_start5       = 18 December 1963\n|term_end5         = 4 March 1964\n|predecessor5      = Gordon Freeth\n|successor5        = [[Doug Anthony]]\n\n|office6           = [[Minister for Defence (Australia)#Ministers for the Navy|Minister for the Navy]]\n|primeminister6    = [[Robert Menzies]]\n|term_start6       = 10 December 1958\n|term_end6         = 18 December 1963\n|predecessor6      = [[Charles Davidson (politician)|Charles Davidson]]\n|successor6        = [[Jim Forbes (Australian politician)|Jim Forbes]]\n\n| order7             = [[Liberal Party of Australia|Leader of the Liberal Party]]\n| term_start7        = 9 January 1968\n| term_end7          = 10 March 1971\n| deputy7            = [[William McMahon]]\n| predecessor7       = [[Harold Holt]]\n| successor7         = William McMahon\n\n|order8              = [[Liberal Party of Australia|Deputy Leader of the Liberal Party]]\n|term_start8         = 10 March 1971\n|term_end8           = 18 August 1971\n|primeminister8      = William McMahon\n|predecessor8        = William McMahon\n|successor8          = [[Billy Snedden]]\n\n\n|constituency_MP9 = [[Division of Higgins|Higgins]]\n|parliament9      = Australian\n|term_start9      = 24 February 1968\n|term_end9        = 11 November 1975\n|predecessor9     = [[Harold Holt]]\n|successor9       = [[Roger Shipton]]\n\n\n|office10          = [[Australian Senate|Senator for]] [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n|term_start10      = 22 February 1950\n|term_end10        = 1 February 1968\n|predecessor10     =\n|successor10       = [[Ivor Greenwood]]\n\n|birth_name    = John Grey Gorton\n|birth_date    ={{birth date|df=y|1911|9|9}}\n|birth_place   = uncertain \u2013 [[Wellington]], New Zealand, ''or'' [[Prahran, Victoria]], Australia\n|death_date    ={{death date and age|df=y|2002|5|19|1911|9|9}}\n|death_place   =[[St Vincent's Hospital, Sydney|St Vincent's Hospital]], Sydney, Australia \n|resting_place     = [[Melbourne General Cemetery]]\n|party= [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] (1949\u20131975, 1993\u20132002)\n|otherparty = [[National Party of Australia|Country]] (until 1949)<br />[[Independent (politician)|Independent]] (1975\u20131993)\n|education    = [[Sydney Church of England Grammar School]]<br />[[Geelong Grammar School]]\n|alma_mater = [[Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|[[Bettina Gorton|Bettina Brown]]<br />|1935|1983|reason=died}}<br />{{marriage|Nancy Home<br />|1993}}\n|children      = 3\n|allegiance    = Australia\n|branch        = [[Royal Australian Air Force]]\n|serviceyears  = 1940\u20131944\n|rank= [[Flight Lieutenant]]\n|unit={{plainlist|\n*No. 61 Operational Training Unit RAF\n*[[No. 232 Squadron RAF]]\n*[[No. 77 Squadron RAAF]]\n*[[No. 2 Operational Conversion Unit RAAF]]\n}}\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n}}\n'''Sir John Grey Gorton''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|GCMG|AC|CH|}} (9 September 1911 \u2013 19 May 2002) was the [[List of Prime Ministers of Australia|nineteenth]] [[Prime Minister of Australia]], in office from 1968 to 1971. He led the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] during that time, having previously been a long-serving government minister.\n\nGorton was born out of wedlock and had a turbulent childhood. He studied at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]], after finishing his secondary education at [[Geelong Grammar School]], and then returned to Australia to take over his father's property in northern [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. Gorton enlisted in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] in 1940, and served as a fighter pilot in [[Malayan Campaign|Malaya]] and [[New Guinea Campaign|New Guinea]] during the Second World War. He suffered severe facial injuries in a crash landing on [[Bintan Island]] in 1942, and whilst being evacuated; his ship was torpedoed and sunk by a Japanese submarine. He returned to farming after being discharged in 1944, and was elected to the [[Shire of Kerang|Kerang Shire Council]] in 1946; he later served a term as shire president.\n\nAfter a previous unsuccessful candidacy at state level, Gorton was elected to the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] at the [[1949 Australian federal election|1949 federal election]]. He took a keen interest in foreign policy, and gained a reputation as a strident [[anti-Communist]]. Gorton was promoted to the ministry in 1958, and over the following decade held a variety of different portfolios in the governments of [[Robert Menzies]] and [[Harold Holt]]. He was responsible at various times for the Navy, public works, education, and science. He was elevated to the Cabinet in 1966, and the following year, he was promoted to [[Leader of the Government in the Senate (Australia)|Leader of the Government in the Senate]].\n\nGorton [[1968 Liberal Party of Australia leadership election|defeated]] three other candidates for the Liberal leadership after [[Disappearance of Harold Holt|Harold Holt's disappearance]] on 17 December 1967. He became the first and only senator to assume the office of Prime Minister, but soon transferred to the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] in line with constitutional convention. The [[Gorton Government]] continued [[Military history of Australia during the Vietnam War|Australian involvement]] in the [[Vietnam War]], but began withdrawing troops amid growing public discontent. It retained office at the [[1969 Australian federal election|1969 federal election]], albeit with a severely reduced majority. Gorton's domestic policies, which emphasised [[centralisation]] and [[economic nationalism]], were often controversial in his own party, and his individualistic style alienated many of his Cabinet members. He resigned as Liberal leader in 1971 after a [[confidence motion]] in his leadership was tied, and was replaced by [[William McMahon]].\n\nAfter losing the premiership, Gorton was elected deputy leader under McMahon and appointed [[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for Defence]]. He was sacked for disloyalty after a few months. After the Coalition's defeat at the [[1972 Australian federal election|1972 federal election]], Gorton [[1972 Liberal Party of Australia leadership election|unsuccessfully stood]] as McMahon's replacement. He briefly served as an opposition [[frontbencher]] under [[Billy Snedden]], but stood down in 1974 and spent the rest of his career as a [[backbencher]]. Gorton resigned from the Liberal Party when [[Malcolm Fraser]] was elected leader, and at the [[1975 Australian federal election|1975 election]] mounted an unsuccessful campaign for the Senate as an [[Independent politician|independent]]. He later spent several years as a political commentator, retiring from public life in 1981.\n\n==Early life==\n===Birth and family background===\n[[File:JohnGorton1913.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton as a toddler in 1913]]\n[[File:NlaGortonmotherAlice1915.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton as a child and his mother Alice in 1915]]\nJohn Grey Gorton was the second child of Alice Sinn and John Rose Gorton; his older sister Ruth was born in 1909. He had no birth certificate, but on official forms recorded his date of birth as 9 September 1911 and his place of birth as [[Wellington]], New Zealand. His birth was registered in the state of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] as occurring on that date, but in the inner [[Melbourne]] suburb of [[Prahran, Victoria|Prahran]]. However, that document contained a number of inaccuracies \u2013 his name was given as \"John Alga Gordon\", his parents were recorded as husband and wife, his father's name was incorrect, and his sister was recorded as deceased.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ian Hancock|title=John Gorton: He Did It His Way|publisher=Hodder|year=2002|page=1|isbn=0733614396}}</ref> At some point, Gorton's father told him that he had actually been born in Wellington. There are no records of his birth in New Zealand, but his parents are known to have travelled there on several occasions.<ref name=p2>Hancock (2002), p. 2.</ref> John Gorton apparently believed he was born in Wellington, listing the city as his place of birth on his RAAF enlistment papers.<ref>[http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/before-office.aspx Before office - John Gorton], National Archives of Australia. Retrieved 6 November 2019.</ref> \n\nIf John Gorton was indeed born in New Zealand, this would have made him a New Zealand citizen from 1 January 1949 under changes to [[New Zealand nationality law]]. Holding dual-citizenship would have rendered Gorton ineligible to sit in Australia's federal parliament under [[Section 44 of the Australian Constitution]]. Gorton's eligibility to have sat in parliament throughout his career is therefore unclear.<ref>[https://williamsummers.blog/2017/08/07/section-44-twist-former-aussie-pm-was-probably-ineligible-for-parliament-due-to-multiple-citizenship/ Section 44 twist: Former Aussie PM was probably ineligible due to multiple citizenship], William Summers (blog). Retrieved 6 November 2019.</ref>\n\nGorton's father was born to a middle-class family in [[Manchester]], [[England]], UK. As a young man he moved to [[Johannesburg]], South Africa, where he went into business as a merchant \u2013 during the [[Second Boer War|Boer War]], he developed a reputation as a [[War profiteering|war profiteer]]. He reputedly escaped the [[Siege of Ladysmith]] by sneaking through Boer lines, and then made his way to Australia.<ref name=p3>Hancock (2002), p. 3.</ref> He was involved in various business schemes in multiple states, and was to said to have \"lived on the brink of a fortune which never quite materialised\".<ref name=p4>Hancock (2002), p. 4.</ref> One of his business partners was the inventor [[George Julius]].<ref name=p3/> At some point, Gorton's father separated from his first wife, Kathleen O'Brien, and began living with Alice Sinn \u2013 born in Melbourne to a German father and an Irish mother.<ref name=p2/> However, Kathleen refused to grant him a divorce. Some official documents record Gorton's parents as having married in New Zealand at some point, but there are no records of this occurring; any such marriage would have been bigamous. Gorton never denied his illegitimacy as an adult, but it did not become generally known until a biography was published during his premiership.<ref name=p4/>\n\n===Childhood===\n[[File:JohnGorton1930.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton as a student at Geelong Grammar School in 1930; he is seated to the left]]\nGorton spent his early years living with his maternal grandparents in [[Port Melbourne, Victoria|Port Melbourne]], as his parents were frequently away on business trips. When he was about four years old, his parents took him to live with them in Sydney, where they had an apartment at [[Edgecliff, New South Wales|Edgecliff]]. Gorton began his education at Edgecliff Preparatory School.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 5.</ref> When he was eight years old, his mother contracted tuberculosis and was sent to a [[sanatorium]] to avoid passing on the disease. She died in September 1920, aged 32. Gorton's grieving father sent his son to live with his estranged wife Kathleen. There, he met his sister Ruth for the first time; he had previously been told that she was dead. Although she was his full sibling, she had been raised by Kathleen since birth, and rarely saw her biological parents. Gorton initially lived with Kathleen and Ruth at their home in [[Cronulla, New South Wales|Cronulla]]. They later moved into a larger house in [[Killara, New South Wales|Killara]], in the north of Sydney.<ref name=hp8>Hancock (2002), p. 8.</ref>\n\nWhile living in Killara, Gorton began attending Headfort College, a short-lived private school run by a former Anglican minister.<ref name=hp8/> In 1924, he began boarding at [[Sydney Church of England Grammar School]] (Shore), initially on a weekly basis but later on a full-time one.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 9.</ref> He did not excel academically, failing the [[Intermediate Certificate (Australia)|Intermediate Certificate]] on his first attempt, but was a well-liked boy and good at sports.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 10.</ref> Gorton began spending his holidays with his father, who had purchased a property in [[Mystic Park, Victoria]], and planted a citrus orchard.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 11.</ref> He left Shore at the end of 1926, and the following year began boarding at [[Geelong Grammar School]], which he would attend for four years from 1927\u201330.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 12.</ref> He represented the school in athletics, [[Australian rules football|football]], and rowing, and in his final year was a school prefect and house captain.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 15.</ref>\n\n===University===\nAfter leaving Geelong Grammar, Gorton spent a year working on his father's property in Mystic Park. His father then took out a second mortgage to allow him to travel to England and attend [[Oxford University]]. Gorton arrived in England in early-1932, and after a period at a \"cramming school\" passed the exam to enter [[Brasenose College, Oxford|Brasenose College]]. He also took flying lessons around the same time, and was awarded a pilot's licence in June 1932. Gorton began his degree in October 1932 and finished in June 1935 with an \"[[Upper-second class|upper second]]\" in History, Politics, and Economics. He was initially something of an outsider, with relatively little money and no social connections. However, his prowess in rowing \u2013 he won the O.U.B.C. Fours in his first year, and was Captain of the [[Brasenose College Boat Club]] \u2013 saw him elected to [[Vincent's Club]] and [[Leander Club]]. In 1934, while on holiday in [[Second Spanish Republic|Spain]], he met his future wife [[Bettina Gorton|Bettina Brown]], the younger sister of one of his College friends. They married in early 1935.<ref name=bdas>[http://biography.senate.gov.au/gorton-john-grey GORTON, SIR JOHN GREY (1911\u20132002)], Biographical Dictionary of the Australian Senate (Online Edition). Retrieved 12 March 2018.</ref>\n\n===Return to Australia===\nAfter his graduation, Gorton and his wife returned to Australia via the [[United States]], spending some time with her family in [[Maine]]. He had expected to take up a position at [[The Herald and Weekly Times]], [[Keith Murdoch]]'s newspaper group. However, he arrived in Melbourne to find his father in failing health; he died in August 1936. Gorton had taken over the management of his father's orchard as soon as he entered hospital. He inherited an overdraft of \u00a35,000, which took several years to pay off. However, the property \u2013 located on the western side of [[North Victorian Wetlands|Kangaroo Lake]] \u2013 was in good condition, requiring only minor improvements. He employed up to ten seasonal workers during picking season. Mystic Park remained his primary residence until he was appointed to the ministry, at which point he and his family moved to Canberra.<ref name=bdas/>\n\n==Military service==\n\n===1940\u20131942===\n[[File:JohnGortonWW21941.jpg|thumb|left|Pilot Officer Gorton]]\n[[File:JohnGorton1941.jpg|thumb|right|Gorton prior to leaving for war service in 1941]]\nOn 31 May 1940, following the outbreak of World War II, Gorton enlisted in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] Reserve.<ref>Hancock: 30</ref> At the age of 29, Gorton was considered too old for pilot training, but he re-applied in September after this rule was relaxed. Gorton was accepted and commissioned into the RAAF on 8 November 1940.<ref>Hancock: 31</ref> He trained as a fighter pilot at [[Somers, Victoria]] and [[Wagga Wagga]], [[New South Wales]], before being sent to the UK. Gorton completed his training at [[RAF Heston]] and [[RAF Honiley]],<ref name=\"Trengrove: 71\">Trengrove: 71</ref> with [[No. 61 Operational Training Unit RAF]], flying [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s.<ref name=\"Hancock: 33\">Hancock: 33</ref> He was disappointed when his first operational posting was [[No. 135 Squadron RAF]], a [[Hawker Hurricane]] unit, as he considered the type greatly inferior to Spitfires.<ref name=\"Trengrove: 71\"/>\n\nDuring late 1941, Gorton and other members of his squadron became part of the [[En cadre|cadre]] of a Hurricane [[wing (air force unit)|wing]] being formed for service in the Middle East. They were sent by sea, with 50 Hurricanes in crates, travelling around Africa to reduce the risk of attack. In December, when the ship was at [[Durban]], South Africa, it was diverted to Singapore, after [[Pacific War|Japan entered the war]].<ref>Trengrove: 72</ref> As it approached its destination in mid-January, [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] forces were [[Battle of Malaya|advancing down the Malayan Peninsula]]. The ship was attacked on at least one occasion by Japanese aircraft, but arrived and unloaded safely after tropical storms made enemy air raids impossible.<ref>Trengrove: 73\u201374</ref> As the Hurricanes were assembled, the pilots were formed into a composite operational squadron, [[No. 232 Squadron RAF]].\n\nIn late January 1942, the squadron became operational and joined the remnants of several others that had been in Malaya, operating out of [[Seletar Airport|RAF Seletar]] and RAF [[Kallang]].<ref>Trengrove: 75</ref> During one of his first [[sortie]]s, Gorton was involved in a brief dogfight over the [[South China Sea]], after which he suffered engine failure and was forced to land on [[Bintan]] island,<ref name=\"Hancock: 33\"/> 40&nbsp;km (25&nbsp;mi) south east of Singapore. As he landed, one of the Hurricane's wheels hit an embankment and flipped over. Gorton was not properly strapped in and his face hit the gun sight and windscreen, mutilating his nose and breaking both cheekbones.<ref name=\"Trengrove: 76\">Trengrove: 76</ref> He also suffered severe lacerations to both arms. He made his way out of the wreck and was rescued by members of the [[Royal Dutch East Indies Army]], who provided some medical treatment. Gorton later claimed that his face was so badly cut and bruised, that a member of the RAF sent to collect him assumed he was near death, collected his personal effects and returned to Singapore without him.<ref name=\"Trengrove: 76\"/> By chance, one week later, Sgt Matt O'Mara of [[No. 453 Squadron RAAF]] also crash landed on Bintan, and arranged for them to be collected.<ref name=\"Trengrove: 77\">Trengrove: 77</ref>\n\nThey arrived back in Singapore, on 11 February, three days after [[battle of Singapore|the island had been invaded]].<ref name=\"Trengrove: 77\"/> As the Allied air force units on Singapore had been destroyed or evacuated by this stage, Gorton was put on the ''Derrymore'', an ammunition ship bound for [[Jakarta|Batavia]] (Jakarta). On 13 February, as it neared its destination, the ship was torpedoed by Japanese submarine I-55 [[Kaidai class submarine]] and the ''Derrymore'' was abandoned. Gorton then spent almost a day on a crowded liferaft, in shark-infested waters, with little drinking water, until the raft was spotted by [[HMAS Ballarat (J184)|HMAS ''Ballarat'']], which picked up the passengers and took them to Batavia.<ref>Trengrove: 80</ref>\n\n[[File:77_Sqn_RAAF_pilots_%26_Kittyhawk_(AWM_NWA0019).JPG|thumb|left|Pilots of B Flight, No. 77 Squadron with a P-40 Kittyhawk in the Northern Territory, January 1943. Gorton is fourth left in the back row.]]\nTwo schoolfriends, who had also been evacuated from Singapore to Batavia, heard that Gorton was in hospital, arranged for them to be put on a ship for [[Fremantle]], which left on 23 February and treated Gorton's wounds.<ref>Trengrove: 81</ref> When the ship arrived in Fremantle, on 3 March, one of Gorton's arm wounds had become septic and needed extensive treatment. However, he was more concerned about the effect that the sight of his mutilated face would have on his wife. It is reported that Betty Gorton, who had been running the farm in his absence, was relieved to see Gorton alive.<ref name=\"Hancock: 33\"/><ref>Trengrove: 82</ref>\n\n===1942\u20131944===\n\nAfter arriving in Australia he was posted to [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] on 12 August 1942 with [[No. 77 Squadron RAAF]] (Kittyhawks). During this time he was involved in his second air accident.  While flying [[P-40E]] A29-60 on 7 September 1942, he was forced to land due to an incorrectly set fuel cock. Both Gorton and his aircraft were recovered several days later after spending time in the bush. On 21 February 1943 the squadron was relocated to [[Milne Bay]], [[New Guinea]].<ref name=naaws>{{cite web|url=http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/before-office.aspx#section2 |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |title=John Gorton, Before office, War service 1940\u201345 | accessdate= 24 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nGorton's final air incident came on 18 March 1943. His A29-192 Kittyhawk's engine failed on takeoff, causing the aircraft to flip at the end of the strip. Gorton was unhurt. In March 1944, Gorton was sent back to Australia with the rank of Flight Lieutenant. His final posting was as a Flying Instructor with [[No. 2 Operational Conversion Unit RAAF|No. 2 Operational Training Unit]] at [[Mildura]], Victoria.  He was then discharged from the RAAF on 5 December 1944.<ref name=naaws/>\n\nDuring late 1944 Gorton went to [[Austin Hospital, Melbourne|Heidelberg Hospital]] for surgery which could not fully repair his facial injuries; he was left permanently disfigured.<ref name=naaws/>\n\n==Early political involvement==\nAfter resuming his life in Mystic Park, Gorton was elected unopposed to the [[Shire of Kerang|Kerang Shire Council]] in September 1946. He remained on the council until 1952, overlapping with his first term in the Senate, and from 1949 to 1950 served as shire president.<ref name=p46>Hancock (2002), p. 46.</ref> Although he had little previous experience, Gorton began to develop a reputation as a powerful public speaker. His first major speech, in April 1946, was an address to a welcome-home gathering for returned soldiers at the Mystic Park Hall. In what [[John Brogden (politician)|John Brogden]] has described as \"Australia's best unknown political speech\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/opinion/when-heartfelt-oratory-gave-us-a-political-vision-to-believe-in/news-story/f6e976b88facb7aef45be610e8025547|title=When heartfelt oratory gave us a political vision to believe in|author=[[John Brogden (politician)|John Brogden]]|date=1 July 2016|access-date=21 September 2018|work=[[The Australian]]}}</ref> he exhorted his audience to honour those who had died in the war by building \"a world in which meanness and poverty, tyranny and hate, have no existence\". Gorton's next major speech was made in September 1947, at a rally against the [[Chifley Government]]'s attempt to nationalise private banks. He told the crowd in [[Kerang]] that they should oppose the establishment of banks run by politicians, and objected in particular to the government's decision not to take the issue to a referendum.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 49.</ref> According to his biographer Ian Hancock, \"the bank nationalisation issue marked his advance beyond purely local politics and stamped him firmly and publicly as an anti-socialist\".<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 51.</ref>\n\nGorton had been a supporter of the [[Country Party (Victoria)|Country Party]] before the war, along with most of his neighbours. Over time, he became frustrated with the party's frequent squabbles with the [[Liberal Party of Australia (Victorian Division)|Liberal Party]] and its willingness to cooperate with the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]].<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 52.</ref> After the Victorian Country Party withdrew from [[Coalition (Australia)|its coalition]] with the Liberals in December 1948, Gorton became involved in efforts to form a new anti-socialist movement that would absorb both parties. At some point he was introduced to [[Magnus Cormack]], the state president of the Liberals, who became something of a mentor.<ref name=p53>Hancock (2002), pp. 53\u201354.</ref> In March 1949, Gorton was elected to the state executive of the new organisation, which named itself the [[Liberal and Country Party]] (LCP).<ref name=p55>Hancock (2002), p. 55.</ref> On a number of occasions he addressed Country Party gatherings, urging its members to join the new party and stressing that it would not neglect rural interests, as many feared.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 56.</ref> However, the LCP did not achieve its goal of uniting the anti-Labor forces, as most Country Party members viewed it as simply a takeover attempt; the new party affiliated with the federal [[Liberal Party of Australia]].<ref name=p53/>\n\nIn June 1949, Gorton stood for the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] as the LCP candidate in [[Northern Province (Victoria)|Northern Province]]. It was a safe Country Party seat, and at the preceding three elections no other parties had bothered to field a candidate.<ref name=p55/> Making right-wing unity the focal point of his campaign, Gorton polled 48.8 percent of the vote to finish less than 400 votes behind the sitting member, [[George Tuckett (politician)|George Tuckett]]. The result impressed the LCP's leadership,<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 57.</ref> and the following month he was [[preselection|preselected]] in third place on its joint [[Australian Senate|Senate]] ticket with the Country Party. He was relatively unknown within the party, and his rural background was a major factor in his selection.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 58.</ref> The Coalition won a large majority at the [[1949 Australian federal election|1949 federal election]], including four out of Victoria's seven senators. The LCP candidates joined the parliamentary Liberal Party.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 59.</ref>\n\n==Senate (1950\u20131968)==\n===Backbencher===\n[[File:JohnGorton1954.JPG|thumb|left|Gorton in 1954]]\nGorton's term in the Senate began on 22 February 1950.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=61}} He was re-elected to additional terms at the [[1951 Australian federal election|1951]], [[1953 Australian Senate election|1953]], [[1958 Australian federal election|1958]], and [[1964 Australian Senate election|1964 elections]], and from 1953 occupied first place on the Coalition's ticket in Victoria. Gorton's early speeches on domestic policy foreshadowed the stances and policy initiatives he would later adopt as prime minister, such as economic nationalism, support for a strong central government, and support for nuclear energy. One of his first notable actions in the Senate came in November 1951, when he successfully moved a motion opposing \"any substantial measure of ownership or control over any Australian broadcasting station\" being granted to non-Australians.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=73}} In his early speeches on foreign policy, Gorton drew analogies between the actions of the Soviet Union and Communist China and those of Nazi Germany.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=68}} He developed a reputation as a \"hardline [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]]\", speaking in favour of the Communist Party Dissolution Bill and campaigning for the \"Yes\" vote during the [[1951 Australian Communist Party ban referendum|1951 referendum]] to ban the [[Communist Party of Australia|Communist Party]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=64\u201366}} At a campaign rally in September 1951, he had to be restrained by police after attempting to drag a heckler from his seat and shouting at him to \"come outside, you yellow rat\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/23077920|title=Women rush from hall|publisher=[[Melbourne Argus]]|date=5 September 1951}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1952 to 1958, Gorton served on the Joint Parliamentary Committee on Foreign Affairs, including as chairman for a period. He developed a keen interest in Asia, which was rooted in his anti-communism, and joined parliamentary delegations to Malaya, South Vietnam, Thailand, and the Philippines. He strongly supported Australia joining the [[Southeast Asia Treaty Organisation]] (SEATO), a collective defence initiative designed to [[domino theory|prevent the spread of communism]] in the region. He also supported [[Taiwanese independence]] and opposed Australian recognition of the People's Republic of China (PRC).{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=67}} On a number of occasions, Gorton spoke of the need for Australia to develop a foreign policy independent of Britain and the United States.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=68}} In May 1957, he told the Senate that Australia should acquire its own nuclear deterrent, including intercontinental missiles.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=69}}\n\n===Government minister===\n====Navy====\n[[File:Paul Hasluck, Shen Chang-huan, John Gorton.jpg|thumb|right|Gorton in 1965 with External Affairs Minister [[Paul Hasluck]] and Taiwanese foreign minister [[Shen Chang-huan]]]]\nGorton was elevated to the ministry after the [[1958 Australian federal election|1958 election]], as [[Minister for the Navy (Australia)|Minister for the Navy]]. This was a junior position subordinate to the Minister for Defence, [[Athol Townley]]. Although his promotion was unexpected,{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=81}} he would serve as Minister for the Navy for more than five years, the longest-serving navy minister in Australia's history.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=96}} Gorton regularly attended meetings of the [[Australian Commonwealth Naval Board|Naval Board]], unlike previous ministers, and championed its recommendations at cabinet meetings. He was able to secure most elements of the board's desired modernisation program, despite Townley showing more interest in the air force. During Gorton's tenure, the navy acquired four Australian-built frigates and six British-built minesweepers, as well as placing orders for three [[Charles F. Adams-class destroyer|''Charles F. Adams''-class destroyer]]s and four [[Oberon-class submarine|''Oberon''-class submarine]]s. He postponed the phasing out of the [[Fleet Air Arm (RAN)|Fleet Air Arm]], due to occur in 1963, and secured the purchase of 27 [[Westland Wessex]] helicopters.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=87\u201390}}\n\nGorton was a supporter and admirer of Robert Menzies, who was sympathetic to his ambitions for higher office and assigned him additional responsibilities. In 1959, he was tasked with securing the passage of the Matrimonial Causes Bill, which introduced uniform divorce laws; he described it as \"a systematic attempt to make a new approach to the problem of divorce\". The bill was opposed by religious conservatives (mostly Catholics) on both sides of politics, but it eventually passed the Senate with only a single amendment.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=85\u201386}} Gorton was appointed assistant minister to the [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Australia)|Minister for External Affairs]] in February 1960, working under Menzies and later under [[Garfield Barwick]] and [[Paul Hasluck]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=84}} In February 1962, he was also made minister-in-charge of the [[CSIRO]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=96}} During [[question time]] in the Senate, he represented ministers from the House of Representatives, allowing him to gain experience in portfolios beyond his own.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=84}}{{efn|In Australia, ministers are drawn from both the House of Representatives and the Senate. To allow the Opposition to ask questions about all governmental actions in both houses, some ministers assume responsibility for portfolios held by ministers from the other chamber.}}\n\n====Education and science====\n[[File:John Gorton, Fred White, Ren\u00e9 Maheu.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton with CSIRO chairman [[Fred White (scientist)|Fred White]] and UNESCO Director-General [[Ren\u00e9 Maheu]] at a regional science organisation meeting in 1964]]\nAfter the [[1963 Australian federal election|1963 election]], Gorton relinquished the navy portfolio and was placed in charge of the government's activities in education and scientific research.{{efn|His formal title was \"Minister in charge of Commonwealth Activities in Education and Research under the Prime Minister\".{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=103}}}} He was also made [[Department of Works (1952\u201373)|Minister for Works]] and [[Department of the Interior (1939\u201372)|Minister for the Interior]], relatively low-profile positions dealing mostly with administrative matters; the latter post was taken over by [[Doug Anthony]] after a few months. Menzies had a personal interest in education, having previously handled the portfolio himself,{{efn|There was no separate education department at the time, with the portfolio instead handled by the Commonwealth Education Office within the [[Prime Minister's Department (Australia)|Prime Minister's Department]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=104}}}} and told Gorton that it should be his primary focus.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=103}} He was given oversight of the Australian Universities Commission, the [[Australian National University]], the [[National Archives of Australia|Commonwealth Archives Office]], the [[Commonwealth Literary Fund]], and the [[National Library of Australia]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=104}} In January 1966, Menzies retired and [[Harold Holt]] became prime minister. Gorton was elevated to [[Cabinet of Australia|cabinet]],{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=100}} and at the end of the year was given the title [[Minister for Education (Australia)|Minister for Education and Science]]. He was placed in charge of the new [[Department of Education and Science (Australia)|Department of Education and Science]], the first time those portfolios had been given a separate department at federal level.<ref>{{cite book|first=Tom|last=Frame| authorlink=Tom Frame (bishop)|title=The Life and Death of Harold Holt|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=2005|isbn=1-74114-672-0|page=168}}</ref>\n\n[[File:JohnGorton.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Senator Gorton in 1967]]\nGorton presided over a \"major intrusion\" of the federal government into the education sector.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=121}} His tenure saw significant increases in the number of university scholarships available, the number of new university entrants, and overall funding of education.{{efn|Between 1963 and 1966, the number of Commonwealth scholarships on offer rose from 4,701 to 8,069, an increase of 72 percent, while the number of new university entrants rose from 17,311 to 24,196, an increase of 40 percent. Total federal funding of education rose by 77 percent from the 1964\u201365 budget to the 1967\u201368 budget.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=121\u2013122}}}} One of the first major issues Gorton confronted was that of state aid to non-government schools. He believed that private schools should have equal access to federal government funding, and in 1964 announced that the government would fund science laboratories for private schools.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=109\u2013111}} This stance, supported by the [[Catholic education in Australia|Catholic education sector]] but opposed by secularists and most Protestant schools, eventually achieved widespread acceptance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_Departments/Parliamentary_Library/Publications_Archive/CIB/CIB9697/97cib2|title=State Aid for Non-Government Schools: The emerging debate|first=Greg|last=McIntosh|year=1996|publisher=Australian Parliamentary Library}}</ref> In September 1965, Gorton created the Commonwealth Advisory Committee on Advanced Education, tasked with advising the government on non-university [[technical and further education]] (TAFE). He announced that the federal government would fund technical colleges on a pro-rata basis with the states,{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=111\u2013112}} and personally oversaw the establishment of the Canberra College of Advanced Education, the forerunner of the [[University of Canberra]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=114\u2013115}} As science minister, he lent his support to the [[Anglo-Australian Telescope]] project, securing cabinet approval for its construction in April 1967.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=120\u2013121}}\n\n==Prime Minister==\n===Holt's disappearance===\n{{See also|Disappearance of Harold Holt|Liberal Party of Australia leadership election, 1968}}\n[[File:John_Gorton_Swearing_In.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton being sworn in as Prime Minister on 10 January 1968.]]\n[[Harold Holt]] disappeared while swimming on 17 December 1967 and was declared presumed drowned two days later. His presumed successor was Liberal deputy leader [[William McMahon]].  However, on 18 December, the Country Party leader and Deputy Prime Minister [[John McEwen]] announced that if McMahon were named the new Liberal leader, he and his party would not serve under him.  His reasons were never stated publicly, but in a private meeting with McMahon, he said \"I will not serve under you because I do not trust you\".<ref>Gavin Souter, ''Acts of Parliament'', 1988, pp. 478\u201379</ref> McEwen's shock declaration triggered a leadership crisis within the Liberal Party; even more significantly, it raised the threat of a possible breaking of the Coalition, which would spell electoral disaster for the Liberals.  Up to that time, the Liberals had never won enough seats in any House of Representatives election to be able to govern without Country Party support.  Indeed, since the Coalition's formation in 1923, the major non-[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] party had only been able to govern alone once, during [[Joseph Lyons]]' first ministry. Even then, Lyons' [[United Australia Party]] had come up four seats short of a majority in its own right, and was only able to garner a bare majority of two when the five members of the [[Emergency Committee of South Australia]] joined the UAP party room.\n\nThe Governor-General [[Richard Casey, Baron Casey|Lord Casey]] swore McEwen in as Prime Minister, on an interim basis pending the Liberal Party electing its new leader. McEwen agreed to accept an interim appointment provided there was no formal statement of time limit. This appointment was in keeping with previous occasions when a conservative Coalition government had been deprived of its leader.<ref>In 1939 when [[Joseph Lyons]] died suddenly, and in 1941 when [[Robert Menzies]] resigned, the Governor-General had commissioned the (unofficial) Deputy Prime Minister, who was the leader of the Country Party, to serve as Prime Minister until the major coalition partner\u2014then the UAP\u2014could choose its new leader.</ref> Casey also concurred in the view put to him by McEwen that to commission a Liberal temporarily as Prime Minister would give that person an unfair advantage in the forthcoming party room ballot for the permanent leader.\n[[File:John_Gorton_1968_colour.jpg|thumb|right|Gorton in his office in 1968.]]\nIn the subsequent [[1968 Liberal Party of Australia leadership election|leadership struggle]], Gorton was championed by Army Minister [[Malcolm Fraser]], Government Whip in the Senate [[Malcolm Scott]] and Liberal Party Whip [[Dudley Erwin]], and with their support he was able to defeat rivals [[Paul Hasluck]], [[Les Bury]] and [[Billy Snedden]] to become Liberal leader even though he was a member of the Senate.  He was elected party leader on 9 January 1968, and appointed Prime Minister on 10 January, replacing McEwen.  He was the only Senator in Australia's history to be Prime Minister and the only Prime Minister to have ever served in the Senate.  He remained a Senator until, in accordance with the [[Westminster system|Westminster]] tradition that the Prime Minister is a member of the lower house of parliament, he resigned on 1 February 1968 to contest the by-election for Holt's old House of Representatives seat of [[Division of Higgins|Higgins]] in south Melbourne.  The by-election in this comfortably safe Liberal seat was held on 24 February; there were three other candidates, but Gorton achieved a massive 68% of the formal vote.  He visited all the polling booths during the day, but was unable to vote for himself as he was still enrolled in [[Division of Mallee|Mallee]], in rural western Victoria.<ref>''the age(melbourne)magazine'', p. 16</ref> Between 2 and 23 February (both dates inclusive) he was a member of neither house of parliament.\n\n===Activities in office===\n[[File:John Gorton 1969.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton at the [[Honeysuckle Creek Tracking Station]] during the [[Apollo 11]] moon landing in 1969]]\nGorton was initially a very popular Prime Minister. He carved out a style quite distinct from those of his predecessors \u2013 the aloof Menzies and the affable, sporty Holt. Gorton liked to portray himself as a man of the people who enjoyed a beer and a gamble, with a bit of a [[larrikinism|\"larrikin\"]] streak about him. Unfortunately for him, this reputation later came back to haunt him.\n\nHe also began to follow new policies, pursuing independent defence and foreign policies and distancing Australia from its traditional ties to Britain. But he continued to support Australia's involvement in the [[Vietnam War]], a position he had reluctantly inherited from Holt, which became increasingly unpopular after 1968. On domestic issues, he favoured centralist policies at the expense of the states, which alienated powerful Liberal state leaders like Sir [[Henry Bolte]] of Victoria and [[Robert Askin|Bob Askin]] of New South Wales. He also fostered an independent [[Australian film industry]] and increased government funding for the arts.\nGorton proved to be a surprisingly poor media performer and public speaker, and was portrayed by the media as a foolish and incompetent administrator. He was unlucky to come up against a new and formidable Labor Opposition Leader in [[Gough Whitlam]]. Also, he was subjected to media speculation about his drinking habits and his involvements with women. He generated great resentment within his party, and his opponents became increasingly critical of his reliance on an inner circle of advisers \u2013 most notably his private secretary [[Ainsley Gotto]].\n\nThe Coalition suffered a 7% swing against it at the [[1969 Australian federal election|1969 election]], and Labor outpolled it on the [[two-party-preferred vote]]. During the close election Gorton promised to waive all future government rent on residential leaseholders in Canberra.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hong|first1=Yu-Hung|title=Myths and Realities of Public Land Leasing: Canberra and Hong Kong|journal=Land Lines|date=March 1999|volume=11|issue=2|url=https://www.lincolninst.edu/pubs/dl/361_linc_landlines%203.99.pdf|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> After surviving the election Gorton came through on his promise, giving away an estimated $100&nbsp;million in equity to leaseholders and abandoning future government rent revenue.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fitzgerald|first1=Karl|title=Canberra's Leasehold Land System|url=http://www.prosper.org.au/2008/01/16/canberra/|website=Prosper Australia|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> Still, Gorton saw the sizeable 45-seat majority he had inherited from Holt cut down to only seven.  Indeed, the Coalition might have lost government had it not been for the [[Democratic Labor Party (historical)|Democratic Labor Party]]'s longstanding practice of preferencing against the ALP.  The Coalition was only assured of a ninth term in government when DLP preferences tipped four marginal seats in Melbourne \u2014the DLP's heartland\u2014to the Liberals.  Had those preferences gone the other way, Whitlam would have become Prime Minister.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/elections/federal/2007/results/senate/vic.htm Analysis of 2007 election in Victoria] by [[Antony Green]]</ref>\n\n===Leadership challenges and resignation===\n[[File:Gorton_and_McMahon.jpg|thumb|Gorton with [[William McMahon]] shortly after the unsuccessful leadership challenge in 1969.]]\nAfter the 1969 election, Gorton [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, 1969|was unsuccessfully challenged for the Liberal leadership]] by McMahon and National Development Minister [[David Fairbairn (politician)|David Fairbairn]]. With the Liberals falling further behind Labor in the polls in 1971, a challenge was launched in March when Defence Minister [[Malcolm Fraser]] resigned.  Fraser had strongly supported Gorton for the leadership two years earlier, but now attacked Gorton on the floor of parliament in his resignation speech, saying that Gorton was \"not fit to hold the great office of Prime Minister.\"\n\nGorton called [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, 1971|a Liberal caucus meeting]] for 10 March 1971 to settle the matter. A motion of confidence in his leadership was tied. Under Liberal caucus rules of the time, a tied vote meant the motion was passed and hence Gorton could have remained as party leader and Prime Minister without further ado.  However, he took it upon himself to resign, saying \"Well, that is not a vote of confidence, so the party will have to elect a new leader.\"<ref>Neil Brown, ''On the Other Hand ... Sketches and Reflections from Political Life'', The Popular Press, 1993, p. 59</ref> A ballot was held and McMahon was elected leader and thus Prime Minister. Australian television marked the end of Gorton's stormy premiership with a newsreel montage accompanied by [[Frank Sinatra|Sinatra's]] anthem \"[[My Way (song)|My Way]]\".\n\nIn a surprise move, Gorton contested and won the position of Deputy Leader, forcing McMahon to make him Defence Minister. This farcical situation ended within five months when McMahon sacked him for disloyalty.\n\n==Final years in parliament==\n[[File:President Nixon meeting with the Hon.Jack G Gorton - NARA - 194715.tif|thumb|left|Gorton meeting with U.S. President [[Richard Nixon]] and [[Alexander Haig]] in April 1971]]\nA number of polls during McMahon's prime ministership had Gorton as both the preferred Liberal leader and the preferred prime minister. In 1972, businessman [[David Hains]] commissioned a series of polls in marginal electorates that showed the Coalition would significantly increase its vote if Gorton mounted a successful comeback; for instance, polling in the [[Division of Henty]] found that his return would add eight points to the Liberal vote. However, Gorton generally downplayed the polling and did not mount an active campaign to oust McMahon.<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 362\u2013363.</ref> Labor went on to win a nine-seat majority at the [[1972 Australian federal election|1972 election]], ending 23 consecutive years of Coalition rule.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 364.</ref> A number of Gorton's contemporaries \u2013 including Country Party leader [[Doug Anthony]] and Labor ministers [[Clyde Cameron]], [[Doug McClelland]], and [[John Wheeldon]] \u2013 retrospectively expressed doubts as to whether Whitlam could have won if Gorton had returned to the prime ministership. [[Rupert Murdoch]], whose newspapers endorsed the Labor Party, stated in 2000 that \"we would most certainly have supported the re-election of a Gorton Government in 1972. And he would have won!\".<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 365.</ref>\n\nMcMahon resigned as Liberal leader a few weeks after the 1972 election. Gorton was one of five candidates who stood [[1972 Liberal Party of Australia leadership election|the resulting leadership ballot]], but polled only the fourth-highest total as [[Billy Snedden]] won a narrow victory over [[Nigel Bowen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110626409|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=21 December 1972|title=Snedden faces his first problems}}</ref> Snedden subsequently appointed him to the opposition frontbench as spokesman for urban and regional development, the environment, and conservation.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=30 January 1973|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110704896|title=Snedden names 'Shadow' team}}</ref> Soon after being sworn in as prime minister, Whitlam responded to a congratulatory letter from Gorton by promising to \"advance some of the causes which you were the first Australian Prime Minister to identify\". Over the following years, several failed initiatives from Gorton's prime ministership were passed into law by the [[Whitlam Government]]. This included the establishment of the [[Australian Film, Television and Radio School]] and the assertion of sovereignty over the territorial seabed and continental shelf.<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 366\u2013367.</ref>\n\n===Social liberalism===\nEarly in 1973, Gorton stated his public support of \"abortion on request, under certain conditions\"; he was opposed to \"compulsory pregnancy\". He nonetheless voted against [[David McKenzie (Victorian politician)|David McKenzie]] and [[Tony Lamb]]'s private member's bill to legalise abortion in the Australian Capital Territory, as he believed it did not provide clear enough guidelines for medical practitioners. He preferred the conditions of the [[Menhennitt ruling]].<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 367\u2013368.</ref> Gorton was also a supporter of no-fault divorce. During the debate over what became the ''[[Family Law Act 1975]]'', he [[cross the floor|crossed the floor]] to oppose a Coalition amendment which he thought complicated the requirements for divorce through separation.<ref name=p377>Hancock (2002), p. 377.</ref>\n\nIn October 1973, Gorton introduced a motion in the House of Representatives calling for the [[LGBT rights in Australia|decriminalisation of homosexuality]], co-sponsored by Labor's [[Moss Cass]]. It was modelled on the recommendations of the UK's [[Wolfenden report]]. While noting his personal objections to homosexuality, Gorton stated that most gay people \"hurt no one, harm no one and yet have this hanging over them\". He dismissed arguments that decriminalisation would violate \"God's law\", noting that many religious leaders were in favour of a change, and stated that the existing law had led to \"[[Gay bashing|bashing]]\", blackmail, and suicides. The motion passed by 24 votes, with all parties receiving a [[conscience vote]]. However, it was of no legal effect as homosexuality law was the province of state laws and territory ordinances.<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 368\u2013369.</ref><ref>[http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/genpdf/hansard80/hansardr80/1973-10-18/0029/hansard_frag.pdf;fileType=application%2Fpdf HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES HOMOSEXUALITY SPEECH], Hansard, 18 October 1973.</ref>\n\n===Resignation from the Liberal Party===\nGorton was re-elected at the [[1974 Australian federal election|1974 election]] with an increased majority.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 371.</ref> He was dropped from shadow cabinet after the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110783471|title=Old line-up changed|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=15 June 1974}}</ref> In November 1974, following an unsuccessful attempt to install [[Malcolm Fraser]] as Liberal leader, he condemned those involved and stated they had caused \"irreparable damage\" to the party.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 374.</ref> On 3 March 1975, as leadership tensions continued to build, Gorton announced that he would not recontest his seat in parliament at the next election, citing his unwillingness to be a perpetual backbencher. He also stated: \"If Fraser got in, it would be a disaster. He is extreme right-wing. The Liberal Party can't be a right-leaning affair.\"<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 376.</ref> When Fraser won [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, 1975|a leadership spill]] on 21 March, Gorton reportedly stormed out of the meeting and slammed the door behind him.<ref name=p377/>\n\nOn 23 May 1975, Gorton announced his resignation from the Liberal Party and his intention to be an independent candidate for one of the new [[Australian Capital Territory]] (ACT) Senate seats. He hoped to join [[Steele Hall]] on the [[crossbench]] and secure the [[Balance of power (parliament)|balance of power]].<ref name=p377/> Opinion polling shortly after his announcement showed him winning 55 percent of the primary vote. His candidacy received endorsements from the small local branches of the [[Liberal Movement (Australia)|Liberal Movement]] and the [[Australia Party]].<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 379.</ref> Gough Whitlam was dismissed as prime minister on 11 November, sparking [[1975 Australian federal election|an early election]] on 13 December. During [[1975 Australian constitutional crisis|the preceding constitutional crisis]], Gorton had denounced Fraser's actions in blocking [[Supply (political science)|supply]] in the Senate.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 380.</ref> In the election, he polled 11.9 percent of the ACT Senate vote running on a two-man ticket with [[Harold Hird]]. It was the second-highest percentage for an independent candidate nation-wide, after [[Brian Harradine]]'s 12.8 percent in Tasmania, but nowhere near enough to win election. He had campaigned mainly on local issues, which obscured his candidacy somewhat in an election that was a virtual referendum on the Whitlam Government.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 381.</ref>\n\n==Retirement and death==\n[[File:Grave_of_John_Gorton,_Melbourne_General_Cemetery.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Grave of Sir John within the 'Prime Ministers Garden' at [[Melbourne General Cemetery]]]]\nGorton retired to [[Canberra]], where he largely kept out of the political limelight. However, in March 1983, he congratulated [[Bob Hawke]] \"for rolling that bastard Fraser\" at [[1983 Australian federal election|that year's election]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Macinnis|first=Peter|title=The Big Book of Australian History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfGLAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=National Library Australia|isbn=978-0-642-27832-6|page=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=VfGLAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA221 221]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, Gorton was recruited to record a series of three-minute radio broadcasts on current affairs, titled \"Sir John Gorton's viewpoints\". He wrote and recorded around 400 segments over the following four years, which were syndicated and broadcast by over 80 radio stations around the country. His broadcasts covered a wide range of issues \u2013 he supported the decriminalisation of marijuana and prostitution, called on Australians to welcome [[Vietnamese boat people]], opposed the creation of [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]], denounced \"the cacophony known as modern music\", opposed Aboriginal land rights, supported uranium mining, and opposed [[Republicanism in Australia|republicanism]]. He frequently criticised the [[Fraser Government]], but grudgingly admired Fraser's ability to get his way as prime minister.<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 384\u2013389.</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, Gorton quietly rejoined the Liberal Party; [[John Hewson]] credited himself with \"returning Gorton to the fold.\"<ref>ABC TV \"Midday Report\", Interview w. J Hewson, 26 May 2010</ref> In 1993, Gorton was invited to open the Liberal Party's campaign headquarters for the [[1993 Australian federal election|1993 election]]. He endorsed Hewson's [[Fightback! (policy)|Fightback!]] package.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/126976611|title=Gorton returns, hankering for change|date=17 February 1993|work=[[The Canberra Times]]}}</ref> In his old age he was rehabilitated by the Liberals; his 90th birthday party was attended by Prime Minister [[John Howard]] who said at the event: \"He (Gorton) was a person who above everything else was first, second and last an Australian.\" Although he was back within Liberal circles, he never forgave Fraser; as late as 2002 he told his biographer Ian Hancock that he still could not tolerate being in the same room as Fraser.<ref>Cameron Stewart, ''Buried alive'', Weekend Australian, 16\u201317 March 2002</ref>\n\nGorton died at Sydney's [[St Vincent's Hospital, Sydney|St Vincent's Hospital]] at the age of 90 in May 2002.<ref>{{cite news|last=Murphy|first=Damien|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/20/1021801645667.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|title=Larrikin PM who sacked himself dies aged 90|date=20 May 2002|accessdate=14 February 2016}}</ref> A [[State funeral]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/international/2002-05-20/state-funeral-for-sir-john-gorton/620960|work=ABC Radio|title=State funeral for Sir John Gorton|date=20 May 2002|accessdate=14 February 2016}}</ref> and memorial service was held on 30 May at [[St Andrew's Cathedral, Sydney|St Andrews' Cathedral]] where extremely critical remarks of Fraser, who was in attendance with wife [[Tamie Fraser|Tamie]], were delivered during the eulogy by Gorton's former Attorney-General [[Tom Hughes (Australian politician)|Tom Hughes]]. Current and former Prime Ministers Howard, [[Gough Whitlam]] and [[Bob Hawke]] were also in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/31/1022569833464.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|title=Hughes's wintry blast for the undertaker PM|date=1 June 2002|accessdate=14 February 2016}}</ref> Gorton was cremated after a private service and his ashes interred within the 'Prime Ministers Garden' at [[Melbourne General Cemetery]].\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriages===\n[[File:Gortonsearly50's.jpg|thumb|left|John and [[Bettina Gorton]] c. 1968]]\nDuring a holiday in Spain while still an undergraduate, Gorton met [[Bettina Gorton|Bettina Brown]] of [[Bangor, Maine]], United States. She was a language student at the [[Sorbonne]]. This meeting came about through Gorton's friend from Oxford, Arthur Brown, who was Bettina's brother. In 1935, Gorton and Bettina Brown were married in Oxford. After his studies were finished, they settled in Australia, taking over his father's orchard, \"Mystic Park\", at [[Lake Kangaroo, Victoria|Lake Kangaroo]] near [[Kerang]], Victoria. They had three children: Joanna, Michael and Robin. Gorton's first wife died of cancer in 1983. In 1993, he remarried to Nancy Home (n\u00e9e Elliott) a long-time acquaintance.<ref name=naabg>{{cite web|url=http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/spouse.aspx|publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]]|title=Bettina Gorton|accessdate=24 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315145301/http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/spouse.aspx|archive-date=15 March 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Religious beliefs===\nGorton was a nominal Christian at least in the early part of his life, but was not a churchgoer. Some sources have identified him as agnostic or even atheist. He attended Anglican schools, and was influenced by the [[Christian socialist]] views of [[James Ralph Darling]], his headmaster at [[Geelong Grammar]].<ref>Williams, Roy (2013). ''In God They Trust?'', Bible Society Australia, p. 149.</ref> In a 1948 speech, Gorton said that \"the story of Christianity is the most tremendous in the history of the world\".<ref>Williams: 151.</ref> However, in the lead-up to the [[1999 Australian republic referendum|1999 referendum]] he publicly opposed mentioning God in the preamble. According to his biographer Ian Hancock: \"Gorton may not have been a believing, let alone a practising, Christian, and when he spoke of religion of 'the soul' he did not have a particular faith in mind. Rather, his religion was founded upon the injunction in the [[Book of Deuteronomy]]: 'Man doth not live by bread only'.\"<ref>Hancock: 107</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:John Gorton bust.jpg|thumb|Bust of John Gorton by sculptor Victor Greenhalgh located in the [[Prime Ministers Avenue]] in the Ballarat Botanical Gardens]]\nGorton was appointed a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] in 1968, a [[Order of the Companions of Honour|Companion of Honour]] in 1971,<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1065982&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526212251/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1065982&search_type=quick&showInd=true |date=26 May 2011 }} \u2013 Companion of Honour</ref> a Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] in 1977<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1073778&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526212331/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1073778&search_type=quick&showInd=true |date=26 May 2011 }} \u2013 Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George</ref> and a Companion of the [[Order of Australia]] in 1988.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=884482&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526212339/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=884482&search_type=quick&showInd=true |date=26 May 2011 }} \u2013 Companion of the Order of Australia</ref> He was awarded the [[Centenary Medal]] in 2001.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1125728&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526212354/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1125728&search_type=quick&showInd=true |date=26 May 2011 }} \u2013 Centenary Medal</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[First Gorton Ministry]]\n*[[Second Gorton Ministry]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|first=Ian|last=Hancock|year=2002|title=John Gorton: He Did It His Way|publisher=Hodder|isbn=0-7336-1439-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Gerard|last=Henderson|authorlink=Gerard Henderson|year=2000|chapter=Sir John Grey Gorton|title=Australian Prime Ministers|editor=[[Michelle Grattan]]|publisher=New Holland|isbn=1-86436-756-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Colin|last=Hughes|authorlink=Colin Hughes|year=1976|title=Mr Prime Minister: Australian Prime Ministers 1901\u20131972|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-550471-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Alan|last=Reid|authorlink=Alan Reid (journalist)|year=1969|title=The Power Struggle|url=https://archive.org/details/powerstruggle0000reid|url-access=registration|publisher=Shakespeare Head Press|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Alan|last=Reid|authorlink=Alan Reid (journalist)|year=1971|title=The Gorton Experiment|publisher=Shakespeare Head Press|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Alan|last=Trengove|year=1969|title=John Grey Gorton: An Informal Biography|publisher=Cassell|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John Gorton}}\n*{{cite web|title=John Gorton |url=http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/|work= Australia's Prime Ministers |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |accessdate=29 June 2010 }}\n*{{cite web|title=Prime Ministers of Australia, John Gorton |publisher=[[National Museum of Australia]]|url=http://www.nma.gov.au/primeministers/john_gorton |accessdate=29 June 2010 }}\n*[http://colsearch.nfsa.afc.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=yes;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=Number%3A350424;querytype=;rec=0;resCount=10 John Gorton at the National Film and Sound Archive]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Harold Holt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Division of Higgins|Member for Higgins]]|years=1968\u20131975}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Roger Shipton]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles Davidson (politician)|Charles Davidson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for the Navy]]|years=1958\u20131963}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Forbes (Australian politician)|Jim Forbes]]}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Gordon Freeth]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Housing (Australia)|Minister for Works]]|years=1963\u20131967}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bert Kelly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Home Affairs (Australia)|Minister for the Interior]]|years=1963\u20131964}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Doug Anthony]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Menzies]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Innovation, Industry, Science and Research (Australia)|Minister in charge of the Commonwealth<br />Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]]|years=1962\u20131963}}\n{{s-non|reason=Absorbed into next}}\n{{s-new|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Minister in charge of Commonwealth Activities<br />in [[Minister for Education (Australia)|Education]] and [[Minister for Innovation, Industry, Science and Research (Australia)|Research]]|years=1963\u20131966}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Malcolm Fraser]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister for [[Minister for Education (Australia)|Education]] and [[Minister for Innovation, Industry, Science and Research (Australia)|Science]]|years=1966\u20131968}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John McEwen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Australia]]|years=1968\u20131971}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William McMahon]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Malcolm Fraser]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for Defence]]|years=1971}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Fairbairn (politician)|David Fairbairn]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Harold Holt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Party of Australia|Leader of the Liberal Party of Australia]]|years=1968\u20131971}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William McMahon]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William McMahon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Party of Australia#Liberal federal deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of the Liberal Party of Australia]]|years=1971}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Billy Snedden]]}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Denham Henty]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=Leader of the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] in the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] | years=1967\u20131968}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Ken Anderson (Australian politician)|Ken Anderson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Australia}}\n{{Liberal Party of Australia}}\n{{Leaders of the Liberal Party of Australia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gorton, John}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of Australia]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for Victoria]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Higgins]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Australian agnostics]]\n[[Category:Australian World War II pilots]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Geelong Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Australian politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Australian Members of the Order of the Companions of Honour]]\n[[Category:Australian members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sydney Church of England Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Australian Freemasons]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Liberal Party of Australia]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Australian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the English writer|John Gorton (writer)}}\n{{short description|Australian politician, 19th Prime Minister of Australia}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Prime Minister\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name=Sir John Gorton\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|GCMG|AC|CH}}\n|image=John Gorton ANIB 1968 (cropped).jpg\n|order=19th [[Prime Minister of Australia]]<!--No election dates.-->\n|term_start    =10 January 1968\n|term_end      =10 March 1971\n|monarch     =[[Elizabeth II]]\n|governor-general = [[Richard Casey, Baron Casey|Lord Casey]]<br />[[Paul Hasluck|Sir Paul Hasluck]]\n|deputy        =[[John McEwen]]<br />[[Doug Anthony]]\n|predecessor   =[[John McEwen]]\n|successor     =[[William McMahon]]\n\n|office1           = [[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for Defence]]\n|primeminister1    = [[William McMahon]]\n|term_start1       = 19 March 1971\n|term_end1         = 13 August 1971\n|predecessor1      = [[Malcolm Fraser]]\n|successor1        = [[David Fairbairn (politician)|David Fairbairn]]\n\n|office2           = [[Minister for Education and Training|Minister for Education and Science]]\n|primeminister2    = [[Robert Menzies]]<br />[[Harold Holt]]<br />[[John McEwen]]<br />Himself\n|term_start2       = 16 February 1962\n|term_end2         = 28 February 1968\n|predecessor2     =\n|successor2        = Malcolm Fraser\n\n|office3            = [[Leader of the Government in the Senate (Australia)|Leader of the Government in the Senate]]\n|term_start3        = 16 October 1967\n|term_end3          = 1 February 1968\n|predecessor3       = [[Denham Henty]]\n|successor3         = [[Ken Anderson (politician)|Ken Anderson]]\n\n|office4           = [[Minister for Social Services (Australia)#List of works ministers|Minister for Works]]\n|primeminister4    = [[Robert Menzies]]<br />[[Harold Holt]]\n|term_start4       = 18 December 1963\n|term_end4         = 28 February 1967\n|predecessor4      = [[Gordon Freeth]]\n|successor4        = [[Bert Kelly]]\n\n|office5           = [[Minister for Home Affairs (Australia)#List of Ministers for the Interior|Minister for the Interior]]\n|primeminister5    = [[Robert Menzies]]\n|term_start5       = 18 December 1963\n|term_end5         = 4 March 1964\n|predecessor5      = Gordon Freeth\n|successor5        = [[Doug Anthony]]\n\n|office6           = [[Minister for Defence (Australia)#Ministers for the Navy|Minister for the Navy]]\n|primeminister6    = [[Robert Menzies]]\n|term_start6       = 10 December 1958\n|term_end6         = 18 December 1963\n|predecessor6      = [[Charles Davidson (politician)|Charles Davidson]]\n|successor6        = [[Jim Forbes (Australian politician)|Jim Forbes]]\n\n| order7             = [[Liberal Party of Australia|Leader of the Liberal Party]]\n| term_start7        = 9 January 1968\n| term_end7          = 10 March 1971\n| deputy7            = [[William McMahon]]\n| predecessor7       = [[Harold Holt]]\n| successor7         = William McMahon\n\n|order8              = [[Liberal Party of Australia|Deputy Leader of the Liberal Party]]\n|term_start8         = 10 March 1971\n|term_end8           = 18 August 1971\n|primeminister8      = William McMahon\n|predecessor8        = William McMahon\n|successor8          = [[Billy Snedden]]\n\n\n|constituency_MP9 = [[Division of Higgins|Higgins]]\n|parliament9      = Australian\n|term_start9      = 24 February 1968\n|term_end9        = 11 November 1975\n|predecessor9     = [[Harold Holt]]\n|successor9       = [[Roger Shipton]]\n\n\n|office10          = [[Australian Senate|Senator for]] [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n|term_start10      = 22 February 1950\n|term_end10        = 1 February 1968\n|predecessor10     =\n|successor10       = [[Ivor Greenwood]]\n\n|birth_name    = John Grey Gorton\n|birth_date    ={{birth date|df=y|1911|9|9}}\n|birth_place   = uncertain \u2013 [[Wellington]], New Zealand, ''or'' [[Prahran, Victoria]], Australia\n|death_date    ={{death date and age|df=y|2002|5|19|1911|9|9}}\n|death_place   =[[St Vincent's Hospital, Sydney|St Vincent's Hospital]], Sydney, Australia \n|resting_place     = [[Melbourne General Cemetery]]\n|party= [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] (1949\u20131975, 1993\u20132002)\n|otherparty = [[National Party of Australia|Country]] (until 1949)<br />[[Independent (politician)|Independent]] (1975\u20131993)\n|education    = [[Sydney Church of England Grammar School]]<br />[[Geelong Grammar School]]\n|alma_mater = [[Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|[[Bettina Gorton|Bettina Brown]]<br />|1935|1983|reason=died}}<br />{{marriage|Nancy Home<br />|1993}}\n|children      = 3\n|allegiance    = Australia\n|branch        = [[Royal Australian Air Force]]\n|serviceyears  = 1940\u20131944\n|rank= [[Flight Lieutenant]]\n|unit={{plainlist|\n*No. 61 Operational Training Unit RAF\n*[[No. 232 Squadron RAF]]\n*[[No. 77 Squadron RAAF]]\n*[[No. 2 Operational Conversion Unit RAAF]]\n}}\n|battles=[[World War II]]\n}}\n'''Sir John Grey Gorton''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|GCMG|AC|CH|}} (9 September 1911 \u2013 19 May 2002) was the [[List of Prime Ministers of Australia|nineteenth]] [[Prime Minister of Australia]], in office from 1968 to 1971. He led the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] during that time, having previously been a long-serving government minister.\n\nGorton was born out of wedlock and had a turbulent childhood. He studied at [[Brasenose College, Oxford]], after finishing his secondary education at [[Geelong Grammar School]], and then returned to Australia to take over his father's property in northern [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. Gorton enlisted in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] in 1940, and served as a fighter pilot in [[Malayan Campaign|Malaya]] and [[New Guinea Campaign|New Guinea]] during the Second World War. He suffered severe facial injuries in a crash landing on [[Bintan Island]] in 1942, and whilst being evacuated; his ship was torpedoed and sunk by a Japanese submarine. He returned to farming after being discharged in 1944, and was elected to the [[Shire of Kerang|Kerang Shire Council]] in 1946; he later served a term as shire president.\n\nAfter a previous unsuccessful candidacy at state level, Gorton was elected to the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] at the [[1949 Australian federal election|1949 federal election]]. He took a keen interest in foreign policy, and gained a reputation as a strident [[anti-Communist]]. Gorton was promoted to the ministry in 1958, and over the following decade held a variety of different portfolios in the governments of [[Robert Menzies]] and [[Harold Holt]]. He was responsible at various times for the Navy, public works, education, and science. He was elevated to the Cabinet in 1966, and the following year, he was promoted to [[Leader of the Government in the Senate (Australia)|Leader of the Government in the Senate]].\n\nGorton [[1968 Liberal Party of Australia leadership election|defeated]] three other candidates for the Liberal leadership after [[Disappearance of Harold Holt|Harold Holt's disappearance]] on 17 December 1967. He became the first and only senator to assume the office of Prime Minister, but soon transferred to the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] in line with constitutional convention. The [[Gorton Government]] continued [[Military history of Australia during the Vietnam War|Australian involvement]] in the [[Vietnam War]], but began withdrawing troops amid growing public discontent. It retained office at the [[1969 Australian federal election|1969 federal election]], albeit with a severely reduced majority. Gorton's domestic policies, which emphasised [[centralisation]] and [[economic nationalism]], were often controversial in his own party, and his individualistic style alienated many of his Cabinet members. He resigned as Liberal leader in 1971 after a [[confidence motion]] in his leadership was tied, and was replaced by [[William McMahon]].\n\nAfter losing the premiership, Gorton was elected deputy leader under McMahon and appointed [[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for Defence]]. He was sacked for disloyalty after a few months. After the Coalition's defeat at the [[1972 Australian federal election|1972 federal election]], Gorton [[1972 Liberal Party of Australia leadership election|unsuccessfully stood]] as McMahon's replacement. He briefly served as an opposition [[frontbencher]] under [[Billy Snedden]], but stood down in 1974 and spent the rest of his career as a [[backbencher]]. Gorton resigned from the Liberal Party when [[Malcolm Fraser]] was elected leader, and at the [[1975 Australian federal election|1975 election]] mounted an unsuccessful campaign for the Senate as an [[Independent politician|independent]]. He later spent several years as a political commentator, retiring from public life in 1981.\n\n==Early life==\n===Birth and family background===\n[[File:JohnGorton1913.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton as a toddler in 1913]]\n[[File:NlaGortonmotherAlice1915.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton as a child and his mother Alice in 1915]]\nJohn Grey Gorton was the second child of Alice Sinn and John Rose Gorton; his older sister Ruth was born in 1909. He had no birth certificate, but on official forms recorded his date of birth as 9 September 1911 and his place of birth as [[Wellington]], New Zealand. His birth was registered in the state of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] as occurring on that date, but in the inner [[Melbourne]] suburb of [[Prahran, Victoria|Prahran]]. However, that document contained a number of inaccuracies \u2013 his name was given as \"John Alga Gordon\", his parents were recorded as husband and wife, his father's name was incorrect, and his sister was recorded as deceased.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ian Hancock|title=John Gorton: He Did It His Way|publisher=Hodder|year=2002|page=1|isbn=0733614396}}</ref> At some point, Gorton's father told him that he had actually been born in Wellington. There are no records of his birth in New Zealand, but his parents are known to have travelled there on several occasions.<ref name=p2>Hancock (2002), p. 2.</ref> John Gorton apparently believed he was born in Wellington, listing the city as his place of birth on his RAAF enlistment papers.<ref>[http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/before-office.aspx Before office - John Gorton], National Archives of Australia. Retrieved 6 November 2019.</ref> \n\nIf John Gorton was indeed born in New Zealand, this would have made him a New Zealand citizen from 1 January 1949 under changes to [[New Zealand nationality law]]. Holding dual-citizenship would have rendered Gorton ineligible to sit in Australia's federal parliament under [[Section 44 of the Australian Constitution]]. Gorton's eligibility to have sat in parliament throughout his career is therefore unclear.<ref>[https://williamsummers.blog/2017/08/07/section-44-twist-former-aussie-pm-was-probably-ineligible-for-parliament-due-to-multiple-citizenship/ Section 44 twist: Former Aussie PM was probably ineligible due to multiple citizenship], William Summers (blog). Retrieved 6 November 2019.</ref>\n\nGorton's father was born to a middle-class family in [[Manchester]], [[England]], UK. As a young man he moved to [[Johannesburg]], South Africa, where he went into business as a merchant \u2013 during the [[Second Boer War|Boer War]], he developed a reputation as a [[War profiteering|war profiteer]]. He reputedly escaped the [[Siege of Ladysmith]] by sneaking through Boer lines, and then made his way to Australia.<ref name=p3>Hancock (2002), p. 3.</ref> He was involved in various business schemes in multiple states, and was to said to have \"lived on the brink of a fortune which never quite materialised\".<ref name=p4>Hancock (2002), p. 4.</ref> One of his business partners was the inventor [[George Julius]].<ref name=p3/> At some point, Gorton's father separated from his first wife, Kathleen O'Brien, and began living with Alice Sinn \u2013 born in Melbourne to a German father and an Irish mother.<ref name=p2/> However, Kathleen refused to grant him a divorce. Some official documents record Gorton's parents as having married in New Zealand at some point, but there are no records of this occurring; any such marriage would have been bigamous. Gorton never denied his illegitimacy as an adult, but it did not become generally known until a biography was published during his premiership.<ref name=p4/>\n\n===Childhood===\n[[File:JohnGorton1930.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton as a student at Geelong Grammar School in 1930; he is seated to the left]]\nGorton spent his early years living with his maternal grandparents in [[Port Melbourne, Victoria|Port Melbourne]], as his parents were frequently away on business trips. When he was about four years old, his parents took him to live with them in Sydney, where they had an apartment at [[Edgecliff, New South Wales|Edgecliff]]. Gorton began his education at Edgecliff Preparatory School.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 5.</ref> When he was eight years old, his mother contracted tuberculosis and was sent to a [[sanatorium]] to avoid passing on the disease. She died in September 1920, aged 32. Gorton's grieving father sent his son to live with his estranged wife Kathleen. There, he met his sister Ruth for the first time; he had previously been told that she was dead. Although she was his full sibling, she had been raised by Kathleen since birth, and rarely saw her biological parents. Gorton initially lived with Kathleen and Ruth at their home in [[Cronulla, New South Wales|Cronulla]]. They later moved into a larger house in [[Killara, New South Wales|Killara]], in the north of Sydney.<ref name=hp8>Hancock (2002), p. 8.</ref>\n\nWhile living in Killara, Gorton began attending Headfort College, a short-lived private school run by a former Anglican minister.<ref name=hp8/> In 1924, he began boarding at [[Sydney Church of England Grammar School]] (Shore), initially on a weekly basis but later on a full-time one.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 9.</ref> He did not excel academically, failing the [[Intermediate Certificate (Australia)|Intermediate Certificate]] on his first attempt, but was a well-liked boy and good at sports.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 10.</ref> Gorton began spending his holidays with his father, who had purchased a property in [[Mystic Park, Victoria]], and planted a citrus orchard.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 11.</ref> He left Shore at the end of 1926, and the following year began boarding at [[Geelong Grammar School]], which he would attend for four years from 1927\u201330.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 12.</ref> He represented the school in athletics, [[Australian rules football|football]], and rowing, and in his final year was a school prefect and house captain.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 15.</ref>\n\n===University===\nAfter leaving Geelong Grammar, Gorton spent a year working on his father's property in Mystic Park. His father then took out a second mortgage to allow him to travel to England and attend [[Oxford University]]. Gorton arrived in England in early-1932, and after a period at a \"cramming school\" passed the exam to enter [[Brasenose College, Oxford|Brasenose College]]. He also took flying lessons around the same time, and was awarded a pilot's licence in June 1932. Gorton began his degree in October 1932 and finished in June 1935 with an \"[[Upper-second class|upper second]]\" in History, Politics, and Economics. He was initially something of an outsider, with relatively little money and no social connections. However, his prowess in rowing \u2013 he won the O.U.B.C. Fours in his first year, and was Captain of the [[Brasenose College Boat Club]] \u2013 saw him elected to [[Vincent's Club]] and [[Leander Club]]. In 1934, while on holiday in [[Second Spanish Republic|Spain]], he met his future wife [[Bettina Gorton|Bettina Brown]], the younger sister of one of his College friends. They married in early 1935.<ref name=bdas>[http://biography.senate.gov.au/gorton-john-grey GORTON, SIR JOHN GREY (1911\u20132002)], Biographical Dictionary of the Australian Senate (Online Edition). Retrieved 12 March 2018.</ref>\n\n===Return to Australia===\nAfter his graduation, Gorton and his wife returned to Australia via the [[United States]], spending some time with her family in [[Maine]]. He had expected to take up a position at [[The Herald and Weekly Times]], [[Keith Murdoch]]'s newspaper group. However, he arrived in Melbourne to find his father in failing health; he died in August 1936. Gorton had taken over the management of his father's orchard as soon as he entered hospital. He inherited an overdraft of \u00a35,000, which took several years to pay off. However, the property \u2013 located on the western side of [[North Victorian Wetlands|Kangaroo Lake]] \u2013 was in good condition, requiring only minor improvements. He employed up to ten seasonal workers during picking season. Mystic Park remained his primary residence until he was appointed to the ministry, at which point he and his family moved to Canberra.<ref name=bdas/>\n\n==Military service==\n\n===1940\u20131942===\n[[File:JohnGortonWW21941.jpg|thumb|left|Pilot Officer Gorton]]\n[[File:JohnGorton1941.jpg|thumb|right|Gorton prior to leaving for war service in 1941]]\nOn 31 May 1940, following the outbreak of World War II, Gorton enlisted in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] Reserve.<ref>Hancock: 30</ref> At the age of 29, Gorton was considered too old for pilot training, but he re-applied in September after this rule was relaxed. Gorton was accepted and commissioned into the RAAF on 8 November 1940.<ref>Hancock: 31</ref> He trained as a fighter pilot at [[Somers, Victoria]] and [[Wagga Wagga]], [[New South Wales]], before being sent to the UK. Gorton completed his training at [[RAF Heston]] and [[RAF Honiley]],<ref name=\"Trengrove: 71\">Trengrove: 71</ref> with [[No. 61 Operational Training Unit RAF]], flying [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s.<ref name=\"Hancock: 33\">Hancock: 33</ref> He was disappointed when his first operational posting was [[No. 135 Squadron RAF]], a [[Hawker Hurricane]] unit, as he considered the type greatly inferior to Spitfires.<ref name=\"Trengrove: 71\"/>\n\nDuring late 1941, Gorton and other members of his squadron became part of the [[En cadre|cadre]] of a Hurricane [[wing (air force unit)|wing]] being formed for service in the Middle East. They were sent by sea, with 50 Hurricanes in crates, travelling around Africa to reduce the risk of attack. In December, when the ship was at [[Durban]], South Africa, it was diverted to Singapore, after [[Pacific War|Japan entered the war]].<ref>Trengrove: 72</ref> As it approached its destination in mid-January, [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] forces were [[Battle of Malaya|advancing down the Malayan Peninsula]]. The ship was attacked on at least one occasion by Japanese aircraft, but arrived and unloaded safely after tropical storms made enemy air raids impossible.<ref>Trengrove: 73\u201374</ref> As the Hurricanes were assembled, the pilots were formed into a composite operational squadron, [[No. 232 Squadron RAF]].\n\nIn late January 1942, the squadron became operational and joined the remnants of several others that had been in Malaya, operating out of [[Seletar Airport|RAF Seletar]] and RAF [[Kallang]].<ref>Trengrove: 75</ref> During one of his first [[sortie]]s, Gorton was involved in a brief dogfight over the [[South China Sea]], after which he suffered engine failure and was forced to land on [[Bintan]] island,<ref name=\"Hancock: 33\"/> 40&nbsp;km (25&nbsp;mi) south east of Singapore. As he landed, one of the Hurricane's wheels hit an embankment and flipped over. Gorton was not properly strapped in and his face hit the gun sight and windscreen, mutilating his nose and breaking both cheekbones.<ref name=\"Trengrove: 76\">Trengrove: 76</ref> He also suffered severe lacerations to both arms. He made his way out of the wreck and was rescued by members of the [[Royal Dutch East Indies Army]], who provided some medical treatment. Gorton later claimed that his face was so badly cut and bruised, that a member of the RAF sent to collect him assumed he was near death, collected his personal effects and returned to Singapore without him.<ref name=\"Trengrove: 76\"/> By chance, one week later, Sgt Matt O'Mara of [[No. 453 Squadron RAAF]] also crash landed on Bintan, and arranged for them to be collected.<ref name=\"Trengrove: 77\">Trengrove: 77</ref>\n\nThey arrived back in Singapore, on 11 February, three days after [[battle of Singapore|the island had been invaded]].<ref name=\"Trengrove: 77\"/> As the Allied air force units on Singapore had been destroyed or evacuated by this stage, Gorton was put on the ''Derrymore'', an ammunition ship bound for [[Jakarta|Batavia]] (Jakarta). On 13 February, as it neared its destination, the ship was torpedoed by Japanese submarine I-55 [[Kaidai class submarine]] and the ''Derrymore'' was abandoned. Gorton then spent almost a day on a crowded liferaft, in shark-infested waters, with little drinking water, until the raft was spotted by [[HMAS Ballarat (J184)|HMAS ''Ballarat'']], which picked up the passengers and took them to Batavia.<ref>Trengrove: 80</ref>\n\n[[File:77_Sqn_RAAF_pilots_%26_Kittyhawk_(AWM_NWA0019).JPG|thumb|left|Pilots of B Flight, No. 77 Squadron with a P-40 Kittyhawk in the Northern Territory, January 1943. Gorton is fourth left in the back row.]]\nTwo schoolfriends, who had also been evacuated from Singapore to Batavia, heard that Gorton was in hospital, arranged for them to be put on a ship for [[Fremantle]], which left on 23 February and treated Gorton's wounds.<ref>Trengrove: 81</ref> When the ship arrived in Fremantle, on 3 March, one of Gorton's arm wounds had become septic and needed extensive treatment. However, he was more concerned about the effect that the sight of his mutilated face would have on his wife. It is reported that Betty Gorton, who had been running the farm in his absence, was relieved to see Gorton alive.<ref name=\"Hancock: 33\"/><ref>Trengrove: 82</ref>\n\n===1942\u20131944===\n\nAfter arriving in Australia he was posted to [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] on 12 August 1942 with [[No. 77 Squadron RAAF]] (Kittyhawks). During this time he was involved in his second air accident.  While flying [[P-40E]] A29-60 on 7 September 1942, he was forced to land due to an incorrectly set fuel cock. Both Gorton and his aircraft were recovered several days later after spending time in the bush. On 21 February 1943 the squadron was relocated to [[Milne Bay]], [[New Guinea]].<ref name=naaws>{{cite web|url=http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/before-office.aspx#section2 |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |title=John Gorton, Before office, War service 1940\u201345 | accessdate= 24 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nGorton's final air incident came on 18 March 1943. His A29-192 Kittyhawk's engine failed on takeoff, causing the aircraft to flip at the end of the strip. Gorton was unhurt. In March 1944, Gorton was sent back to Australia with the rank of Flight Lieutenant. His final posting was as a Flying Instructor with [[No. 2 Operational Conversion Unit RAAF|No. 2 Operational Training Unit]] at [[Mildura]], Victoria.  He was then discharged from the RAAF on 5 December 1944.<ref name=naaws/>\n\nDuring late 1944 Gorton went to [[Austin Hospital, Melbourne|Heidelberg Hospital]] for surgery which could not fully repair his facial injuries; he was left permanently disfigured.<ref name=naaws/>\n\n==Early political involvement==\nAfter resuming his life in Mystic Park, Gorton was elected unopposed to the [[Shire of Kerang|Kerang Shire Council]] in September 1946. He remained on the council until 1952, overlapping with his first term in the Senate, and from 1949 to 1950 served as shire president.<ref name=p46>Hancock (2002), p. 46.</ref> Although he had little previous experience, Gorton began to develop a reputation as a powerful public speaker. His first major speech, in April 1946, was an address to a welcome-home gathering for returned soldiers at the Mystic Park Hall. In what [[John Brogden (politician)|John Brogden]] has described as \"Australia's best unknown political speech\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/opinion/when-heartfelt-oratory-gave-us-a-political-vision-to-believe-in/news-story/f6e976b88facb7aef45be610e8025547|title=When heartfelt oratory gave us a political vision to believe in|author=[[John Brogden (politician)|John Brogden]]|date=1 July 2016|access-date=21 September 2018|work=[[The Australian]]}}</ref> he exhorted his audience to honour those who had died in the war by building \"a world in which meanness and poverty, tyranny and hate, have no existence\". Gorton's next major speech was made in September 1947, at a rally against the [[Chifley Government]]'s attempt to nationalise private banks. He told the crowd in [[Kerang]] that they should oppose the establishment of banks run by politicians, and objected in particular to the government's decision not to take the issue to a referendum.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 49.</ref> According to his biographer Ian Hancock, \"the bank nationalisation issue marked his advance beyond purely local politics and stamped him firmly and publicly as an anti-socialist\".<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 51.</ref>\n\nGorton had been a supporter of the [[Country Party (Victoria)|Country Party]] before the war, along with most of his neighbours. Over time, he became frustrated with the party's frequent squabbles with the [[Liberal Party of Australia (Victorian Division)|Liberal Party]] and its willingness to cooperate with the [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]].<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 52.</ref> After the Victorian Country Party withdrew from [[Coalition (Australia)|its coalition]] with the Liberals in December 1948, Gorton became involved in efforts to form a new anti-socialist movement that would absorb both parties. At some point he was introduced to [[Magnus Cormack]], the state president of the Liberals, who became something of a mentor.<ref name=p53>Hancock (2002), pp. 53\u201354.</ref> In March 1949, Gorton was elected to the state executive of the new organisation, which named itself the [[Liberal and Country Party]] (LCP).<ref name=p55>Hancock (2002), p. 55.</ref> On a number of occasions he addressed Country Party gatherings, urging its members to join the new party and stressing that it would not neglect rural interests, as many feared.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 56.</ref> However, the LCP did not achieve its goal of uniting the anti-Labor forces, as most Country Party members viewed it as simply a takeover attempt; the new party affiliated with the federal [[Liberal Party of Australia]].<ref name=p53/>\n\nIn June 1949, Gorton stood for the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] as the LCP candidate in [[Northern Province (Victoria)|Northern Province]]. It was a safe Country Party seat, and at the preceding three elections no other parties had bothered to field a candidate.<ref name=p55/> Making right-wing unity the focal point of his campaign, Gorton polled 48.8 percent of the vote to finish less than 400 votes behind the sitting member, [[George Tuckett (politician)|George Tuckett]]. The result impressed the LCP's leadership,<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 57.</ref> and the following month he was [[preselection|preselected]] in third place on its joint [[Australian Senate|Senate]] ticket with the Country Party. He was relatively unknown within the party, and his rural background was a major factor in his selection.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 58.</ref> The Coalition won a large majority at the [[1949 Australian federal election|1949 federal election]], including four out of Victoria's seven senators. The LCP candidates joined the parliamentary Liberal Party.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 59.</ref>\n\n==Senate (1950\u20131968)==\n===Backbencher===\n[[File:JohnGorton1954.JPG|thumb|left|Gorton in 1954]]\nGorton's term in the Senate began on 22 February 1950.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=61}} He was re-elected to additional terms at the [[1951 Australian federal election|1951]], [[1953 Australian Senate election|1953]], [[1958 Australian federal election|1958]], and [[1964 Australian Senate election|1964 elections]], and from 1953 occupied first place on the Coalition's ticket in Victoria. Gorton's early speeches on domestic policy foreshadowed the stances and policy initiatives he would later adopt as prime minister, such as economic nationalism, support for a strong central government, and support for nuclear energy. One of his first notable actions in the Senate came in November 1951, when he successfully moved a motion opposing \"any substantial measure of ownership or control over any Australian broadcasting station\" being granted to non-Australians.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=73}} In his early speeches on foreign policy, Gorton drew analogies between the actions of the Soviet Union and Communist China and those of Nazi Germany.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=68}} He developed a reputation as a \"hardline [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]]\", speaking in favour of the Communist Party Dissolution Bill and campaigning for the \"Yes\" vote during the [[1951 Australian Communist Party ban referendum|1951 referendum]] to ban the [[Communist Party of Australia|Communist Party]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=64\u201366}} At a campaign rally in September 1951, he had to be restrained by police after attempting to drag a heckler from his seat and shouting at him to \"come outside, you yellow rat\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/23077920|title=Women rush from hall|publisher=[[Melbourne Argus]]|date=5 September 1951}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1952 to 1958, Gorton served on the Joint Parliamentary Committee on Foreign Affairs, including as chairman for a period. He developed a keen interest in Asia, which was rooted in his anti-communism, and joined parliamentary delegations to Malaya, South Vietnam, Thailand, and the Philippines. He strongly supported Australia joining the [[Southeast Asia Treaty Organisation]] (SEATO), a collective defence initiative designed to [[domino theory|prevent the spread of communism]] in the region. He also supported [[Taiwanese independence]] and opposed Australian recognition of the People's Republic of China (PRC).{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=67}} On a number of occasions, Gorton spoke of the need for Australia to develop a foreign policy independent of Britain and the United States.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=68}} In May 1957, he told the Senate that Australia should acquire its own nuclear deterrent, including intercontinental missiles.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=69}}\n\n===Government minister===\n====Navy====\n[[File:Paul Hasluck, Shen Chang-huan, John Gorton.jpg|thumb|right|Gorton in 1965 with External Affairs Minister [[Paul Hasluck]] and Taiwanese foreign minister [[Shen Chang-huan]]]]\nGorton was elevated to the ministry after the [[1958 Australian federal election|1958 election]], as [[Minister for the Navy (Australia)|Minister for the Navy]]. This was a junior position subordinate to the Minister for Defence, [[Athol Townley]]. Although his promotion was unexpected,{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=81}} he would serve as Minister for the Navy for more than five years, the longest-serving navy minister in Australia's history.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=96}} Gorton regularly attended meetings of the [[Australian Commonwealth Naval Board|Naval Board]], unlike previous ministers, and championed its recommendations at cabinet meetings. He was able to secure most elements of the board's desired modernisation program, despite Townley showing more interest in the air force. During Gorton's tenure, the navy acquired four Australian-built frigates and six British-built minesweepers, as well as placing orders for three [[Charles F. Adams-class destroyer|''Charles F. Adams''-class destroyer]]s and four [[Oberon-class submarine|''Oberon''-class submarine]]s. He postponed the phasing out of the [[Fleet Air Arm (RAN)|Fleet Air Arm]], due to occur in 1963, and secured the purchase of 27 [[Westland Wessex]] helicopters.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=87\u201390}}\n\nGorton was a supporter and admirer of Robert Menzies, who was sympathetic to his ambitions for higher office and assigned him additional responsibilities. In 1959, he was tasked with securing the passage of the Matrimonial Causes Bill, which introduced uniform divorce laws; he described it as \"a systematic attempt to make a new approach to the problem of divorce\". The bill was opposed by religious conservatives (mostly Catholics) on both sides of politics, but it eventually passed the Senate with only a single amendment.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=85\u201386}} Gorton was appointed assistant minister to the [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Australia)|Minister for External Affairs]] in February 1960, working under Menzies and later under [[Garfield Barwick]] and [[Paul Hasluck]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=84}} In February 1962, he was also made minister-in-charge of the [[CSIRO]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=96}} During [[question time]] in the Senate, he represented ministers from the House of Representatives, allowing him to gain experience in portfolios beyond his own.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=84}}{{efn|In Australia, ministers are drawn from both the House of Representatives and the Senate. To allow the Opposition to ask questions about all governmental actions in both houses, some ministers assume responsibility for portfolios held by ministers from the other chamber.}}\n\n====Education and science====\n[[File:John Gorton, Fred White, Ren\u00e9 Maheu.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton with CSIRO chairman [[Fred White (scientist)|Fred White]] and UNESCO Director-General [[Ren\u00e9 Maheu]] at a regional science organisation meeting in 1964]]\nAfter the [[1963 Australian federal election|1963 election]], Gorton relinquished the navy portfolio and was placed in charge of the government's activities in education and scientific research.{{efn|His formal title was \"Minister in charge of Commonwealth Activities in Education and Research under the Prime Minister\".{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=103}}}} He was also made [[Department of Works (1952\u201373)|Minister for Works]] and [[Department of the Interior (1939\u201372)|Minister for the Interior]], relatively low-profile positions dealing mostly with administrative matters; the latter post was taken over by [[Doug Anthony]] after a few months. Menzies had a personal interest in education, having previously handled the portfolio himself,{{efn|There was no separate education department at the time, with the portfolio instead handled by the Commonwealth Education Office within the [[Prime Minister's Department (Australia)|Prime Minister's Department]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=104}}}} and told Gorton that it should be his primary focus.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=103}} He was given oversight of the Australian Universities Commission, the [[Australian National University]], the [[National Archives of Australia|Commonwealth Archives Office]], the [[Commonwealth Literary Fund]], and the [[National Library of Australia]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=104}} In January 1966, Menzies retired and [[Harold Holt]] became prime minister. Gorton was elevated to [[Cabinet of Australia|cabinet]],{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=100}} and at the end of the year was given the title [[Minister for Education (Australia)|Minister for Education and Science]]. He was placed in charge of the new [[Department of Education and Science (Australia)|Department of Education and Science]], the first time those portfolios had been given a separate department at federal level.<ref>{{cite book|first=Tom|last=Frame| authorlink=Tom Frame (bishop)|title=The Life and Death of Harold Holt|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=2005|isbn=1-74114-672-0|page=168}}</ref>\n\n[[File:JohnGorton.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Senator Gorton in 1967]]\nGorton presided over a \"major intrusion\" of the federal government into the education sector.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|p=121}} His tenure saw significant increases in the number of university scholarships available, the number of new university entrants, and overall funding of education.{{efn|Between 1963 and 1966, the number of Commonwealth scholarships on offer rose from 4,701 to 8,069, an increase of 72 percent, while the number of new university entrants rose from 17,311 to 24,196, an increase of 40 percent. Total federal funding of education rose by 77 percent from the 1964\u201365 budget to the 1967\u201368 budget.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=121\u2013122}}}} One of the first major issues Gorton confronted was that of state aid to non-government schools. He believed that private schools should have equal access to federal government funding, and in 1964 announced that the government would fund science laboratories for private schools.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=109\u2013111}} This stance, supported by the [[Catholic education in Australia|Catholic education sector]] but opposed by secularists and most Protestant schools, eventually achieved widespread acceptance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_Departments/Parliamentary_Library/Publications_Archive/CIB/CIB9697/97cib2|title=State Aid for Non-Government Schools: The emerging debate|first=Greg|last=McIntosh|year=1996|publisher=Australian Parliamentary Library}}</ref> In September 1965, Gorton created the Commonwealth Advisory Committee on Advanced Education, tasked with advising the government on non-university [[technical and further education]] (TAFE). He announced that the federal government would fund technical colleges on a pro-rata basis with the states,{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=111\u2013112}} and personally oversaw the establishment of the Canberra College of Advanced Education, the forerunner of the [[University of Canberra]].{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=114\u2013115}} As science minister, he lent his support to the [[Anglo-Australian Telescope]] project, securing cabinet approval for its construction in April 1967.{{sfn|Hancock|2002|pp=120\u2013121}}\n\n==Prime Minister==\n===Holt's disappearance===\n{{See also|Disappearance of Harold Holt|Liberal Party of Australia leadership election, 1968}}\n[[File:John_Gorton_Swearing_In.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton being sworn in as Prime Minister on 10 January 1968.]]\n[[Harold Holt]] disappeared while swimming on 17 December 1967 and was declared presumed drowned two days later. His presumed successor was Liberal deputy leader [[William McMahon]].  However, on 18 December, the Country Party leader and Deputy Prime Minister [[John McEwen]] announced that if McMahon were named the new Liberal leader, he and his party would not serve under him.  His reasons were never stated publicly, but in a private meeting with McMahon, he said \"I will not serve under you because I do not trust you\".<ref>Gavin Souter, ''Acts of Parliament'', 1988, pp. 478\u201379</ref> McEwen's shock declaration triggered a leadership crisis within the Liberal Party; even more significantly, it raised the threat of a possible breaking of the Coalition, which would spell electoral disaster for the Liberals.  Up to that time, the Liberals had never won enough seats in any House of Representatives election to be able to govern without Country Party support.  Indeed, since the Coalition's formation in 1923, the major non-[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] party had only been able to govern alone once, during [[Joseph Lyons]]' first ministry. Even then, Lyons' [[United Australia Party]] had come up four seats short of a majority in its own right, and was only able to garner a bare majority of two when the five members of the [[Emergency Committee of South Australia]] joined the UAP party room.\n\nThe Governor-General [[Richard Casey, Baron Casey|Lord Casey]] swore McEwen in as Prime Minister, on an interim basis pending the Liberal Party electing its new leader. McEwen agreed to accept an interim appointment provided there was no formal statement of time limit. This appointment was in keeping with previous occasions when a conservative Coalition government had been deprived of its leader.<ref>In 1939 when [[Joseph Lyons]] died suddenly, and in 1941 when [[Robert Menzies]] resigned, the Governor-General had commissioned the (unofficial) Deputy Prime Minister, who was the leader of the Country Party, to serve as Prime Minister until the major coalition partner\u2014then the UAP\u2014could choose its new leader.</ref> Casey also concurred in the view put to him by McEwen that to commission a Liberal temporarily as Prime Minister would give that person an unfair advantage in the forthcoming party room ballot for the permanent leader.\n[[File:John_Gorton_1968_colour.jpg|thumb|right|Gorton in his office in 1968.]]\nIn the subsequent [[1968 Liberal Party of Australia leadership election|leadership struggle]], Gorton was championed by Army Minister [[Malcolm Fraser]], Government Whip in the Senate [[Malcolm Scott]] and Liberal Party Whip [[Dudley Erwin]], and with their support he was able to defeat rivals [[Paul Hasluck]], [[Les Bury]] and [[Billy Snedden]] to become Liberal leader even though he was a member of the Senate.  He was elected party leader on 9 January 1968, and appointed Prime Minister on 10 January, replacing McEwen.  He was the only Senator in Australia's history to be Prime Minister and the only Prime Minister to have ever served in the Senate.  He remained a Senator until, in accordance with the [[Westminster system|Westminster]] tradition that the Prime Minister is a member of the lower house of parliament, he resigned on 1 February 1968 to contest the by-election for Holt's old House of Representatives seat of [[Division of Higgins|Higgins]] in south Melbourne.  The by-election in this comfortably safe Liberal seat was held on 24 February; there were three other candidates, but Gorton achieved a massive 68% of the formal vote.  He visited all the polling booths during the day, but was unable to vote for himself as he was still enrolled in [[Division of Mallee|Mallee]], in rural western Victoria.<ref>''the age(melbourne)magazine'', p. 16</ref> Between 2 and 23 February (both dates inclusive) he was a member of neither house of parliament.\n\n===Activities in office===\n[[File:John Gorton 1969.jpg|thumb|left|Gorton at the [[Honeysuckle Creek Tracking Station]] during the [[Apollo 11]] moon landing in 1969]]\nGorton was initially a very popular Prime Minister. He carved out a style quite distinct from those of his predecessors \u2013 the aloof Menzies and the affable, sporty Holt. Gorton liked to portray himself as a man of the people who enjoyed a beer and a gamble, with a bit of a [[larrikinism|\"larrikin\"]] streak about him. Unfortunately for him, this reputation later came back to haunt him.\n\nHe also began to follow new policies, pursuing independent defence and foreign policies and distancing Australia from its traditional ties to Britain. But he continued to support Australia's involvement in the [[Vietnam War]], a position he had reluctantly inherited from Holt, which became increasingly unpopular after 1968. On domestic issues, he favoured centralist policies at the expense of the states, which alienated powerful Liberal state leaders like Sir [[Henry Bolte]] of Victoria and [[Robert Askin|Bob Askin]] of New South Wales. He also fostered an independent [[Australian film industry]] and increased government funding for the arts.\nGorton proved to be a surprisingly poor media performer and public speaker, and was portrayed by the media as a foolish and incompetent administrator. He was unlucky to come up against a new and formidable Labor Opposition Leader in [[Gough Whitlam]]. Also, he was subjected to media speculation about his drinking habits and his involvements with women. He generated great resentment within his party, and his opponents became increasingly critical of his reliance on an inner circle of advisers \u2013 most notably his private secretary [[Ainsley Gotto]].\n\nThe Coalition suffered a 7% swing against it at the [[1969 Australian federal election|1969 election]], and Labor outpolled it on the [[two-party-preferred vote]]. During the close election Gorton promised to waive all future government rent on residential leaseholders in Canberra.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hong|first1=Yu-Hung|title=Myths and Realities of Public Land Leasing: Canberra and Hong Kong|journal=Land Lines|date=March 1999|volume=11|issue=2|url=https://www.lincolninst.edu/pubs/dl/361_linc_landlines%203.99.pdf|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> After surviving the election Gorton came through on his promise, giving away an estimated $100&nbsp;million in equity to leaseholders and abandoning future government rent revenue.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fitzgerald|first1=Karl|title=Canberra's Leasehold Land System|url=http://www.prosper.org.au/2008/01/16/canberra/|website=Prosper Australia|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> Still, Gorton saw the sizeable 45-seat majority he had inherited from Holt cut down to only seven.  Indeed, the Coalition might have lost government had it not been for the [[Democratic Labor Party (historical)|Democratic Labor Party]]'s longstanding practice of preferencing against the ALP.  The Coalition was only assured of a ninth term in government when DLP preferences tipped four marginal seats in Melbourne \u2014the DLP's heartland\u2014to the Liberals.  Had those preferences gone the other way, Whitlam would have become Prime Minister.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/elections/federal/2007/results/senate/vic.htm Analysis of 2007 election in Victoria] by [[Antony Green]]</ref>\n\n===Leadership challenges and resignation===\n[[File:Gorton_and_McMahon.jpg|thumb|Gorton with [[William McMahon]] shortly after the unsuccessful leadership challenge in 1969.]]\nAfter the 1969 election, Gorton [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, 1969|was unsuccessfully challenged for the Liberal leadership]] by McMahon and National Development Minister [[David Fairbairn (politician)|David Fairbairn]]. With the Liberals falling further behind Labor in the polls in 1971, a challenge was launched in March when Defence Minister [[Malcolm Fraser]] resigned.  Fraser had strongly supported Gorton for the leadership two years earlier, but now attacked Gorton on the floor of parliament in his resignation speech, saying that Gorton was \"not fit to hold the great office of Prime Minister.\"\n\nGorton called [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, 1971|a Liberal caucus meeting]] for 10 March 1971 to settle the matter. A motion of confidence in his leadership was tied. Under Liberal caucus rules of the time, a tied vote meant the motion was passed and hence Gorton could have remained as party leader and Prime Minister without further ado.  However, he took it upon himself to resign, saying \"Well, that is not a vote of confidence, so the party will have to elect a new leader.\"<ref>Neil Brown, ''On the Other Hand ... Sketches and Reflections from Political Life'', The Popular Press, 1993, p. 59</ref> A ballot was held and McMahon was elected leader and thus Prime Minister. Australian television marked the end of Gorton's stormy premiership with a newsreel montage accompanied by [[Frank Sinatra|Sinatra's]] anthem \"[[My Way (song)|My Way]]\".\n\nIn a surprise move, Gorton contested and won the position of Deputy Leader, forcing McMahon to make him Defence Minister. This farcical situation ended within five months when McMahon sacked him for disloyalty.\n\n==Final years in parliament==\n[[File:President Nixon meeting with the Hon.Jack G Gorton - NARA - 194715.tif|thumb|left|Gorton meeting with U.S. President [[Richard Nixon]] and [[Alexander Haig]] in April 1971]]\nA number of polls during McMahon's prime ministership had Gorton as both the preferred Liberal leader and the preferred prime minister. In 1972, businessman [[David Hains]] commissioned a series of polls in marginal electorates that showed the Coalition would significantly increase its vote if Gorton mounted a successful comeback; for instance, polling in the [[Division of Henty]] found that his return would add eight points to the Liberal vote. However, Gorton generally downplayed the polling and did not mount an active campaign to oust McMahon.<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 362\u2013363.</ref> Labor went on to win a nine-seat majority at the [[1972 Australian federal election|1972 election]], ending 23 consecutive years of Coalition rule.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 364.</ref> A number of Gorton's contemporaries \u2013 including Country Party leader [[Doug Anthony]] and Labor ministers [[Clyde Cameron]], [[Doug McClelland]], and [[John Wheeldon]] \u2013 retrospectively expressed doubts as to whether Whitlam could have won if Gorton had returned to the prime ministership. [[Rupert Murdoch]], whose newspapers endorsed the Labor Party, stated in 2000 that \"we would most certainly have supported the re-election of a Gorton Government in 1972. And he would have won!\".<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 365.</ref>\n\nMcMahon resigned as Liberal leader a few weeks after the 1972 election. Gorton was one of five candidates who stood [[1972 Liberal Party of Australia leadership election|the resulting leadership ballot]], but polled only the fourth-highest total as [[Billy Snedden]] won a narrow victory over [[Nigel Bowen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110626409|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=21 December 1972|title=Snedden faces his first problems}}</ref> Snedden subsequently appointed him to the opposition frontbench as spokesman for urban and regional development, the environment, and conservation.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=30 January 1973|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110704896|title=Snedden names 'Shadow' team}}</ref> Soon after being sworn in as prime minister, Whitlam responded to a congratulatory letter from Gorton by promising to \"advance some of the causes which you were the first Australian Prime Minister to identify\". Over the following years, several failed initiatives from Gorton's prime ministership were passed into law by the [[Whitlam Government]]. This included the establishment of the [[Australian Film, Television and Radio School]] and the assertion of sovereignty over the territorial seabed and continental shelf.<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 366\u2013367.</ref>\n\n===Social liberalism===\nEarly in 1973, Gorton stated his public support of \"abortion on request, under certain conditions\"; he was opposed to \"compulsory pregnancy\". He nonetheless voted against [[David McKenzie (Victorian politician)|David McKenzie]] and [[Tony Lamb]]'s private member's bill to legalise abortion in the Australian Capital Territory, as he believed it did not provide clear enough guidelines for medical practitioners. He preferred the conditions of the [[Menhennitt ruling]].<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 367\u2013368.</ref> Gorton was also a supporter of no-fault divorce. During the debate over what became the ''[[Family Law Act 1975]]'', he [[cross the floor|crossed the floor]] to oppose a Coalition amendment which he thought complicated the requirements for divorce through separation.<ref name=p377>Hancock (2002), p. 377.</ref>\n\nIn October 1973, Gorton introduced a motion in the House of Representatives calling for the [[LGBT rights in Australia|decriminalisation of homosexuality]], co-sponsored by Labor's [[Moss Cass]]. It was modelled on the recommendations of the UK's [[Wolfenden report]]. While noting his personal objections to homosexuality, Gorton stated that most gay people \"hurt no one, harm no one and yet have this hanging over them\". He dismissed arguments that decriminalisation would violate \"God's law\", noting that many religious leaders were in favour of a change, and stated that the existing law had led to \"[[Gay bashing|bashing]]\", blackmail, and suicides. The motion passed by 24 votes, with all parties receiving a [[conscience vote]]. However, it was of no legal effect as homosexuality law was the province of state laws and territory ordinances.<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 368\u2013369.</ref><ref>[http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/genpdf/hansard80/hansardr80/1973-10-18/0029/hansard_frag.pdf;fileType=application%2Fpdf HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES HOMOSEXUALITY SPEECH], Hansard, 18 October 1973.</ref>\n\n===Resignation from the Liberal Party===\nGorton was re-elected at the [[1974 Australian federal election|1974 election]] with an increased majority.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 371.</ref> He was dropped from shadow cabinet after the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/110783471|title=Old line-up changed|work=[[The Canberra Times]]|date=15 June 1974}}</ref> In November 1974, following an unsuccessful attempt to install [[Malcolm Fraser]] as Liberal leader, he condemned those involved and stated they had caused \"irreparable damage\" to the party.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 374.</ref> On 3 March 1975, as leadership tensions continued to build, Gorton announced that he would not recontest his seat in parliament at the next election, citing his unwillingness to be a perpetual backbencher. He also stated: \"If Fraser got in, it would be a disaster. He is extreme right-wing. The Liberal Party can't be a right-leaning affair.\"<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 376.</ref> When Fraser won [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, 1975|a leadership spill]] on 21 March, Gorton reportedly stormed out of the meeting and slammed the door behind him.<ref name=p377/>\n\nOn 23 May 1975, Gorton announced his resignation from the Liberal Party and his intention to be an independent candidate for one of the new [[Australian Capital Territory]] (ACT) Senate seats. He hoped to join [[Steele Hall]] on the [[crossbench]] and secure the [[Balance of power (parliament)|balance of power]].<ref name=p377/> Opinion polling shortly after his announcement showed him winning 55 percent of the primary vote. His candidacy received endorsements from the small local branches of the [[Liberal Movement (Australia)|Liberal Movement]] and the [[Australia Party]].<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 379.</ref> Gough Whitlam was dismissed as prime minister on 11 November, sparking [[1975 Australian federal election|an early election]] on 13 December. During [[1975 Australian constitutional crisis|the preceding constitutional crisis]], Gorton had denounced Fraser's actions in blocking [[Supply (political science)|supply]] in the Senate.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 380.</ref> In the election, he polled 11.9 percent of the ACT Senate vote running on a two-man ticket with [[Harold Hird]]. It was the second-highest percentage for an independent candidate nation-wide, after [[Brian Harradine]]'s 12.8 percent in Tasmania, but nowhere near enough to win election. He had campaigned mainly on local issues, which obscured his candidacy somewhat in an election that was a virtual referendum on the Whitlam Government.<ref>Hancock (2002), p. 381.</ref>\n\n==Retirement and death==\n[[File:Grave_of_John_Gorton,_Melbourne_General_Cemetery.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Grave of Sir John within the 'Prime Ministers Garden' at [[Melbourne General Cemetery]]]]\nGorton retired to [[Canberra]], where he largely kept out of the political limelight. However, in March 1983, he congratulated [[Bob Hawke]] \"for rolling that bastard Fraser\" at [[1983 Australian federal election|that year's election]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Macinnis|first=Peter|title=The Big Book of Australian History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfGLAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=National Library Australia|isbn=978-0-642-27832-6|page=[https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=VfGLAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA221 221]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, Gorton was recruited to record a series of three-minute radio broadcasts on current affairs, titled \"Sir John Gorton's viewpoints\". He wrote and recorded around 400 segments over the following four years, which were syndicated and broadcast by over 80 radio stations around the country. His broadcasts covered a wide range of issues \u2013 he supported the decriminalisation of marijuana and prostitution, called on Australians to welcome [[Vietnamese boat people]], opposed the creation of [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]], denounced \"the cacophony known as modern music\", opposed Aboriginal land rights, supported uranium mining, and opposed [[Republicanism in Australia|republicanism]]. He frequently criticised the [[Fraser Government]], but grudgingly admired Fraser's ability to get his way as prime minister.<ref>Hancock (2002), pp. 384\u2013389.</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, Gorton quietly rejoined the Liberal Party; [[John Hewson]] credited himself with \"returning Gorton to the fold.\"<ref>ABC TV \"Midday Report\", Interview w. J Hewson, 26 May 2010</ref> In 1993, Gorton was invited to open the Liberal Party's campaign headquarters for the [[1993 Australian federal election|1993 election]]. He endorsed Hewson's [[Fightback! (policy)|Fightback!]] package.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/126976611|title=Gorton returns, hankering for change|date=17 February 1993|work=[[The Canberra Times]]}}</ref> In his old age he was rehabilitated by the Liberals; his 90th birthday party was attended by Prime Minister [[John Howard]] who said at the event: \"He (Gorton) was a person who above everything else was first, second and last an Australian.\" Although he was back within Liberal circles, he never forgave Fraser; as late as 2002 he told his biographer Ian Hancock that he still could not tolerate being in the same room as Fraser.<ref>Cameron Stewart, ''Buried alive'', Weekend Australian, 16\u201317 March 2002</ref>\n\nGorton died at Sydney's [[St Vincent's Hospital, Sydney|St Vincent's Hospital]] at the age of 90 in May 2002.<ref>{{cite news|last=Murphy|first=Damien|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/20/1021801645667.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|title=Larrikin PM who sacked himself dies aged 90|date=20 May 2002|accessdate=14 February 2016}}</ref> A [[State funeral]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/international/2002-05-20/state-funeral-for-sir-john-gorton/620960|work=ABC Radio|title=State funeral for Sir John Gorton|date=20 May 2002|accessdate=14 February 2016}}</ref> and memorial service was held on 30 May at [[St Andrew's Cathedral, Sydney|St Andrews' Cathedral]] where extremely critical remarks of Fraser, who was in attendance with wife [[Tamie Fraser|Tamie]], were delivered during the eulogy by Gorton's former Attorney-General [[Tom Hughes (Australian politician)|Tom Hughes]]. Current and former Prime Ministers Howard, [[Gough Whitlam]] and [[Bob Hawke]] were also in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/31/1022569833464.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|title=Hughes's wintry blast for the undertaker PM|date=1 June 2002|accessdate=14 February 2016}}</ref> Gorton was cremated after a private service and his ashes interred within the 'Prime Ministers Garden' at [[Melbourne General Cemetery]].\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriages===\n[[File:Gortonsearly50's.jpg|thumb|left|John and [[Bettina Gorton]] c. 1968]]\nDuring a holiday in Spain while still an undergraduate, Gorton met [[Bettina Gorton|Bettina Brown]] of [[Bangor, Maine]], United States. She was a language student at the [[Sorbonne]]. This meeting came about through Gorton's friend from Oxford, Arthur Brown, who was Bettina's brother. In 1935, Gorton and Bettina Brown were married in Oxford. After his studies were finished, they settled in Australia, taking over his father's orchard, \"Mystic Park\", at [[Lake Kangaroo, Victoria|Lake Kangaroo]] near [[Kerang]], Victoria. They had three children: Joanna, Michael and Robin. Gorton's first wife died of cancer in 1983. In 1993, he remarried to Nancy Home (n\u00e9e Elliott) a long-time acquaintance.<ref name=naabg>{{cite web|url=http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/spouse.aspx|publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]]|title=Bettina Gorton|accessdate=24 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315145301/http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/spouse.aspx|archive-date=15 March 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Religious beliefs===\nGorton was a nominal Christian at least in the early part of his life, but was not a churchgoer. Some sources have identified him as agnostic or even atheist. He attended Anglican schools, and was influenced by the [[Christian socialist]] views of [[James Ralph Darling]], his headmaster at [[Geelong Grammar]].<ref>Williams, Roy (2013). ''In God They Trust?'', Bible Society Australia, p. 149.</ref> In a 1948 speech, Gorton said that \"the story of Christianity is the most tremendous in the history of the world\".<ref>Williams: 151.</ref> However, in the lead-up to the [[1999 Australian republic referendum|1999 referendum]] he publicly opposed mentioning God in the preamble. According to his biographer Ian Hancock: \"Gorton may not have been a believing, let alone a practising, Christian, and when he spoke of religion of 'the soul' he did not have a particular faith in mind. Rather, his religion was founded upon the injunction in the [[Book of Deuteronomy]]: 'Man doth not live by bread only'.\"<ref>Hancock: 107</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:John Gorton bust.jpg|thumb|Bust of John Gorton by sculptor Victor Greenhalgh located in the [[Prime Ministers Avenue]] in the Ballarat Botanical Gardens]]\nGorton was appointed a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] in 1968, a [[Order of the Companions of Honour|Companion of Honour]] in 1971,<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1065982&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526212251/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1065982&search_type=quick&showInd=true |date=26 May 2011 }} \u2013 Companion of Honour</ref> a Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] in 1977<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1073778&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526212331/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1073778&search_type=quick&showInd=true |date=26 May 2011 }} \u2013 Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George</ref> and a Companion of the [[Order of Australia]] in 1988.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=884482&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526212339/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=884482&search_type=quick&showInd=true |date=26 May 2011 }} \u2013 Companion of the Order of Australia</ref> He was awarded the [[Centenary Medal]] in 2001.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1125728&search_type=quick&showInd=true It's an Honour] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526212354/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1125728&search_type=quick&showInd=true |date=26 May 2011 }} \u2013 Centenary Medal</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[First Gorton Ministry]]\n*[[Second Gorton Ministry]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|first=Ian|last=Hancock|year=2002|title=John Gorton: He Did It His Way|publisher=Hodder|isbn=0-7336-1439-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Gerard|last=Henderson|authorlink=Gerard Henderson|year=2000|chapter=Sir John Grey Gorton|title=Australian Prime Ministers|editor=[[Michelle Grattan]]|publisher=New Holland|isbn=1-86436-756-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Colin|last=Hughes|authorlink=Colin Hughes|year=1976|title=Mr Prime Minister: Australian Prime Ministers 1901\u20131972|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-550471-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Alan|last=Reid|authorlink=Alan Reid (journalist)|year=1969|title=The Power Struggle|url=https://archive.org/details/powerstruggle0000reid|url-access=registration|publisher=Shakespeare Head Press|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Alan|last=Reid|authorlink=Alan Reid (journalist)|year=1971|title=The Gorton Experiment|publisher=Shakespeare Head Press|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Alan|last=Trengove|year=1969|title=John Grey Gorton: An Informal Biography|publisher=Cassell|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John Gorton}}\n*{{cite web|title=John Gorton |url=http://primeministers.naa.gov.au/primeministers/gorton/|work= Australia's Prime Ministers |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |accessdate=29 June 2010 }}\n*{{cite web|title=Prime Ministers of Australia, John Gorton |publisher=[[National Museum of Australia]]|url=http://www.nma.gov.au/primeministers/john_gorton |accessdate=29 June 2010 }}\n*[http://colsearch.nfsa.afc.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=yes;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=Number%3A350424;querytype=;rec=0;resCount=10 John Gorton at the National Film and Sound Archive]{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Harold Holt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Division of Higgins|Member for Higgins]]|years=1968\u20131975}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Roger Shipton]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles Davidson (politician)|Charles Davidson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for the Navy]]|years=1958\u20131963}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Forbes (Australian politician)|Jim Forbes]]}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Gordon Freeth]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Housing (Australia)|Minister for Works]]|years=1963\u20131967}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bert Kelly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Home Affairs (Australia)|Minister for the Interior]]|years=1963\u20131964}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Doug Anthony]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Robert Menzies]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Innovation, Industry, Science and Research (Australia)|Minister in charge of the Commonwealth<br />Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation]]|years=1962\u20131963}}\n{{s-non|reason=Absorbed into next}}\n{{s-new|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Minister in charge of Commonwealth Activities<br />in [[Minister for Education (Australia)|Education]] and [[Minister for Innovation, Industry, Science and Research (Australia)|Research]]|years=1963\u20131966}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Malcolm Fraser]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Minister for [[Minister for Education (Australia)|Education]] and [[Minister for Innovation, Industry, Science and Research (Australia)|Science]]|years=1966\u20131968}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John McEwen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Australia]]|years=1968\u20131971}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William McMahon]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Malcolm Fraser]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Defence (Australia)|Minister for Defence]]|years=1971}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Fairbairn (politician)|David Fairbairn]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Harold Holt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Party of Australia|Leader of the Liberal Party of Australia]]|years=1968\u20131971}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William McMahon]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William McMahon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Liberal Party of Australia#Liberal federal deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of the Liberal Party of Australia]]|years=1971}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Billy Snedden]]}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Denham Henty]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=Leader of the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] in the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] | years=1967\u20131968}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Ken Anderson (Australian politician)|Ken Anderson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Australia}}\n{{Liberal Party of Australia}}\n{{Leaders of the Liberal Party of Australia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gorton, John}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of Australia]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for Victoria]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Higgins]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Australian agnostics]]\n[[Category:Australian World War II pilots]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Geelong Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Australian politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Australian Members of the Order of the Companions of Honour]]\n[[Category:Australian members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sydney Church of England Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Australian Freemasons]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Liberal Party of Australia]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Australian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of German descent]]\n", "name_user": "194.223.32.152", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Gorton"}
{"title_page": "Antiquarian Horological Society", "text_new": "\n\nThe '''Antiquarian Horological Society''', abbreviated to '''AHS''', is the [[United Kingdom|UK]]-based learned society for scholars and enthusiasts of [[horology]]. Its administrative office is at 4 Lovat Lane, a [[listed building]] close to the [[Monument_to_the_Great_Fire_of_London|Monument]], in the [[City of London]]. In early 2016, the Society appointed [[Patricia Fara|Dr Patricia Fara of Clare College, Cambridge]] as its new president, following the untimely death of its previous president [[Professor Lisa Jardine]]. The Chairman is Dr James Nye.\n\nThe Society was founded in 1953.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} It unites collectors, scholars and museum professionals interested in the historical aspects of [[horology]] &ndash; the study of the art, science, social history and technology of timekeepers, such as [[clocks]] and [[watches]].\n\nThe society is a [[Charitable organization|registered charity]] under English law.<ref>{{EW charity|260925|Antiquarian Horological Society}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe principal meetings of the Society are held periodically, primarily in [[London]]. Meetings may also be multi-day seminars, held in a number of locations such as Oxford. The Society hosts a London Lecture Series, which from January 2019 will be held at [[St Mary-at-Hill]], a [[Christopher Wren|Wren]] church opposite the Society's headquarters in Lovat Lane.  The annual general meeting is usually held at the [[National Maritime Museum]] and involves a one-day seminar. Once a year the organization usually organizes an international study tour, travelling to a foreign locale to study historic horological artefacts.\n\nBesides the main body that meets in London, there also are numerous Sections, most of them regional groups of members spread throughout the United Kingdom, plus five international sections (Ireland, USA, Canada, Netherlands) and three special interest sections with interests in [[turret clocks]],{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}} [[wristwatches]] and electrical horology. Sections may hold their own meetings and in some cases publish members' newsletters or organize horological study tours. The usual focus is on the presentation of papers on horological subjects. Some meetings involve visits to museums, restoration workshops or private collections.\n\n==Library==\nThe Society maintains an horological library, which is functionally integrated with the library of the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]] at [[Guildhall, London]].\n\n==Publications==\n''Antiquarian Horology & the Proceedings of the Antiquarian Horological Society'', generally known as ''[http://www.ahsoc.org/publications/the-journal/ Antiquarian Horology]'', is the Society's quarterly [[academic journal]], which is peer-reviewed and available to members, and to the public in a variety of public libraries.\n\nThe Society also publishes books on horological subjects, which are available to the public.\n\n== Affiliated organisations ==\nIn 2012, the AHS formally affiliated with the [[Royal Astronomical Society]].\nIn 2014, the AHS formally affiliated with the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]].\nIn 2016, the AHS formally affiliated with the [http://www.walesclocks.org.uk/ Wales and Marches Horological Society]\n==Sister organisations==\nIts main sister organizations in other countries pursuing similar goals are:\n\n* ''Association Fran\u00e7aise des Amateurs d'Horlogerie Ancienne'' - AFAHA (France)\n* ''[[Chronometrophilia]] (Switzerland)\n* ''[[Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Chronometrie]]'' - DGC (Germany)\n* ''HORA Associazione Italiana Cultori di Orologeria Antica'' (Italy)\n* ''[[National Association of Watch and Clock Collectors]]'' - NAWCC (United States of America)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |last=Beeson |first=C.F.C. |authorlink=Cyril Beeson |editor-last=Simcock |editor-first=A.V |year=1989 |origyear=1962 |edition=3rd |title=Clockmaking in Oxfordshire 1400\u20131850 |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Museum of the History of Science, Oxford|Museum of the History of Science]] |isbn=0 903364 06 9 |pages=2, 3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ahsoc.org/ Antiquarian Horological Society website]\n*[http://www.grettonbook.com The Gretton Project]: Research endeavour and book (''THROUGH THE GOLDEN AGE \u2013 Charles Gretton \u2013 Watch and Clockmaking'', published 2016) about renowned clockmaker and watchmaker [[Charles Gretton]] (1648\u20131731), Master of the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]] in 1700. The book contains a substantial historical introduction as well as historical appendices that provide details about clockmaking and watchmaking in London in the late 17th and early 18th centuries.\n\n[[Category:Horological organizations]]\n[[Category:Charities based in England]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1953]]\n[[Category:City of London]]\n", "text_old": "\n\nThe '''Antiquarian Horological Society''', abbreviated to '''AHS''', is the [[United Kingdom|UK]]-based learned society for scholars and enthusiasts of [[horology]]. Its administrative office is at 4 Lovat Lane, a [[listed building]] close to the [[Monument_to_the_Great_Fire_of_London|Monument]], in the [[City of London]]. In early 2016, the Society appointed [[Patricia Fara|Dr Patricia Fara of Clare College, Cambridge]] as its new president, following the untimely death of its previous president [[Professor Lisa Jardine]]. The Chairman is Dr James Nye.\n\nThe Society was founded in 1953.{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=2}} It unites collectors, scholars and museum professionals interested in the historical aspects of [[horology]] &ndash; the study of the art, science, social history and technology of timekeepers, such as [[clocks]] and [[watches]].\n\nThe society is a [[Charitable organization|registered charity]] under English law.<ref>{{EW charity|260925|Antiquarian Horological Society}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\nThe principal meetings of the Society are held periodically, primarily in [[London]]. Meetings may also be multi-day seminars, held in a number of locations such as Oxford. The Society hosts a London Lecture Series, which from January 2019 will be held at [[St Mary-at-Hill]], a [[Christopher Wren|Wren]] church opposite the Society's headquarters in Lovat Lane.  The annual general meeting is usually held at the [[National Maritime Museum]] and involves a one-day seminar. Once a year the organization usually organizes an international study tour, travelling to a foreign locale to study historic horological artefacts.\n\nBesides the main body that meets in London, there also are numerous Sections, most of them regional groups of members spread throughout the United Kingdom, plus five international sections (Ireland, USA, Canada, Netherlands) and three special interest sections with interests in [[turret clocks]],{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=3}} [[wristwatches]] and electrical horology. Sections may hold their own meetings and in some cases publish members' newsletters or organize horological study tours. The usual focus is on the presentation of papers on horological subjects. Some meetings involve visits to museums, restoration workshops or private collections.\n\n==Library==\nThe Society maintains an horological library, which is functionally integrated with the library of the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]] at [[Guildhall, London]].\n\n==Publications==\n''Antiquarian Horology & the Proceedings of the Antiquarian Horological Society'', generally known as ''[http://www.ahsoc.org/publications/the-journal/ Antiquarian Horology]'', is the Society's quarterly [[academic journal]], which is peer-reviewed and available to members, and to the public in a variety of public libraries.\n\nThe Society also publishes books on horological subjects, which are available to the public.\n\n== Affiliated organisations ==\nIn 2012, the AHS formally affiliated with the [[Royal Astronomical Society]].\nIn 2014, the AHS formally affiliated with the [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]].\nIn 2016, the AHS formally affiliated with the [http://www.walesclocks.org.uk/ Wales and Marches Horological Society]\n==Sister organisations==\nIts main sister organizations in other countries pursuing similar goals are:\n\n* ''Association Fran\u00e7aise des Amateurs d'Horlogerie Ancienne'' - AFAHA (France)\n* ''[[Chronometrophilia]] (Switzerland)\n* ''[[Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Chronometrie]]'' - DGC (Germany)\n* ''HORA Associazione Italiana Cultori di Orologeria Antica'' (Italy)\n* ''[[National Association of Watch and Clock Collectors]]'' - NAWCC (United States of America)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |last=Beeson |first=C.F.C. |authorlink=Cyril Beeson |editor-last=Simcock |editor-first=A.V |year=1989 |origyear=1962 |edition=3rd |title=Clockmaking in Oxfordshire 1400\u20131850 |location=Oxford |publisher=[[Museum of the History of Science, Oxford|Museum of the History of Science]] |isbn=0 903364 06 9 |pages=2, 3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ahsoc.org/ Antiquarian Horological Society website]\n\n[[Category:Horological organizations]]\n[[Category:Charities based in England]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1953]]\n[[Category:City of London]]\n", "name_user": "Dania.Sheldon", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(added five words to one external links description)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiquarian_Horological_Society"}
{"title_page": "Ben Haverkort", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Ben Haverkort\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1961|10|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Amsterdam]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| position       = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| years1         = \n| years2         = \n| years3         = \n| clubs1         = [[Telstar (football club)|Telstar]]\n| clubs2         = [[SC Cambuur]]\n| clubs3         = [[FC Emmen|Emmen]]\n| caps1          = \n| goals1         = \n| totalcaps      = \n| totalgoals     = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1  = \n| nationalcaps1  = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| medaltemplates = \n| module         = \n  {{Infobox football official | embed = yes | image =\n  | otheroccupation     = \n  | years1              = 1999\u20132011\n  | league1             = [[Eredivisie]]\n  | role1               = Referee\n  | internationalyears1 = 2002-2006\n  | confederation1      = [[FIFA]] listed\n  | internationalrole1  = Referee\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Ben Haverkort''' (born 27 October 1961) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] former [[association football|football]] player and referee. He played professional football in the Dutch second division before taking up refereeing, officiating in the Dutch first division and international football.\n\n==Playing career==\nAfter playing youth football for [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] Haverkort spent time at [[Eerste Divisie]] teams [[Telstar (football club)|Telstar]], [[SC Cambuur]] and [[FC Emmen|Emmen]].<ref name=\"ref-footballers\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/mar/31/have-former-footballers-become-referees |title=Have any former professional footballers become referees? |work=The Guardian |date=31 March 2010 |accessdate=29 September 2011 |author=Ashdown, John |author2=Bandini, Paolo}}</ref><ref name=\"worldreferee\">{{cite web |url=http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=896&linkType=referee&contextType=bio |title=Ben Haverkort |work=WorldReferee.com |date=13 October 2008 |accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraaf\">{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/fcgroningen/9930972/__Ben_Haverkort_bij_FC_Groningen__.html |title=Oud-arbiter Haverkort manager FC Groningen |work=De Telegraaf |date=31 May 2011 |accessdate=29 September 2011 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n==Refereeing career==\nAfter retiring from playing Haverkort took up refereeing in 1995 getting to national league level in 1999. Haverkort earned a place on the [[FIFA International Referees List]] beginning in 2002,<ref>Kutschera, Ambrosius. [http://www.rsssf.com/intldetails/2002e3.html \"International Matches 2002 - Europe, July-December\"]. ''[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]'', 2 February 2005. Retrieved on 23 May 2013.</ref> serving as a fourth official in [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualification|Euro 2004 qualifiers]]<ref>UEFA. [http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1579/match=69369/index.html \"Liechtenstein 0-3 Turkey\"]. 6 September 2003. Retrieved on 23 May 2013.</ref> and [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2006 World Cup qualifiers]].<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary=8071/matches/match=36766/report.html \"Match Report - France - Israel 0:0\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905055825/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary%3D8071/matches/match%3D36766/report.html |date=2011-09-05 }}. 4 September 2004. Retrieved on 23 May 2013.</ref>\n\nHaverkort retired from refereeing in 2011 to take up a management role for [[FC Groningen]].<ref name=\"telegraaf\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haverkort, Ben}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch football referees]]\n[[Category:Dutch footballers]]\n[[Category:SC Telstar players]]\n[[Category:SC Cambuur players]]\n[[Category:FC Emmen players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Ben Haverkort\n| image          = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1961|10|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Amsterdam]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| position       = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| years1         = \n| years2         = \n| years3         = \n| clubs1         = [[Telstar (football club)|Telstar]]\n| clubs2=[[SC Cambuur]]\n| clubs3=[[FC Emmen|Emmen]]\n| caps1          = \n| goals1         = \n| totalcaps      = \n| totalgoals     = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1  = \n| nationalcaps1  = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}{{Infobox football official\n| name                = Ben Haverkort\n \n| fullname            = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1961|10|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          = <!-- Use {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} if dead (death date followed by birth date) -->\n| death_place         = \n| otheroccupation     = \n| years1              = 1999\u20132011\n| league1             = [[Eredivisie]]\n| role1               = Referee\n| internationalyears1 = 2002-2006\n| confederation1      = [[FIFA]] listed\n| internationalrole1  = Referee\n}}'''Ben Haverkort''' (born 27 October 1961) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] former [[association football|football]] player and referee. He played professional football in the Dutch second division before taking up refereeing, officiating in the Dutch first division and international football.\n\n==Playing career==\nAfter playing youth football for [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] Haverkort spent time at [[Eerste Divisie]] teams [[Telstar (football club)|Telstar]], [[SC Cambuur]] and [[FC Emmen|Emmen]].<ref name=\"ref-footballers\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/mar/31/have-former-footballers-become-referees | title=Have any former professional footballers become referees? | work=The Guardian | date=31 March 2010 | accessdate=29 September 2011 | author=Ashdown, John |author2=Bandini, Paolo}}</ref><ref name=\"worldreferee\">{{cite web | url=http://worldreferee.com/site/copy.php?linkID=896&linkType=referee&contextType=bio | title=Ben Haverkort | work=WorldReferee.com | date=13 October 2008 | accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraaf\">{{cite news | url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/fcgroningen/9930972/__Ben_Haverkort_bij_FC_Groningen__.html | title=Oud-arbiter Haverkort manager FC Groningen | work=De Telegraaf | date=31 May 2011 | accessdate=29 September 2011 | language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n==Refereeing career==\nAfter retiring from playing Haverkort took up refereeing in 1995 getting to national league level in 1999. Haverkort earned a place on the [[FIFA International Referees List]] beginning in 2002,<ref>Kutschera, Ambrosius. [http://www.rsssf.com/intldetails/2002e3.html \"International Matches 2002 - Europe, July-December\"]. ''[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]'', 2 February 2005. Retrieved on 23 May 2013.</ref> serving as a fourth official in [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualification|Euro 2004 qualifiers]]<ref>UEFA. [http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/matches/round=1579/match=69369/index.html \"Liechtenstein 0-3 Turkey\"]. 6 September 2003. Retrieved on 23 May 2013.</ref> and [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2006 World Cup qualifiers]].<ref>FIFA. [https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary=8071/matches/match=36766/report.html \"Match Report - France - Israel 0:0\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905055825/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary%3D8071/matches/match%3D36766/report.html |date=2011-09-05 }}. 4 September 2004. Retrieved on 23 May 2013.</ref>\n\nHaverkort retired from refereeing in 2011 to take up a management role for [[FC Groningen]].<ref name=\"telegraaf\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haverkort, Ben}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch football referees]]\n[[Category:Dutch footballers]]\n[[Category:SC Telstar players]]\n[[Category:SC Cambuur players]]\n[[Category:FC Emmen players]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "merge infoboxes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Haverkort"}
